{"title_page": "Child cannibalism", "text_new": "[[File:Saturn devouring his Son by Giambattista Tiepolo.jpg|thumb|200px|''Saturn Devouring His Son'' by [[Giambattista Tiepolo]], 1745.]]\n'''Child cannibalism''' or '''fetal cannibalism''' is the [[Human cannibalism|act of eating]] a [[child]] or [[fetus]].\n\n==Ritual practice accusations==\n{{Main|Blood libel|Ritual abuse||Page 4 = }}\n\n==Modern cases==\n\n=== China ===\nEww China eats babies!!!!!\n\nControversy has been sparked when the performance artist [[Zhu Yu (artist)|Zhu Yu]] claimed that he prepared, cooked and ate real human bodies, including fetuses,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Baby-eating photos are part of Chinese artist's performance|url = http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/local/archives/2001/03/23/78704|work = Taipei Times|date=23 March 2001|accessdate = 2015-11-21}}</ref> as an artistic [[performance]].<ref>Rojas, Carlos. (2002). [http://www3.iath.virginia.edu/pmc/text-only/issue.502/12.3rojas.txt \"Cannibalism and the Chinese Body Politic: Hermeneutics and Violence in Cross-Cultural Perception\"]. ''[[Postmodern Culture]]'', 12 (3). Retrieved July 8, 2006.</ref> The performance was called ''Eating People'' he claimed it was to protest against cannibalism.<ref name=\"urbanlegends.about.com\">{{cite web | url = http://urbanlegends.about.com/od/horrors/a/eating_babies.htm | title = Do They Eat Babies in China? | last = Emery | first = David | accessdate = 2009-01-09 | publisher = [[About.com]]}}</ref> It was intended as \"[[shock art]]\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mRmppyhh9W0C&pg=PA163&lpg=PA163&dq=chinese+artist+shock+babies&source=bl&ots=2sZELAVEhy&sig=e7JxKo1AdcKcueBCajIS8QIX6B0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CFsQ6AEwDGoVChMI2ofesOn-xwIVhTw-Ch2gogjH#v=onepage&q=chinese%20artist%20shock%20babies&f=false Berghuis 2006], p. 163.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2rLBvrlKI7QC&pg=PA729&lpg=PA729&dq=chinese+artist+shock+babies&source=bl&ots=zzVfKkLZrA&sig=1Kx283Zg3cWvgiptoLuncF0C4So&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CFgQ6AEwC2oVChMI2ofesOn-xwIVhTw-Ch2gogjH#v=onepage&q=chinese%20artist%20shock%20babies&f=false Davis 2009], p. 729.</ref> The [[Ministry of Culture of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Ministry of Culture]] cited a menace to social order and the spiritual health of the Chinese people, banned exhibitions involving culture, animal abuse, corpses, and overt violence and sexuality<ref>New China, new art; Munich ; New York : Prestel, c2008.</ref> and Zhu Yu was prosecuted for his deeds.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u5f55\u50cf\u4f5c\u54c1\u300a\u6731\u6631\u4fae\u8fb1\u5c38\u4f53\u6848\u300b\u6587\u5b57\u8bb0\u5f55 |url=http://arts.tom.com/Archive/1003/2003/7/8-46320.html |date=2004-06-04 |accessdate=2015-11-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040604083027/http://arts.tom.com/Archive/1003/2003/7/8-46320.html |archivedate=June 4, 2004 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = \u6731\u6631_\u4e92\u52a8\u767e\u79d1|url = http://www.baike.com/wiki/%25E6%259C%25B1%25E6%2598%25B1&prd=citiaorebang|website = www.baike.com|accessdate = 2015-11-21}}</ref>  \n\nSnopes and other urban legend sites have said the \"fetus\" used by Zhu Yu was most likely constructed from a duck's body and a doll head.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/fetus-feast/|title=FACT CHECK: Are Human Fetuses 'Taiwan's Hottest Dish'?|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hoaxorfact.com/crime/chinese-eat-baby-soup-for-sex-facts-analysis.html|title=Chinese Eat Baby Soup for Sex \u2013 Facts Analysis|date=2014-07-10|website=Hoax Or Fact|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref><ref name=\"urbanlegends.about.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liveabout.com/do-they-eat-babies-in-china-3299484|title=No, People in China Don't Eat Babies|last=expert|first=David Emery David Emery is an internet folklore|last2=Legends|first2=Debunker of Urban|website=LiveAbout|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27|last3=hoaxes|last4=Snopes.com|first4=popular misconceptions He currently writes for}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/flesh-potted/|title=Cannibal Restaurant Hoax|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.hiddenharmonies.org/2012/05/08/so-they-eat-babies/|title=Hidden Harmonies China Blog \u00bb So they eat babies?|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pmc.iath.virginia.edu/issue.502/12.3rojas.html|title=Cannibalism and the Chinese Body Politic: Hermeneutics and Violence in Cross-Cultural Perception|website=pmc.iath.virginia.edu|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref><ref>http://pmc.iath.virginia.edu/text-only/issue.502/12.3rojas.txt</ref> Other images from another art exhibit were falsely circulated along with Zhu Yu's photographs and claimed to be evidence of fetus soup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wereblog.com/zhu-yu-shanghai-art-festival-man-eating-fetus|title=The Truth Behind The Viral Photo Of A Chinese Man Eating Fetus|last=Chino|date=2015-04-30|website=Wereblog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n\nCritics see the propagation of these rumors as a form of [[blood libel]], or accusing one's enemy of eating children, and accuse countries of using this as a political lever.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jesus21.com/poppydixon/sex/chinese_eating_fetuses.html|title=Eating Fetuses: The lurid Christian fantasy of godless Chinese eating \"unborn children.\"|last=Dixon|first=Poppy|date=October 2000|accessdate=12 December 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080313105007/http://www.jesus21.com/poppydixon/sex/chinese_eating_fetuses.html|archivedate=March 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Korea===\nCapsule pills filled with human baby flesh in the form of powder were seized by South Koreans from [[Koreans in China|ethnic Koreans living in China]], who had tried to smuggle them into South Korea and consume the capsules themselves or distribute them to other ethnic Korean citizens of China living in South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/chinese-made-infant-flesh-capsules-seized-korea/story?id=16296176|title=Chinese-Made Infant Flesh Capsules Seized in S. Korea|last=News|first=A. B. C.|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=7 May 2012 |title=Pills filled with powdered human baby flesh found by customs officials  |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/southkorea/9250438/Pills-filled-with-powdered-human-baby-flesh-found-by-customs-officials.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 7 May 2012|title=S Korea cracks down on 'human flesh capsules' |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia-pacific/2012/05/201257142432164324.html |newspaper=Al Jazeera |location= |access-date= }}</ref> Experts later suggested that the pills had actually been made of newborn placenta for the documented practice of [[human placentophagy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lifestyle.inquirer.net/54285/eating-placenta-an-age-old-practice-in-china/|title=Eating placenta, an age-old practice in China|date=2012-06-25|website=Inquirer Lifestyle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://placentabenefits.info/placenta-in-demand-creating-a-black-market-in-china/|title=Placenta in Demand, Creating a Black Market in China|date=2012-07-03|website=Placenta Benefits|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\n==Satire==\n[[Jonathan Swift]]'s 1729 satiric article \"[[A Modest Proposal|A Modest Proposal for Preventing the Children of Poor People in Ireland from Being a Burden to Their Parents or Country, and for Making Them Beneficial to the Public]]\" proposed the utilization of an economic system based on poor people selling their children to be eaten, claiming that this would benefit the economy, family values, and general happiness of Ireland. The target of Swift's satire is the rationalism of modern economics, and the growth of rationalistic modes of thinking at the expense of more traditional human values.\n\n==References in popular culture==\n*In [[Fruit Chan]]'s ''[[Dumplings (film)|Dumplings]]'', fetuses are consumed with the belief of their rejuvenating properties.\n*In the Taiwan ghost movie, ''[[The Heirloom]]'' (2005), infants who've died or been aborted are kept in jars and fed blood to raise 'young ghosts' (who grant the bloodletter powers).\n*Japanese rock band [[Dir en grey]]'s song \"Umbrella\" is about the act of child cannibalism.\n*In [[Cormac McCarthy]]'s novel ''[[The Road]]'', a father and son encounter a family that consumes a [[fetus]].\n*In the popular comedy ''[[Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me]]'', the character [[Fat Bastard (character)|Fat Bastard]] is known for his obsession with eating infants.\n*In an episode of ''[[South Park]]'' titled ''[[Krazy Kripples]]'', [[Christopher Reeve]] is shown eating [[fetus]]es in order to regain his mobility as well as to seemingly become stronger (in satirical reference to his acting roles as [[Superman]], his real-life [[paralysis]], and subsequent advocacy for fetal [[stem cell]] research).\n*In an episode of ''[[Robot Chicken]]'', \"Nutcracker Sweet\", the resurrected [[Walt Disney]] feeds exclusively on Cuban children. After watching coverage of the [[Elian Gonzales]] deportation case on the news, Disney sets out on a quest to devour the boy.\n*In [[Robert Kirkman]]'s ''[[The Walking Dead (comic book)|The Walking Dead]]'' and its [[The Walking Dead (TV series)|live-action adaptation]], a group of survivors who dubbed themselves \"the Hunters\" turned to eating their children to survive in the [[zombie]] [[apocalypse]], though not without clear remorse.\n*In \"[[Nanny McPhee|Nanny Mcphee]]\" the youngest child (who is a baby) in the  Brown family, Aggie, is supposedly cooked and fed to the other children in the family by Nanny McPhee. This, however, is not the case, as they soon find out Aggie is safe and what they were eating was in fact chicken.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Albert Fish]]\n*[[Human placentophagy]]\n*[[Child sacrifice]]\n*''[[Saturn Devouring His Son]]''\n* [[Traditional Chinese medicines derived from the human body]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.theseoultimes.com/ST/?url=/ST/db/read.php?idx=7333 Photos in South-Korean newspaper]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070929133846/http://www.asianews.it/view.php?l=en&art=5860 Italian Asian article]\n*[http://www.snopes.com/horrors/cannibal/fetus.htm Urban legends website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060523030156/http://6news.ljworld.com/section/capitolchats/story/168864 LJ News]\n\n[[Category:Cannibalism]]\n[[Category:Child murder]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Saturn devouring his Son by Giambattista Tiepolo.jpg|thumb|200px|''Saturn Devouring His Son'' by [[Giambattista Tiepolo]], 1745.]]\n'''Child cannibalism''' or '''fetal cannibalism''' is the [[Human cannibalism|act of eating]] a [[child]] or [[fetus]].\n\n==Ritual practice accusations==\n{{Main|Blood libel|Ritual abuse||Page 4 = }}\n\n==Modern cases==\n\n=== China ===\nControversy has been sparked when the performance artist [[Zhu Yu (artist)|Zhu Yu]] claimed that he prepared, cooked and ate real human bodies, including fetuses,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Baby-eating photos are part of Chinese artist's performance|url = http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/local/archives/2001/03/23/78704|work = Taipei Times|date=23 March 2001|accessdate = 2015-11-21}}</ref> as an artistic [[performance]].<ref>Rojas, Carlos. (2002). [http://www3.iath.virginia.edu/pmc/text-only/issue.502/12.3rojas.txt \"Cannibalism and the Chinese Body Politic: Hermeneutics and Violence in Cross-Cultural Perception\"]. ''[[Postmodern Culture]]'', 12 (3). Retrieved July 8, 2006.</ref> The performance was called ''Eating People'' he claimed it was to protest against cannibalism.<ref name=\"urbanlegends.about.com\">{{cite web | url = http://urbanlegends.about.com/od/horrors/a/eating_babies.htm | title = Do They Eat Babies in China? | last = Emery | first = David | accessdate = 2009-01-09 | publisher = [[About.com]]}}</ref> It was intended as \"[[shock art]]\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mRmppyhh9W0C&pg=PA163&lpg=PA163&dq=chinese+artist+shock+babies&source=bl&ots=2sZELAVEhy&sig=e7JxKo1AdcKcueBCajIS8QIX6B0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CFsQ6AEwDGoVChMI2ofesOn-xwIVhTw-Ch2gogjH#v=onepage&q=chinese%20artist%20shock%20babies&f=false Berghuis 2006], p. 163.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2rLBvrlKI7QC&pg=PA729&lpg=PA729&dq=chinese+artist+shock+babies&source=bl&ots=zzVfKkLZrA&sig=1Kx283Zg3cWvgiptoLuncF0C4So&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CFgQ6AEwC2oVChMI2ofesOn-xwIVhTw-Ch2gogjH#v=onepage&q=chinese%20artist%20shock%20babies&f=false Davis 2009], p. 729.</ref> The [[Ministry of Culture of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Ministry of Culture]] cited a menace to social order and the spiritual health of the Chinese people, banned exhibitions involving culture, animal abuse, corpses, and overt violence and sexuality<ref>New China, new art; Munich ; New York : Prestel, c2008.</ref> and Zhu Yu was prosecuted for his deeds.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u5f55\u50cf\u4f5c\u54c1\u300a\u6731\u6631\u4fae\u8fb1\u5c38\u4f53\u6848\u300b\u6587\u5b57\u8bb0\u5f55 |url=http://arts.tom.com/Archive/1003/2003/7/8-46320.html |date=2004-06-04 |accessdate=2015-11-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040604083027/http://arts.tom.com/Archive/1003/2003/7/8-46320.html |archivedate=June 4, 2004 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = \u6731\u6631_\u4e92\u52a8\u767e\u79d1|url = http://www.baike.com/wiki/%25E6%259C%25B1%25E6%2598%25B1&prd=citiaorebang|website = www.baike.com|accessdate = 2015-11-21}}</ref>  \n\nSnopes and other urban legend sites have said the \"fetus\" used by Zhu Yu was most likely constructed from a duck's body and a doll head.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/fetus-feast/|title=FACT CHECK: Are Human Fetuses 'Taiwan's Hottest Dish'?|