uses.html|title=Eating Fetuses: The lurid Christian fantasy of godless Chinese eating \"unborn children.\"|last=Dixon|first=Poppy|date=October 2000|accessdate=12 December 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080313105007/http://www.jesus21.com/poppydixon/sex/chinese_eating_fetuses.html|archivedate=March 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Korea===\nCapsule pills filled with human baby flesh in the form of powder were seized by South Koreans from [[Koreans in China|ethnic Koreans living in China]], who had tried to smuggle them into South Korea and consume the capsules themselves or distribute them to other ethnic Korean citizens of China living in South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/chinese-made-infant-flesh-capsules-seized-korea/story?id=16296176|title=Chinese-Made Infant Flesh Capsules Seized in S. Korea|last=News|first=A. B. C.|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=7 May 2012 |title=Pills filled with powdered human baby flesh found by customs officials  |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/southkorea/9250438/Pills-filled-with-powdered-human-baby-flesh-found-by-customs-officials.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 7 May 2012|title=S Korea cracks down on 'human flesh capsules' |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia-pacific/2012/05/201257142432164324.html |newspaper=Al Jazeera |location= |access-date= }}</ref> Experts later suggested that the pills had actually been made of newborn placenta for the documented practice of [[human placentophagy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lifestyle.inquirer.net/54285/eating-placenta-an-age-old-practice-in-china/|title=Eating placenta, an age-old practice in China|date=2012-06-25|website=Inquirer Lifestyle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://placentabenefits.info/placenta-in-demand-creating-a-black-market-in-china/|title=Placenta in Demand, Creating a Black Market in China|date=2012-07-03|website=Placenta Benefits|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\n==Satire==\n[[Jonathan Swift]]'s 1729 satiric article \"[[A Modest Proposal|A Modest Proposal for Preventing the Children of Poor People in Ireland from Being a Burden to Their Parents or Country, and for Making Them Beneficial to the Public]]\" proposed the utilization of an economic system based on poor people selling their children to be eaten, claiming that this would benefit the economy, family values, and general happiness of Ireland. The target of Swift's satire is the rationalism of modern economics, and the growth of rationalistic modes of thinking at the expense of more traditional human values.\n\n==References in popular culture==\n*In [[Fruit Chan]]'s ''[[Dumplings (film)|Dumplings]]'', fetuses are consumed with the belief of their rejuvenating properties.\n*In the Taiwan ghost movie, ''[[The Heirloom]]'' (2005), infants who've died or been aborted are kept in jars and fed blood to raise 'young ghosts' (who grant the bloodletter powers).\n*Japanese rock band [[Dir en grey]]'s song \"Umbrella\" is about the act of child cannibalism.\n*In [[Cormac McCarthy]]'s novel ''[[The Road]]'', a father and son encounter a family that consumes a [[fetus]].\n*In the popular comedy ''[[Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me]]'', the character [[Fat Bastard (character)|Fat Bastard]] is known for his obsession with eating infants.\n*In an episode of ''[[South Park]]'' titled ''[[Krazy Kripples]]'', [[Christopher Reeve]] is shown eating [[fetus]]es in order to regain his mobility as well as to seemingly become stronger (in satirical reference to his acting roles as [[Superman]], his real-life [[paralysis]], and subsequent advocacy for fetal [[stem cell]] research).\n*In an episode of ''[[Robot Chicken]]'', \"Nutcracker Sweet\", the resurrected [[Walt Disney]] feeds exclusively on Cuban children. After watching coverage of the [[Elian Gonzales]] deportation case on the news, Disney sets out on a quest to devour the boy.\n*In [[Robert Kirkman]]'s ''[[The Walking Dead (comic book)|The Walking Dead]]'' and its [[The Walking Dead (TV series)|live-action adaptation]], a group of survivors who dubbed themselves \"the Hunters\" turned to eating their children to survive in the [[zombie]] [[apocalypse]], though not without clear remorse.\n*In \"[[Nanny McPhee|Nanny Mcphee]]\" the youngest child (who is a baby) in the  Brown family, Aggie, is supposedly cooked and fed to the other children in the family by Nanny McPhee. This, however, is not the case, as they soon find out Aggie is safe and what they were eating was in fact chicken.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Albert Fish]]\n*[[Human placentophagy]]\n*[[Child sacrifice]]\n*''[[Saturn Devouring His Son]]''\n* [[Traditional Chinese medicines derived from the human body]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.theseoultimes.com/ST/?url=/ST/db/read.php?idx=7333 Photos in South-Korean newspaper]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070929133846/http://www.asianews.it/view.php?l=en&art=5860 Italian Asian article]\n*[http://www.snopes.com/horrors/cannibal/fetus.htm Urban legends website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060523030156/http://6news.ljworld.com/section/capitolchats/story/168864 LJ News]\n\n[[Category:Cannibalism]]\n[[Category:Child murder]]\n", "name_user": "184.14.120.93", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Child_cannibalism"}
{"title_page": "Roundell Palmer, 3rd Earl of Selborne", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = The Earl of Selborne\n|honorific-suffix = [[Order of the Companions of Honour|CH]] [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]\n|image =Lord Selbourne.jpg\n|office1 = [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Board of Trade]]\n|term_start1 = 1922\n|term_end1 = 1924\n|monarch1 = [[George V]]\n|predecessor1 = [[William Mitchell-Thomson, 1st Baron Selsdon|William Mitchell-Thomson]]\n|successor1 = [[A. V. Alexander, 1st Earl Alexander of Hillsborough|A. V. Alexander]]\n|office2 = [[Minister of Economic Warfare]]\n|term_start2 = 1942\n|term_end2 = 1945\n|predecessor2 = [[Hugh Dalton]]\n|successor2 = [[Simon Fraser, 15th Lord Lovat|Lord Lovat]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1887|4|15|df=y}}\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1971|9|3|1887|4|15|df=y}}\n}}\n\n'''Roundell Cecil Palmer, 3rd Earl of Selborne''', [[Order of the Companions of Honour|CH]], [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] (15 April 1887 \u2013 3 September 1971), known as \"Top Wolmer\" and styled '''Viscount Wolmer''' from 1895 to 1941, was a British administrator, intelligence officer and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician.\n\n==Background and education==\nBorn in the [[City of Westminster]], Wolmer was the eldest son of [[William Palmer, 2nd Earl of Selborne]] and his wife, the former [[Maud Palmer, Countess of Selborne|Lady Maud Cecil]], daughter of [[Robert Cecil, 3rd Marquess of Salisbury]]. He was educated at [[Winchester College]] and graduated from [[University College, Oxford]] in 1909. He was the cousin of [[Robert Gascoyne-Cecil, 5th Marquess of Salisbury]].\n\n==Political career==\nA few months later, at the [[December 1910 United Kingdom general election|December 1910 general election]] Lord Wolmer entered Parliament as Member of Parliament (MP) for the [[Newton (UK Parliament constituency)|Newton division of Lancashire]]. He was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to his uncle, the [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs]], [[Robert Cecil, 1st Viscount Cecil of Chelwood|Lord Robert Cecil]] in 1916 and Assistant Director of the War Trade Department from 1916 to 1918. At the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]], he did not stand in Newton (which was won by the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician, [[Robert Young (Lancashire politician)|Robert Young]]), but was elected to the newly formed constituency of [[Aldershot (UK Parliament constituency)|Aldershot]] that year. From 1922 to 1924, he was [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Board of Trade]] and [[Assistant Postmaster-General]] from 1924 to 1929.\n\nIn November 1940, Lord Wolmer resigned his seat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|Commons]], and was [[writ of acceleration|called up to the House of Lords]] in his father's [[Baron Selborne|barony of Selborne]] in January 1941.<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/35039/page/191 London Gazette, 10 January 1941]</ref> He was Director of Cement at the [[Ministry of Works (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Works]] from 1940 to 1942. In 1942, he inherited his father's earldom and his last political post was as [[Minister of Economic Warfare]] from 1942 to 1945. This put him in charge of the Special Operations Executive, which ran undercover operations of sabotage in Occupied Europe. As head of SOE it was his policy to back the Chetniks in Jugoslavia despite the numerous items of intelligence which suggested that they were in league with the Germans. He was responsible for a delay of 12 months in support being given to Tito's Partisans and when Fitzroy McLean was ordered to go to Cairo with a view to establishing contact with Tito he did everything he could to frustrate the mission.<ref>Special Operations Europe by Basil Davidson, Victor Gollancz Ltd, 1980</ref> He was made a member of the [[Order of the Companions of Honour]] after the war and in 1948 was Master of the [[Worshipful Company of Mercers]], then chairman of the [[National Provincial Bank]] from 1951 to 1953 and deputy chairman of [[Boots Group|Boots]] from 1951 to 1964.\n\n==Family==\nOn 9 June 1910, he married the Honourable Grace Ridley, third daughter of [[Matthew White Ridley, 1st Viscount Ridley]]. They had six surviving children:\n\n* Lady Anne Beatrice Mary (1911\u20132002), married the Reverend John Brewis.\n* William Matthew Palmer, Viscount Wolmer (1912\u20131942).\n* Lady Laura Mary (1915\u20131999), married [[Cyril Eastaugh]], [[Bishop of Peterborough]].\n* Hon. Robert Jocelyn (1919\u20131991), married Anne Palmer, 11th Baroness Lucas.\n* Lady Mary Sophia (1920\u20132001), Hon. Anthony Strachey, son of [[Maurice Towneley-O'Hagan, 3rd Baron O'Hagan]].\n* Hon. Edward Roundell (1926\u20131974), married Joanna Bacon (a daughter of [[Edmund Castell Bacon|Sir Edmund Bacon, Bt]]).\n\nLord Selborne's wife died in 1959 and on 3 March 1966, he married Valerie Bevan ''n\u00e9e'' de Thomkahaza, a daughter of a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] politician. His eldest son had also died on active service in 1942 and upon his own death in 1971 in [[Alton, Hampshire]] aged 84, was succeeded in his titles by his grandson, [[John Palmer, 4th Earl of Selborne|John]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* [http://www.burkes-peerage.net/ Burke's Peerage & Gentry]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | viscount-wolmer-1 | the Earl of Selborne }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Newton (UK Parliament constituency)|Newton]]\n | years  = [[December 1910 United Kingdom general election|Dec 1910]] \u2013 [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]\n | before = [[James Andrew Seddon|James Seddon]]\n | after  = [[Robert Young (Lancashire politician)|Robert Young]]\n}}\n{{s-new | constituency }}\n{{s-ttl | title = [