{"title_page": "Banksia borealis", "text_new": "{{Short description|Species of shrub in the genus ''Banksia''}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|image = \n|genus = Banksia\n|display_parents = 2\n|parent = Banksia ser. Dryandra\n|species = borealis\n|authority = ([[Alex George|A.S.George]]) [[Austin Mast|A.R.Mast]] & [[Kevin Thiele|K.R.Thiele]]<ref name=\"APC\">{{cite web |title=''Banksia borealis'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/205085|website=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"APC\" />\n|synonyms = ''Dryandra borealis'' <small>A.S.George</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Banksia borealis''''' is a species of sprawling shrub that is [[Endemism|endemic]] to Western Australia. It has leaves with sharply pointed lobes on each side, between thirty and fifty flowers in a gold-coloured spike and egg-shaped fruit. There are two subspecies occurring in two [[Disjunct distribution|disjunct]] areas.\n\n==Description==\n''Banksia borealis'' is a sprawling shrub that typically grows to a height of {{cvt|1|m}} and forms a [[lignotuber]], or a shrub to {{cvt|2.5|m}} that does not form a lignotuber. The stems have soft hairs held close to the surface. The leaves are broadly linear in outline, {{cvt|40-90|mm}} long and {{cvt|12-30|mm}} wide on a [[Petiole (botany)|petiole]] up to {{cvt|2|mm}} long, with between five and twelve sharply pointed lobes on each side. Between thirty and fifty flowers are borne in a spike on the end of short side branches, each flower with a hairy, golden [[perianth]] {{cvt|32-35|mm}} long, the [[Gynoecium#Pistils|pistil]] {{cvt|39-47|mm}} long. Flowering occurs from July to November and the fruit is a hairy, egg-shaped [[Follicle (fruit)|follicle]] {{cvt|8-13|mm}} long.<ref name=FloraBase>{{FloraBase|name=''Banksia borealis''|id=32626}}</ref><ref name=\"Nuytsia\">{{cite journal|last1=George|first1=Alex S.|title=New taxa and a new infrageneric classification in ''Dryandra'' R.Br.|journal=Nuytsia|date=1996|volume=10|issue=3|pages=343\u2013345}}</ref><ref name=\"CSIRO\">{{cite book |last1=George |first1=Alex S. |title=Flora of Australia |volume=17B |date=1999 |publisher=Australian Biological Resources Study, Canberra |location=Canberra |page=283 |url=https://www.environment.gov.au/system/files/pages/6d8c5c3b-8545-437e-b9b3-944ac95ee07a/files/flora-australia-17b-proteaceae-3-hakea-dryandra.pdf |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy and naming==\nThis banksia was first formally described in 1996 by [[Alex George]] in the journal ''[[Nuytsia (journal)|Nuytsia]]'' and given the name ''Dryandra borealis'' from specimens he collected in 1966, near the road between [[Kalbarri, Western Australia|Kalbarri]] and [[Ajana, Western Australia|Ajana]].<ref name=\"Nuytsia\" /><ref name=APNI1>{{cite web|title=''Dryandra borealis''|url= https://id.biodiversity.org.au/instance/apni/558984|publisher=APNI|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> In 2007, [[Austin Mast]] and [[Kevin Thiele]] transferred all the dryandras to the genus ''[[Banksia]]'' and this species became ''Banksia borealis''.<ref name=APNI>{{cite web|title=''Banksia borealis''|url= https://id.biodiversity.org.au/instance/apni/614236|publisher=APNI|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CSIRO2\">{{cite journal|last1=Mast|first1=Austin R.|last2=Thiele|first2=Kevin|title=The transfer of Dryandra R.Br. to Banksia L.f. (Proteaceae)|journal=Australian Systematic Botany|date=2013|volume=20|issue=1|pages=63\u201371|doi=10.1071/SB06016}}</ref> The [[Botanical name|specific epithet]] (''borealis'') is a Latin word meaning \"northern\"<ref name=\"Stearn\">{{cite book |author=[[William T. Stearn]] |title=Botanical Latin. History, grammar, syntax, terminology and vocabulary |date=1992 |publisher=Timber Press |location=Portland, Oregon |edition=4th|page=377}}</ref> referring to the distribution of this species, the most northerly of all the dryandras.<ref name=\"Nuytsia\" />\n\nIn the same journal, George described two subspecies of ''Dryandra borealis'', later moved to ''Banksia'' by Mast and Thiele, and the names are accepted by the [[Australian Plant Census]]:\n* [[Banksia borealis subsp. borealis |''Banksia borealis'' <small>A.S.George</small> subsp. ''borealis'']]<ref name=\"APC1\">{{cite web |title=''Banksia borealis'' subsp. ''borealis'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/205088|website=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> is a shrub with a lignotuber;\n* ''Banksia borealis'' subsp. ''elatior'' <small>A.S.George</small><ref name=\"APC2\">{{cite web |title=''Banksia borealis'' subsp. ''elatior'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/205087|website=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> lacks a lignotuber.<ref name=\"Nuytsia\" />\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n''Banksia borealis'' occurs in two disjunct areas of Western Australia. Subspecies ''borealis'' is relatively common and grows in [[Kwongan]] between Kalbarri, [[Northampton, Western Australia|Northampton]] and [[Yuna, Western Australia|Yuna]]. Subspecies ''elatior'' is only known from a few small populations near [[Three Springs, Western Australia|Three Springs]] where it grows in tall scrub and low woodland.<ref name=\"Nuytsia\" />\n\n==Conservation status==\nSubspecies ''borealis'' is classified as \"not threatened\" by the Western Australian Government [[Department of Parks and Wildlife (Western Australia)|Department of Parks and Wildlife]],<ref name=FloraBase1>{{FloraBase|name=''Banksia borealis'' subsp. ''borealis''|id=32627}}</ref> but subspecies ''elatior'' is classified as \"[[Declared Rare and Priority Flora List|Priority Three]]\"<ref name=FloraBase2>{{FloraBase|name=''Banksia borealis'' subsp. ''elatior''|id=32628}}</ref>  meaning that it is poorly known and known from only a few locations but is not under imminent threat.<ref name=codes>{{cite web|title=Conservation codes for Western Australian Flora and Fauna|url=https://www.dpaw.wa.gov.au/images/documents/plants-animals/threatened-species/Listings/Conservation%20code%20definitions.pdf|publisher=Government of Western Australia Department of Parks and Wildlife|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4856563}}\n\n[[Category:Banksia ser. Dryandra|borealis]]\n[[Category:Banksia taxa by scientific name|borealis]]\n[[Category:Endemic flora of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Eudicots of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1996]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Species of shrub in the genus ''Banksia''}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|image = \n|genus = Banksia\n|display_parents = 2\n|parent = Banksia ser. Dryandra\n|species = borealis\n|authority = ([[Alex George|A.S.George]]) [[Austin Mast|A.R.Mast]] & [[Kevin Thiele|K.R.Thiele]]<ref name=\"APC\">{{cite web |title=''Banksia borealis'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/205085|website=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"APC\" />\n|synonyms = ''Dryandra borealis'' <small>A.S.George</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Banksia borealis''''' is a species of sprawling shrub that is [[Endemism|endemic]] to Western Australia. It has leaves with sharply pointed lobes on each side, between thirty and fifty flowers in a gold-coloured spike and egg-shaped fruit. There are two subspecies occurring in two [[Disjunct distribution|disjunct]] areas.\n\n==Description==\n''Banksia borealis'' is a sprawling shrub that typically grows to a height of {{cvt|1|m}} and forms a [[lignotuber]], or a shrub to {{cvt|2.5|m}} that does not form a lignotuber. The stems have soft hairs held close to the surface. The leaves are broadly linear in outline, {{cvt|40-90|mm}} long and {{cvt|12-30|mm}} wide on a [[Petiole (botany)|petiole]] up to {{cvt|2|mm}} long, with between five and twelve sharply pointed lobes on each side. Between thirty and fifty flowers are borne in a spike on the end of short side branches, each flower with a hairy, golden [[perianth]] {{cvt|32-35|mm}} long, the [[Gynoecium#Pistils|pistil]] {{cvt|39-47|mm}} long. Flowering occurs from July to November and the fruit is a hairy, egg-shaped [[Follicle (fruit)|follicle]] {{cvt|8-13|mm}} long.<ref name=FloraBase>{{FloraBase|name=''Banksia borealis''|id=32626}}</ref><ref name=\"Nuytsia\">{{cite journal|last1=George|first1=Alex S.|title=New taxa and a new infrageneric classification in ''Dryandra'' R.Br.|journal=Nuytsia|date=1996|volume=10|issue=3|pages=343\u2013345}}</ref><ref name=\"CSIRO\">{{cite book |last1=George |first1=Alex S. |title=Flora of Australia |volume=17B |date=1999 |publisher=Australian Biological Resources Study, Canberra |location=Canberra |page=283 |url=https://www.environment.gov.au/system/files/pages/6d8c5c3b-8545-437e-b9b3-944ac95ee07a/files/flora-australia-17b-proteaceae-3-hakea-dryandra.pdf |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy and naming==\nThis banksia was first formally described in 1996 by [[Alex George]] in the journal ''[[Nuytsia (journal)|Nuytsia]]'' and given the name ''Dryandra borealis'' from specimens he collected in 1966, near the road between [[Kalbarri, Western Australia|Kalbarri]] and [[Ajana, Western Australia|Ajana]].<ref name=\"Nuytsia\" /><ref name=APNI1>{{cite web|title=''Dryandra borealis''|url= https://id.biodiversity.org.au/instance/apni/558984|publisher=APNI|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> In 2007, [[Austin Mast]] and [[Kevin Thiele]] transferred all the dryandras to the genus ''[[Banksia]]'' and this species became ''Banksia borealis''.<ref name=APNI>{{cite web|title=''Banksia borealis''|url= https://id.biodiversity.org.au/instance/apni/614236|publisher=APNI|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CSIRO\">{{cite journal|last1=Mast|first1=Austin R.|last2=Thiele|first2=Kevin|title=The transfer of Dryandra R.Br. to Banksia L.f. (Proteaceae)|journal=Australian Systematic Botany|date=2013|volume=20|issue=1|pages=63\u201371|doi=10.1071/SB06016}}</ref> The [[Botanical name|specific epithet]] (''borealis'') is a Latin word meaning \"northern\"<ref name=\"Stearn\">{{cite book |author=[[William T. Stearn]] |title=Botanical Latin. History, grammar, syntax, terminology and vocabulary |date=1992 |publisher=Timber Press |location=Portland, Oregon |edition=4th|page=377}}</ref> referring to the distribution of this species, the most northerly of all the dryandras.<ref name=\"Nuytsia\" />\n\nIn the same journal, George described two subspecies of ''Dryandra borealis'', later moved to ''Banksia'' by Mast and Thiele, and the names are accepted by the [[Australian Plant Census]]:\n* [[Banksia borealis subsp. borealis |''Banksia borealis'' <small>A.S.George</small> subsp. ''borealis'']]<ref name=\"APC1\">{{cite web |title=''Banksia borealis'' subsp. ''borealis'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/205088|website=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> is a shrub with a lignotuber;\n* ''Banksia borealis'' subsp. ''elatior'' <small>A.S.George</small><ref name=\"APC2\">{{cite web |title=''Banksia borealis'' subsp. ''elatior'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/205087|website=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> lacks a lignotuber.<ref name=\"Nuytsia\" />\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n''Banksia borealis'' occurs in two disjunct areas of Western Australia. Subspecies ''borealis'' is relatively common and grows in [[Kwongan]] between Kalbarri, [[Northampton, Western Australia|Northampton]] and [[Yuna, Western Australia|Yuna]]. Subspecies ''elatior'' is only known from a few small populations near [[Three Springs, Western Australia|Three Springs]] where it grows in tall scrub and low woodland.<ref name=\"Nuytsia\" />\n\n==Conservation status==\nSubspecies ''borealis'' is classified as \"not threatened\" by the Western Australian Government [[Department of Parks and Wildlife (Western Australia)|Department of Parks and Wildlife]],<ref name=FloraBase1>{{FloraBase|name=''Banksia borealis'' subsp. ''borealis''|id=32627}}</ref> but subspecies ''elatior'' is classified as \"[[Declared Rare and Priority Flora List|Priority Three]]\"<ref name=FloraBase2>{{FloraBase|name=''Banksia borealis'' subsp. ''elatior''|id=32628}}</ref>  meaning that it is poorly known and known from only a few locations but is not under imminent threat.<ref name=codes>{{cite web|title=Conservation codes for Western Australian Flora and Fauna|url=https://www.dpaw.wa.gov.au/images/documents/plants-animals/threatened-species/Listings/Conservation%20code%20definitions.pdf|publisher=Government of Western Australia Department of Parks and Wildlife|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4856563}}\n\n[[Category:Banksia ser. Dryandra|borealis]]\n[[Category:Banksia taxa by scientific name|borealis]]\n[[Category:Endemic flora of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Eudicots of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1996]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banksia_borealis"}
{"title_page": "The Epoch Times", "text_new": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Newspaper focused on China, based in New York City}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name              = The Epoch Times\n| image             = Epochtimescover.png\n| caption           = Front page of ''The Epoch Times'' New York edition for March 18, 2016\n| type              = International newspaper\n| format            = [[Broadsheet]]\n| owners            = Epoch Media Group\n| founder           = David blackburn\n| publisher         = Epoch Media Group\n| foundation        = {{start date and age|2000|5|20}}\n| political         = [[Conservatism]], [[anti-Communism]], [[anti-Socialism]], [[Right-wing populism]]\n| language          = Multiple, mainly Chinese and English\n| headquarters      = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| circulation       = 1,314,375 (2012, unaudited)<ref name=WWdistribution>[http://ads.epochtimes.com/pages/distribution-pricing-newspapers-distribution.htm \"The Epoch Times \u2013 Worldwide distribution\"]. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817010655/http://ads.epochtimes.com/pages/distribution-pricing-newspapers-distribution.htm|date=17 August 2008}} Retrieved 6 March 2014.</ref>\n| sister newspapers =\n| website           = {{URL|https://www.theepochtimes.com/}}\n}}\n'''''The Epoch Times''''' is a multi-language newspaper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2010/06/the-epoch-times-doesnt-like-to-brag-067223|title=The Epoch Times doesn't like to brag|last=Morais|first=Betsy|publisher=[[Politico]]|date=June 23, 2010}}</ref> It was founded in 2000 by John Tang and a group of [[Chinese Americans]] associated with the [[Falun Gong]] spiritual movement.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lawrence|first=Susan V.|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB108190438992282143 |title=Falun Gong Fields Media Weapons |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |date=14 April 2004}}</ref> Though the newspaper is known for general interest topics with a focus on news about China and its [[human rights in China|human rights issues]], it has become known for its support of [[Donald Trump|U.S. President Donald Trump]] and favorable coverage of far-right politicians according to this article who anyone can edit in Europe; a 2019 report showed it to be the second-largest funder of pro-Trump Facebook advertising after the Trump campaign.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|last=Brown|first=Hayes|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/hayesbrown/epoch-times-trump-administration-falun-gong|title=A Newspaper Banned In China Is Now One Of Trump's Biggest Defenders|work=BuzzFeed News|date=October 23, 2018|access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/a-letter-to-our-readers-regarding-buzzfeeds-reporting-about-the-epoch-times_2697534.html|title=A Letter to Our Readers Regarding BuzzFeed's Reporting About The Epoch Times|date=2018-10-23|website=The Epoch Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=https://popular.info/p/the-epoch-of-social-media|title=The Epoch of Social Media|website=popular.info|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref><ref name=\"NBCNews\"/><ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" /><ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\">{{Cite magazine|url=http://www.chinafile.com/reporting-opinion/media/german-edition-of-falun-gong-affiliated-epoch-times-aligns-far-right |title=The German Edition of Falun Gong's 'Epoch Times' Aligns with the Far Right |first=Bethany |last=Allen-Ebrahimian |publisher=Center on U.S.-China Relations at Asia Society |magazine=China File |date=23 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028135010/http://www.chinafile.com/reporting-opinion/media/german-edition-of-falun-gong-affiliated-epoch-times-aligns-far-right |archive-date=28 October 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BI-facebook\">{{Cite news |title=Aside from the Trump campaign itself, the biggest spender on pro-Trump Facebook ads is reportedly a secretive New York-based newspaper |last=Gilbert |first=Ben |date=August 21, 2019 |newspaper=Business Insider |publisher=Insider Inc. |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/epoch-times-pro-trump-facebook-ads-2019-8 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821030349/https://www.businessinsider.com/epoch-times-pro-trump-facebook-ads-2019-8 |archive-date=21 August 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy}}</ref><ref name=\":3\"/> The newspaper is part of the '''Epoch Media Group''', which also operates [[New Tang Dynasty Television]] (NTD).<ref name=\"NBCNews\"/> The group's news sites and [[YouTube]] channels have spread [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] such as [[QAnon]] and [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vaccination]] propaganda.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/technology/facebook-ads-epoch-times.html|title=Facebook Bans Ads From The Epoch Times|last=Alba|first=Davey|date=2019-08-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/8/23/20830229/epoch-times-facebook-ban-buying-ads-violating-policies-trump-propaganda|title=Epoch Times banned from advertising after sneaking pro-Trump propaganda onto Facebook|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=2019-08-23|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> \n\nFor its articles, the publication draws from a network within China, as well as staff living in the West.<ref name=\"Congressional Research Service2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|title=China and Falun Gong|author=Thomas Lum|date=August 11, 2006|publisher=Congressional Research Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205064042/http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|archivedate=February 5, 2012|df=mdy-all}} <!-- page CRS-8, list of Falun Gong-affiliated media --></ref><ref name=\"sfgate23\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/CULTURE-AND-RELIGION-Dissident-media-linked-to-2587555.php|title=Dissident media linked to Falun Gong / Chinese-language print, broadcast outlets in U.S. are making waves|last=Hua|first=Vanessa|date=December 18, 2005|work=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=December 9, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Schworm_Boston_Globe_12_03_20072\">{{Cite news|url=http://archive.boston.com/news/world/asia/articles/2007/12/03/chinese_american_activists_decry_chinas_communism/|title=Chinese-American activists decry China's communism|first=Peter|last=Schworm|date=December 3, 2007|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> ''The Epoch Times'' has print editions in English, Chinese, and six other languages.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/about-us|title=The Epoch Times - About Us|website=www.theepochtimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref> Fifteen additional languages are published online only. The English edition of ''The Epoch Times'' is sold in broadsheet format Monday to Friday in New York City and Washington, D.C., and weekly across the United States and Canada.<ref name=\":0\" /> A typical issue includes news sections, including Nation, World, Business, Opinion, and Commentary, and lifestyle sections, including Travel, Life & Tradition, Mind & Body, Food, and Puzzles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://printarchive.epochtimes.com/a1/en/region.php?dir=us/nyc|title=Epoch Times: Print Archive: United States: New York City|website=epoch Times|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' has been publishing in Chinese since May 2000. It is either sold or distributed free-of-charge in 35 countries, including various international regional editions. ''The Epoch Times'' websites are blocked in mainland China.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.aim.org/media-monitor/independent-chinese-newspaper-bucks-communists/|title= Independent Chinese Newspaper Bucks Communists|last1= Gossett|first1= Sherrie|date= 15 June 2005|website= aim.org|publisher= Accuracy in Media|access-date= 19 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n''The Epoch Times'' was founded in 2000 by John Tang and other [[Chinese Americans]] associated with the spiritual practice [[Falun Gong]].<ref>|title=\"The Epoch Times\", Falun Gong, and Me|https://www.williamgairdner.ca/the-epoch-times-falun-gong-and-me/</ref> The founders said they were responding to censorship inside China and a lack of international understanding about the Chinese government's repression of Falun Gong.<ref name=\"Congressional Research Service\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|title=China and Falun Gong|author=Thomas Lum|date=August 11, 2006|publisher=Congressional Research Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205064042/http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|archivedate=February 5, 2012|df=mdy-all}}<!-- page CRS-8, list of Falun Gong-affiliated media --></ref><ref>Ownby 2008, p. 223.</ref> In May 2000, the paper was first published in the [[Chinese language]] in New York, with the web launch in August 2000.<ref name=About_Us>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/n3/about-us \"''The Epoch Times'' \u2013 About Us\"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106083455/https://www.theepochtimes.com/n3/about-us |date=November 6, 2016}} theepochtimes.com access-date 6 March 2014</ref>\n\nBy 2003, ''The Epoch Times'' website and group of newspapers had grown into one of the largest Chinese-language news sites and newspaper groups outside China, with local editions in the U.S., Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Japan, Indonesia, Taiwan, Hong Kong, and major Western European countries.<ref name=zhao /> The first English edition launched online in 2003, followed by the New York print edition in 2004.<ref name=About_Us />\n\nIn 2000, ten of ''The Epoch Times'' correspondents were imprisoned in China, but current staff of the Chinese-language edition work in Hong Kong.<ref name=Tenth>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/canada/epoch-times-marks-10-years-in-canada-53136.html |title=Epoch Times Marks 10 Years in Canada|work=Epoch Times|date=March 17, 2011|access-date=July 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[NBC News]], \"little is publicly known about the precise ownership, origins or influences of ''The Epoch Times'',\" and it is loosely organized into several regional [[Nonprofit organization|tax free non-profits]], under the umbrella of the Epoch Media Group, together with [[New Tang Dynasty Television]].<ref name=\"NBCNews\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/trump-qanon-impending-judgment-day-behind-facebook-fueled-rise-epoch-n1044121|title=Trump, QAnon and an impending judgment day: Behind the Facebook-fueled rise of The Epoch Times|author=Brandy Zadrozny and Ben Collins|date=August 20, 2019|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> Its revenue in 2017 was [[United States dollar|US$]]8.1 million, and reported a spending of US$7.2 million.\n\n== Distribution ==\n[[File:Epoch Times Montreal.jpg|thumb|''\u00c9poqueTimes'' headquarters in [[Montreal]]'s [[Chinatown, Montreal|Chinatown]] in 2015]]\nAs of February 2012, 67 ''The Epoch Times'' newspaper editions{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} are published, in print in 11 languages, online in 21 languages.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nIn April 2019, videos and ads from the Epoch Media Group including ''The Epoch Times'' and New Tang Dynasty (NTD) totaled 3 billion views on Facebook, YouTube and Twitter, according to the analytics company Tubular. That ranked it 11th among all video creators, and ahead of any other traditional news publisher, according to NBC News.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" />\n\n== Relationship to Falun Gong ==\n[[Associated Press]] reporter [[Nahal Toosi]] wrote that it is \"technically inaccurate\" to say that the Falun Gong organization owns ''The Epoch Times,'' but many of the newspaper's staffers are Falun Gong practitioners. Toosi noted \"many observers\" have said Falun Gong uses the newspaper for its public relations campaigns,<ref name=\"thepost\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/05/AR2007020500185_pf.html|title=Paper denies representing Falun Gong|newspaper=Washington Post|access-date=4 December 2015}}</ref> and the paper is connected with the group and carries sympathetic coverage of it.<ref name=\"thepost\" /><ref name=\"Groot, Stafford 2012\" /><ref name=Elwood2007>{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=34vGv_HDGG8C&pg=PA217 |page=217 |title=World Religions in America |editor=Jacob Neusner |publisher=Westminster John Knox Press |year=2007 |last=Ellwood |first=Robert S. |last2=Csikszentmihalyi |first2=Mark A. |chapter=East Asian Religions |isbn=9781611640472 |quote=... the ''Epoch Times'', an anticommunist newspaper connected with Falun Gong organization...}}</ref><ref name=Sun2009>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAsB54UlQE8C&pg=PR11 |page=xi |last=Sun |first=Wanning |title=Media and the Chinese Diaspora: Community, Communications and Commerce |publisher=Routledge |year=2009 |isbn=9781134263592 |quote=...the ''Epoch Times''&nbsp;\u2013 a globally circulated pro-Falun Gong, anti-Communist Chinese-language newspaper...}}</ref><ref name=Denton2011>{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ul89eeKHLGEC&pg=PA268 |page=268 |title=Places of Memory in Modern China: History, Politics, and Identity |editor=Marc Andre Matten |last=Denton |first=Kirk A. |chapter=Yan'an as a Site of Memory |publisher=Brill |year=2011 |isbn=9789004219014 |series=Leiden Series in Comparative Historiography |volume=5 |quote=An article in the anti-Communist, Falun Gong ''Epoch Times'' claims, without citing any sources, that Zhang's death was the result of an accident involving opium use.}}</ref>\n\nThe English ''Epoch Times'' chair Stephen Gregory said in 2007: \"It's not a Falun Gong newspaper. Falun Gong is a question of an individual's belief. The paper's not owned by Falun Gong, it doesn't speak for Falun Gong, it doesn't represent Falun Gong. It does cover the persecution of Falun Gong in China.\"<ref name=\"thepost\" /> In 2003 sociologist [[Yuezhi Zhao]] wrote that the paper \"displays an indisputable ideological and organizational affinity with Falun Gong\" and that it strongly emphasizes negative portrayals of the Chinese government and positive portrayals of Falun Gong. Per Zhao, ''Epoch'' portrays itself as neutral, independent, and public-interest oriented.<ref name=\"zhao\" />  \n\nCanadian scholar Clement Tong wrote<ref name=\"Groot, Stafford 2012\">{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lm2tdagEnL4C&pg=PA103 |page=103 |title=The Engaging State: South Australia's Engagement with the Asia-Pacific Region |editor=John Spoehr |editor2=Purnendra Jain |chapter=China and South Australia |publisher=Wakefield Press |year=2012 |isbn=9781743051573 |last=Groot |first=Gerry |last2=Stafford |first2=Glen |quote=In related vein, another paper with wide distribution but published elsewhere is ''The Epoch Times'' (Dajiyuan shibao), the qigong meditation religious group Falun gong mouth-piece, which runs a strong anti-communist line.}}</ref><ref name=\"Thornton2008\">{{Cite book |title=Popular Protest in China |last=Thornton |first=Patricia M. |editor=Kevin J. O'Brien |pages=199\u2013200 |chapter=Manufacturing Dissent in Transnational China |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=9780674041585 |year=2008 |series=Harvard Contemporary China |volume=15}}</ref><ref name=\"Tong2015\">{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kpHvCgAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA71 |page=71 |editor=Jean-Guy A. Goulet |editor2=Liam D. Murphy |editor3=Anastasia Panagakos |last=Tong |first=Clement |title=Religious Diversity Today: Experiencing Religion in the Contemporary World |chapter=Western Apocalyptic Narratives in the International Arena |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2015 |isbn=9781440833328 |volume=3}}</ref><ref name=\"James Jiann Hua To, 2014\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KGe7AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA197 |page=97 |title=Qiaowu: Extra-Territorial Policies for the Overseas Chinese |author=James Jiann Hua To |publisher=Brill |year=2014 |isbn=9789004272286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Noakes |first=Stephen |title=Falun Gong, Ten Years On |date=June 2010 |journal=Pacific Affairs |volume=83 |number=2 |pages=349\u201357 |quote=The Epoch Times newspaper also serves as a mouthpiece for Falun Gong internationally...|doi= 10.5509/2010832349}}</ref> ''The Epoch Times'' \"operates as a mouthpiece for\" Falun Gong without an official statement of affiliation with the movement.<ref name=\"Tong2015\" /> In 2008, David Ownby, director of the Center for East Asian Studies at the [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]] and the author of ''Falun Gong and the Future of China'', said the newspaper is set up by Falun Gong practitioners with their own money.<ref name=\"Ownby 2008 p.223\" /> He describes ''The Epoch Times'' as wishing to be taken seriously as a global newspaper rather than being judged on the basis of its strong association with Falun Gong.<ref name=\"Ownby 2008 p.223\">{{Cite book |last=Ownby |first=David |title=Falun Gong and the Future of China |year=2008 |url=https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb/page/223 223] |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199716371}}</ref><ref name=\"Ownby 2008 p.8\">{{Cite book |last=Ownby |first=David |title=Falun Gong and the Future of China |year=2008 |url=https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb/page/8 8] |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199716371}}</ref> He wrote: \"''Epoch Times'' is a newspaper with a mission, that of reporting on issues bearing on human rights throughout the world, which allows for considerable focus on China and Falun Gong.\"<ref name=\"DO2\">Ownby 2008, p. 221.</ref> The paper's reporting on Chinese affairs often highlights negative news about the Chinese government, and covers Falun Gong in a sympathetic light. The paper is seen to articulate Falun Gong's views on a range of issues, and may be part of a ''de facto'' media alliance with democracy activists in exile.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Couldry|first=Nick|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yRVtAAAAQBAJ|title=Contesting Media Power: Alternative Media in a Networked World|last2=Curran|first2=James|date=2003-09-22|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=9780742575202}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, [[Li Hongzhi]], the founder of Falun Gong, appeared at the newspaper's office in New York City and called for the expansion of ''The Epoch Times'' to \"become regular media\". Former employees also noted the involvement of Falun Gong practitioners in the management and editorial process.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /> Three anonymous former employees said ''Epoch Times'' workers were encouraged to attend weekly \"Fa study\" sessions outside work hours to study the teachings of Li Hongzhi.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n''The Epoch Times'' runs frequent promotional stories about the [[Shen Yun]] dance troupe that is affiliated with Falun Gong. ''The New Yorker'''s review of Shen Yun called ''The Epoch Times'' \"the world\u2019s foremost purveyor of Shen Yun content.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/stepping-into-the-uncanny-unsettling-world-of-shen-yun|title=Stepping Into the Uncanny, Unsettling World of Shen Yun|last=Tolentino|first=Jia|date=2019-03-19|access-date=2019-08-24|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, an [[NBC News]] investigative report suggested ''The Epoch Times's'' political coverage may be affected by Falun Gong believers' anticipation of a judgment day in which communists are sent to hell, and Falun Gong's allies are spared. Former ''Epoch Times''' employees told NBC News that President Donald Trump is viewed as a key anti-communist ally,<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /> allegedly \"hastening judgement day and the delivery of communists to hell.\"<ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\">{{cite news |last1=Zadrozny |first1=Brandy |last2=Collins |first2=Ben |title=Facebook bans ads from The Epoch Times after huge pro-Trump buy |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/23/facebook-bans-ads-from-the-epoch-times-after-huge-pro-trump-buy.html |accessdate=7 October 2019 |agency=CNBC |date=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notable coverage ==\n=== Organ harvesting in China ===\n{{Further|Persecution of Falun Gong#Organ harvesting |Organ harvesting from Falun Gong practitioners in China}}\nIn March 2006, ''The Epoch Times'' published the allegations of three Chinese individuals who said that thousands of [[Falun Gong]] practitioners had been killed to supply China's organ transplant industry,<ref>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/worse-than-any-nightmarejournalist-quits-china-to-expose-concentration-camp-horrors-and-bird-flu-coverup_1732938.html \"Worse Than Any Nightmare\u2014Journalist Quits China to Expose Concentration Camp Horrors and Bird Flu Coverup\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207185741/http://en.epochtimes.com/news/6-3-10/39111.html |date=February 7, 2009}}, Epoch Times, 10 March 2006</ref><ref>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/news/6-3-17/39405.html \"New Witness Confirms Existence of Chinese Concentration Camp, Says Organs Removed from Live Victims\"] ''The Epoch Times'', 17 March 2006</ref><ref name=36cc /> including a doctor, who said there were 36 concentration camps all over China.<ref name=36cc>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/news/6-3-31/39910.html \"Source Reveals Other Chinese Concentration Camps\"] ''The Epoch Times'', 31 March 2006</ref> The [[Kilgour\u2013Matas report]]<ref name=orgharv>[[David Kilgour]], [[David Matas]] (6 July 2006, revised 31 January 2007) [http://organharvestinvestigation.net \"An Independent Investigation into Allegations of Organ Harvesting of Falun Gong Practitioners in China\"] (in 22 languages) organharvestinvestigation.net</ref> stated that \"the source of 41,500 transplants for the six year period 2000 to 2005 is unexplained\" and \"we believe that there has been and continues today to be large scale organ seizures from unwilling [[Falun Gong]] practitioners\".<ref name=orgharv /> Appendix 16 of the revised report refuted [[Harry Wu]]'s negative comments.<ref name=orgharv />\n\nIn 2008, two United Nations Special Rapporteurs reiterated their requests for \"the Chinese government to fully explain the allegation of taking vital organs from Falun Gong practitioners and the source of organs for the sudden increase in organ transplants that has been going on in China since the year 2000\".<ref>[http://www.theinformationdaily.com/2008/05/09/united-nations-human-rights-special-rapporteurs-reiterate-findings-on-chinas-organ-harvesting-from-falun-gong-practitioners \"United Nations Human Rights Special Rapporteurs Reiterate Findings on China's Organ Harvesting from Falun Gong Practitioners\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512183828/http://www.theinformationdaily.com/2008/05/09/united-nations-human-rights-special-rapporteurs-reiterate-findings-on-chinas-organ-harvesting-from-falun-gong-practitioners |date=May 12, 2015}}, The Information Daily.com, 9 May 2008</ref> The Chinese government has consistently denied the allegations. The Foreign Affairs Subcommittee of the [[United States House of Representatives]] has adopted resolutions condemning alleged organ harvesting from Falun Gong prisoners of conscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-resolution/343/text |title=H.Res.343 \u2013 Expressing concern regarding persistent and credible reports of systematic, state-sanctioned organ harvesting from non-consenting prisoners of conscience in the People's Republic of China, including from large numbers of Falun Gong practitioners and members of other religious and ethnic minority groups. |author=Ileana Ros-Lehtinen |date=25 June 2015 |publisher=Library of Congress |access-date=20 December 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122222318/https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-resolution/343/text |archivedate=November 22, 2016 |url-status=live |website=congress.gov |df=mdy}}</ref>\n\n=== Other reports ===\nDuring the 2009 [[New York City Comptroller]] elections, ''The Epoch Times'' alleged that [[Taiwan]]-born [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee [[John Liu]] is part of a \"United Front\" by the [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] (CCP) to infiltrate the United States and subvert its government, democracy, and human rights in general.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/content/view/22317/ |title=Chinese Communist Party Subverts Democracies and Rights Abroad |work=The Epoch Times |date=September 10, 2009 |access-date=December 18, 2009}}</ref> The newspaper alleged that \"the CCP works tenaciously and systematically to place its people [...] in key positions in corporations, academia, and government in the United States and other countries.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/content/view/22292/|title=Editor's Note on Coverage of John Liu: Uncovering a hidden threat|date=September 10, 2009}}</ref> ''The Epoch Times'' also published an 8-page \"special edition\", and also featured on its website a section focused on coverage of Liu's reported ties with CCP officials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/component/option,com_ettopic/topicid,57/ |title=John Liu and the United Front |work=The Epoch Times |access-date=December 18, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Hu Jintao]]'s visit to Canada in June 2010, the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' noted that ''The Epoch Times'' had published several \"hard-hitting\" critical stories on Hu's visit, such as allegations of the local Chinese embassy's orchestration of welcome parades, as well as an alleged recording of a speech by the first secretary of education Liu Shaohua, in which Liu stated that embassy would provide accommodation and transport for over 3,000 participants in the welcome parade.<ref name=star>Susan Delacourt, [https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/827903--harper-helps-hu-keep-critics-away \"Harper helps Hu keep critics away\"], thestar.com 25 Jun 2010</ref>\n\nCanadian media reported that the parliamentary press office made deliberate arrangements in relation to Hu's public appearances limiting ''The Epoch Times''{{'}} access to the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], even though the newspaper is an accredited member of the Canadian Parliamentary Press Gallery.<ref name=star /> The paper carried an exclusive interview with outspoken Canadian Member of Parliament [[Rob Anders]], wherein Anders alleged that the Chinese government used gifts and business deals in attempts to influence Canadian political decisions.<ref name='Secrecy'>{{Cite news |first=Norma |last=Greenaway |title=Liberals decry secrecy around CSIS report |date=August 3, 2010 |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/Liberals+decry+secrecy+around+CSIS+report/3355144/story.html |work=Vancouver Sun |access-date=2012-05-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100805081220/http://www.vancouversun.com/news/Liberals+decry+secrecy+around+CSIS+report/3355144/story.html |archivedate=2010-08-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vancourier.com/Chinese+Canadian+leader+laments+agency+allegations/3337835/story.html |title=Chinese-Canadian leader laments spy agency allegations |publisher=[[Vancouver Courier]] |date=July 29, 2010 |access-date=2012-05-25}}</ref>\n\nA story in ''The Epoch Times'' on February 17, 2020 shared a map from the internet that falsely alleged massive sulfur dioxide releases from crematoriums during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] in China, speculating that 14,000 bodies may have been burned.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/map-forecast-based-past-data-not-real-time-satellite-readings|title=This map is a forecast based on past data, not real-time satellite readings|date=2020-02-20|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epochtimes.com/b5/20/2/17/n11875579.htm|title=\u6b66\u6f22\u4e8c\u6c27\u5316\u786b\u7206\u8868 \u53f0\u5b78\u8005\uff1a\u71d2\u5c4d\u9ad4\u662f\u5408\u7406\u63a8\u65b7 - \u5927\u7d00\u5143|date=2020-02-17|website=\u5927\u7d00\u5143 www.epochtimes.com|language=zh-TW|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref> A fact check by [[Agence France-Presse|AFP]] reported that the map was a NASA forecast taken out of context.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== Editorial stance ==\nThe editorial stance of ''The Epoch Times'' is generally considered [[anti-communism|anti-communist]], specifically opposing the [[Communist Party of China]].<ref name=\"Thornton2008\" />\n\nIn recent years, the newspaper has also been noted for favorable coverage of the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]], [[far-right politics in Germany|the German far right]], and the [[History of far-right movements in France|French far right]].<ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\" /><ref name=\":12\">[https://meedia.de/2016/03/18/kopp-sputnik-epoch-times-co-nachrichten-aus-einem-rechten-paralleluniversum/ Kopp, Sputnik, Epoch Times & Co: Nachrichten aus einem rechten Paralleluniversum] Stefan Winterbauer, Meedia. March 13, 2016</ref><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/155076/obscure-newspaper-fueling-far-right-europe|title=The Obscure Newspaper Fueling the Far-Right in Europe|last=Hettena|first=Seth|date=2019-09-17|work=The New Republic|access-date=2019-12-16|issn=0028-6583}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a report by NBC News, ''The Epoch Times'' \"generally stayed out of U.S. politics\" before 2016, \"unless they dovetailed with Chinese interests.\" Ben Hurley, a former ''Epoch Times'' employee until 2013, told NBC News that the newspaper was critical toward abortion and LGBT, and that Falun Gong practitioners \"saw communism everywhere\" including in internationalist figures like [[Hillary Clinton]] and [[Kofi Annan]], \"but there was more room for disagreements in the early days.\" Since 2016, according to NBC News, ''The Epoch Times'' has promoted favorable coverage of [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] campaign and presidency, and emphasized issues such as [[Islamic terrorism]] and [[illegal immigration to the United States]]. It has also emphasized \"what the publication claims is a labyrinthian, global conspiracy led by [Hillary] Clinton and former President Barack Obama to tear down Trump.\"<ref name=\"NBCNews\" />\n\nThe newspaper counters what it considers to be Chinese Communist Party propaganda through its own opinion pieces and reporting. It covers causes and groups opposed to the CCP, including Falun Gong, dissidents, activists, and supporters of the [[Central Tibetan Administration|Tibetan government-in-exile]]. The paper also reports on Falun Gong-related news, including the group's attempt to sue former [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Communist Party general secretary]] [[Jiang Zemin]] under civil legislation for \"[[genocide]]\", not covered by most other overseas Chinese-language newspapers.<ref name=\"sfgate2\">{{Cite news|url= https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/CULTURE-AND-RELIGION-Dissident-media-linked-to-2587555.php|title= Dissident media linked to Falun Gong / Chinese-language print, broadcast outlets in U.S. are making waves|work= San Francisco Chronicle|date= December 18, 2005|access-date= December 9, 2006|first= Vanessa|last= Hua}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper is also at odds with the [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]]-owned newspaper ''[[World Journal]]'', accusing it of being a \"megaphone for the evil Chinese Communist Party\".<ref name= \"HPheartsandmind\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/chinese-press-abroad_n_4729474|title=The Chinese Press Battles For Hearts And Minds Abroad|date=February 13, 2014|website=HuffPost Canada}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epochtimes.com/gb/14/1/24/n4067175.htm|title=\u65e7\u91d1\u5c71\u6cd5\u8f6e\u529f\u5b66\u5458\u81f4\u4e16\u754c\u65e5\u62a5\u7684\u516c\u5f00\u4fe1 - \u5927\u7eaa\u5143|date=January 24, 2014|website=\u5927\u7eaa\u5143 www.epochtimes.com}}</ref>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' is known for alleging [[conspiracy|conspiracies]] against former [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Communist Party general secretary]] [[Jiang Zemin]],<ref name= \"HPheartsandmind\" /> under whose administration Falun Gong was suppressed in China.\n\nIn 2005, the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' reported that \"three new U.S.-based, Chinese-language media outlets that provide provocative reporting about the Communist Party, government oppression and social unrest in China [namely ''The Epoch Times'', Sound of Hope, and NTDTV] have ties to the Falun Gong spiritual movement.\" When interviewed, executives at each outlet claimed they did not represent the Falun Gong movement as a whole.<ref name=\"sfgate2\" />\n\n''The Epoch Times'' also picks up mainstream [[News agency|newswire]] stories and in some places can resemble a community newspaper.<ref name=\"waves\">Eugenia Chien, [http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a \"Falun Gong-Linked Media Venture Makes Waves, Raises Questions\"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306081937/http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a |date=March 6, 2008}} ''New America Media'', News Analysis, May 16, 2006</ref> According to sociologist [[Yuezhi Zhao|Zhao Yuezhi]], \"While mainstream newspaper typically treat Web versions as an extension of the already-existing print version, ''The Epoch Times'' website serves as the master for all its worldwide papers.\"<ref name=\"zhao\">Zhao, Yuezhi, \"Falun Gong, Identity, and the Struggle over Meaning Inside and Outside China\", pp 209\u2013223 in ''Contesting Media Power: Alternative Media in a Networked World'', edited by Nick Couldry and James Curran (Rowman & Littlefield, 2003)</ref>\n\nIn some cases ''The Epoch Times'' operates in a hostile overseas environment, in which \"overseas Chinese media companies choosing to remain independent or publish non-approved content become the targets of an aggressive campaign of elimination or control.\" In one instance Chinese diplomatic officials made threats against media for reporting Falun Gong-related content; in other cases, advertisers have been regularly threatened not to support ''The Epoch Times'' in any way. Communist Party authorities have been accused of resorting to \"militant methods\" against the newspaper and its staff, including attacking staff and destroying computer equipment.<ref>{{Cite book|title= Qiaowu: Extra-Territorial Policies for the Overseas Chinese|last= To|first= James Jiann Hua|publisher= BRILL|year= 2014|isbn= 9789004272286|location= |pages= 180}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper reported that in 2005 the Communist Party \"exerted hard and soft pressure\" on printing houses in Hong Kong, forcing the paper to stop printing, after it reported on Tibet, human rights, Falun Gong, and was the first media to break the story on [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]].<ref>{{Cite book|title= Taiwan: The Threatened Democracy|last= Herschensohn|first= Bruce|publisher= WND Books|year= 2006|isbn= 9780977898428|location= |pages= 99}}</ref> The newspaper was also briefly banned from Malaysia after coming under reported pressure by the Chinese Communist Party.<ref name=Sun2009 />\n\nIn 2016, the newspaper was removed from the pharmacy of [[Australian National University]], after the president of the [[Chinese Students and Scholars Association]] confronted the pharmacist and threw out the papers. The incident drew national media coverage over questions of Chinese government sponsored overseas student organizations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/education/the-patriotic-education-of-chinese-students-at-australian-universities-20161003-gru13j.html|title=The 'patriotic education' of Chinese students at Australian universities|last=Wen|first=Alexander Joske and Philip|date=2016-10-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/world/asia/canberra-pharmacy-at-front-line-of-chinas-push-for-global-influence-20160901-gr65xy|title=Canberra pharmacy at front line of China's push for global influence|date=2016-09-01|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, The German edition of the newspaper, ''The Epoch Times Deutschland'', which became Web-only in 2012, was accused by online magazine ''The China File'' of being aligned with the German far-right, and attractive to supporters of the [[Alternative for Germany]] (AfD) party and the anti-immigrant group [[Pegida]].<ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\" />  Stefanie Albrecht, a reporter for the German broadcaster RTL who spent several days inside the Berlin office of ''The Epoch Times'' while investigating the far right, said that ''The Epoch Times'' staffers she met had no journalistic training and didn't check facts, trusting instead in the alternative sources they consulted.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn [[France]], ''The Epoch TImes'' gives \"an unfettered platform to [[Jean-Marie Le Pen]], the patriarch of the French far right, and his daughter, [[Marine Le Pen|Marine]], who leads the nationalist party her father founded,\" according to ''[[The New Republic]]''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Trump administration ==\nAccording to ''[[BuzzFeed News]]'', ''The Epoch Times'' is known as \"one of the staunchest defenders of [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Donald Trump's presidency]].\"<ref name=\":22\" /> The paper has championed Trump's [[Spygate (conspiracy theory)|Spygate conspiracy theory]] in its news coverage and advertising, and the Epoch Media Group's ''Edge of Wonder'' videos on YouTube have spread the right-wing, pro-Trump [[QAnon|QAnon conspiracy theory]].<ref name=\"NBCNews\" />\n\nThe ''Edge of Wonder'' hosts, according to ''[[The Daily Dot]]'', \"embrace QAnon completely\" even though \"almost nothing QAnon has foretold has actually taken place.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/layer8/edge-wonder-qanon-youtube/|title=This massive YouTube channel is normalizing QAnon|date=2019-08-27|website=The Daily Dot|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> An NBC News report found that the ''Edge of Wonder'' hosts have been creative director and chief photo editor at ''The Epoch Times,'' and the newspaper promoted ''Edge of Wonder'' videos in dozens of Facebook posts through 2019.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /> The hosts and the newspaper's publisher deny that they are currently affiliated.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/our-response-to-nbc-news-inappropriate-questions_2971493.html|title=Our Response to NBC News' Inappropriate Questions|last=|first=|date=|work=The Epoch Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edgeofwonder.tv/about|title=Edge of Wonder|website=edgeofwonder.tv|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn a response to a ''BuzzFeed'' report about ''The Epoch Times''' coverage of Trump, ''The Epoch Times'' editor-in-chief Jasper Fakkert wrote in a letter to readers: \"We see the Trump administration's efforts to change socialist policies in America, as well as set policies to counter infiltration and subversion by China, as remarkable reversals from past policies, and sincere efforts that, if fully realized, will benefit America and the world as a whole.\"<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":32\" />\n\nIn April 2018, ''The Epoch Times'' publisher Stephen Gregory and editor-in-chief Jasper Fakkert reported a third-hand claim that [[Donald Trump]] reads ''The Epoch Times'' every day and \"it's the one newspaper that he believes to be a truthful and correct paper.\"<ref name=\":22\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/trump-said-to-describe-the-epoch-times-as-most-credible-newspaper_2495714.html|title=Trump Said to Describe The Epoch Times as 'Most Credible Newspaper'|date=2018-04-16|website=The Epoch Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, ''The Epoch Times'' photographer Samira Bouaou broke White House protocol and handed Trump a folder during an official event.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/white-house-reviews-incident-involving-epoch-times-photographer-handing-a-folder-to-trump/2018/09/18/e9d8b8ba-bac5-11e8-bdc0-90f81cc58c5d_story.html|title=White House reviews incident involving ''The Epoch Times'' photographer handing a folder to Trump|last=Nakamura|first=David|date=September 18, 2018|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919014513/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/white-house-reviews-incident-involving-epoch-times-photographer-handing-a-folder-to-trump/2018/09/18/e9d8b8ba-bac5-11e8-bdc0-90f81cc58c5d_story.html?tid=pm_politics_pop|archive-date=September 19, 2018|last2=Shih|first2=Gerry|quote=The photographer, identified by other photojournalists as Samira Bouaou, passed the purple-colored folder to Trump as he was walking out of the East Room on Sept. 12 after delivering remarks at a reception for the Congressional Medal of Honor Society.}}</ref>\n\nDuring the February 2020 [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|Iowa Democratic Caucuses]], ''The Epoch Times'' shared viral [[disinformation]] from the conservative group [[Judicial Watch]] that falsely alleged inflated voter rolls.<ref name=\":8\" /> The claim, which went viral on Facebook, was debunked by fact checkers and the Iowa secretary of state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/live-blog/iowa-caucuses-live-updates-2020-democrats-make-their-final-pitches-n1128596/ncrd1128966|title=Debunked claims about Iowa voter fraud pushed by conservative activists|last=Brandy Zadrozny26d ago / 8:32 PM UTC|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/iowa-misinformation-spreads-online-despite-new-policies/|title=Iowa Misinformation Spreads Online, Despite New Policies|work=Wired|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref> A Harvard media expert quoted by NBC News said ''The Epoch Times'' employed a \"classic disinformation tactic\" known as \"trading up the chain,\" in which false stories are repackaged and shared.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Advertising controversies ===\n\n==== Ad ban on Facebook ====\nDuring a six month period in 2019, ''The Epoch Times'' spent more than $1.5 million on about 11,000 Facebook ads that NBC News said were \"pro-Trump advertisements\". NBC said the amount spent was more than any group except the Trump campaign itself.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref name=\"BI-facebook\" /> Political ad spending on Facebook in April 2019 through an account called \"Coverage of the Trump Presidency by The Epoch Times\" exceeded any politician's spending except Trump and Democrat [[Joe Biden]].<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\"FWIW: Where are they now\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anotheracronym.org/newsletter/where-are-they-now/|title=FWIW: Where are they now?|website=ACRONYM|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Journalist [[Judd Legum]] wrote in May 2019 that ''The Epoch Times'' ads were \"boosting Donald Trump and floating conspiracy theories about Joe Biden\".<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\"FWIW: Where are they now\" />\n\nIn August 2019, [[Facebook]] banned ''The Epoch Times'' from advertising on its platform, after finding that the newspaper broke Facebook's political transparency rules by publishing pro-Trump subscription ads through [[Sockpuppet (Internet)|sockpuppet]] pages such as \u201cHonest Paper\u201d and \u201cPure American Journalism.\"<ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> A Facebook representative told NBC: \"Over the past year we removed accounts associated with ''The Epoch Times'' for violating our ad policies, including trying to get around our review systems.\" <ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" />\n\n''The Epoch Times'' publisher, Stephen Gregory, wrote in response that the paper didn't intend to violate Facebook's rules. The video ads, he wrote, \"are overtly ''Epoch Times'' advertisements for our subscriptions,\u201d and \"discuss ''The Epoch Times''\u2019 editorial and feature content and encourage people to subscribe to our print newspaper.\"<ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/epoch-times-statement-in-response-to-nbc-facebook-stories_3053492.html|title=Epoch Times Statement in Response to NBC Facebook Stories|date=2019-08-23|website=www.theepochtimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\n==== Removal of ''The BL'' on Facebook ====\nIn October 2019, the fact-checking website [[Snopes]] reported that ''The Epoch Times'' is closely linked to a large network of Facebook pages and groups called ''The BL'' (''The Beauty of Life'') that shares pro-Trump views and conspiracy theories such as [[QAnon]]. ''The BL'' has spent at least $510,698 on Facebook advertising. Hundreds of the ads were removed for violations of Facebook's advertising rules. The ''BL'' network of pages has 28 million followers on Facebook in total, according to ''Snopes''. The editor-in-chief of ''The BL'' recently worked as editor-in-chief of ''The Epoch Times,'' and several other ''BL'' employees are listed as current or former employees of ''The Epoch Times''. ''The BL'' is registered in [[Middletown, Orange County, New York|Middletown]], [[New York (state)|New York]], to an address that also is registered to Falun Gong's ''Sound of Hope Radio Network'' and is associated with the YouTube series ''Beyond Science,'' but Snopes found \"the outlet as a whole is literally the English-language edition of ''Epoch Times'' Vietnam.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/10/11/pro-trump-outlet-linked-epoch-times/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Expanding Pro-Trump Outlet 'The BL' Is Closely Linked to The Epoch Times|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/12/13/facebook-bl-cib/|title=If Facebook Is Dealing with Deceptive 'BL' Network, It's Not Working|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> Snopes found that''The BL'' uses more than 300 fake Facebook profiles based in Vietnam and other countries, using names, stock photos and celebrity photos in their profiles to emulate Americans, to administer more than 150 pro-Trump Facebook groups amplifying its content.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/11/12/bl-fake-profiles/|title=How a Pro-Trump Network Is Building a Fake Empire on Facebook and Getting Away with It|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\nAn unnamed representative of ''The BL'' wrote to ''Snopes'' that \u201cThe BL has NO connection with ''The Epoch Times'',\" and a \"few of our staff has job experience \u2026 working in ''The Epoch Times'', but now they are working full time in The BL.\u201d ''The Epoch Times''\u2019 publisher, Stephen Gregory, said \u201c''The Epoch Times'' is not affiliated with the BL.\u201d <ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn December 2019, Facebook announced it removed a large network of accounts, pages, and groups linked to The BL and Epoch Media Group for coordinated inauthentic behavior on behalf of a foreign actor. The network had 55 million followers on Facebook and Instagram, and $9.5 million had been spent on Facebook ads through its accounts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://about.fb.com/news/2019/12/removing-coordinated-inauthentic-behavior-from-georgia-vietnam-and-the-us/|title=Removing Coordinated Inauthentic Behavior From Georgia, Vietnam and the US|date=2019-12-20|website=About Facebook|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\nOn December 20, 2019, ''The New York Times'' reported, in \"Facebook Discovers Fakes That Show Evolution of [[Fake news|Disinformation]]\", that Facebook had deleted \"hundreds of accounts with ties to the Epoch Media Group, parent company of the Falun Gong-related publication and conservative news outlet ''The Epoch Times''\" using fake profile photos that had been generated using [[artificial intelligence]]. The [[Atlantic Council#The Digital Forensic Research Lab (DFRLab)|Atlantic Council Digital Forensic Research Lab]] (DFRLab) director Graham Brookie stated that the coordinated network of fake accounts demonstrated \"an eerie, tech-enabled future of disinformation\". Facebook's head of security policy, Nathaniel Gleicher, said, \"What\u2019s new here is that this is purportedly a U.S.-based media company leveraging foreign actors posing as Americans to push political content. We\u2019ve seen it a lot with state actors in the past.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/20/business/facebook-ai-generated-profiles.html?ribbon-ad-idx=2&rref=business|title=Facebook Discovers Fakes That Show Evolution of Disinformation|website=The New York Times|language=en|date=2019-12-20|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/facebook-says-pro-trump-media-outlet-used-artificial-intelligence-create-n1105951|title=Facebook says a pro-Trump media outlet used artificial intelligence to create fake people and push conspiracies|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n==== YouTube ads ====\nAs Facebook banned ''The Epoch Times'' from advertising, the newspaper shifted its spending to [[YouTube]]. ''The Epoch Times'' has spent more than $1 million on YouTube ads, some promoting conspiracy theories,''The New York Times'' reported in February 2020.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Editorials ==\n=== Nine commentaries on the Communist Party ===\nIn November 2004, the Chinese version of ''The Epoch Times'' published a series of editorials titled \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"<ref name=9com>[http://www.ninecommentaries.com/english \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"] ninecommentaries.com/english</ref> ({{Lang-zh|t=\u4e5d\u8a55\u5171\u7522\u9ee8|s=\u4e5d\u8bc4\u5171\u4ea7\u515a|first=t|links=no}}). The editorials detail what ''The Epoch Times'' characterizes as the CCP's violent political campaigns throughout its history, from its ascent to power under [[Mao Zedong]] to its present-day form. The CCP is criticized as an illegitimate institution that used underhanded tactics to gain power. The commentaries allege that the CCP \"destroyed traditional Chinese culture\" and call the CCP an \"evil cult\".<ref>{{Cite web|author=The Epoch Times Dec 26, 2004 |url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/commentary-8-on-how-the-chinese-communist-party-is-an-evil-cult_3950.html |title=Part 8: On How the Chinese Communist Party Is an Evil Cult |work=The Epoch Times |date=December 26, 2004 |access-date=December 18, 2009}}</ref> According to China scholar David Ownby, the Nine Commentaries are a \"condemnation of communism and a direct indictment of the legitimacy of the Chinese Communist Party's rule in China\". While acknowledging the \"unnecessary violence\" the Chinese Communist Party has inflicted, Ownby finds that the lack of balance and nuance in tone and style makes the editorials resemble \"anti-Communist propaganda written in Taiwan in the 1950s.\"<ref name=\"DO2\" />\n\nThe Nine Commentaries have been translated into more than 30 other languages<ref name=9com /> and released as a DVD.<ref name=9comDVD>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s8oaUepvc70 \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"] NTDTV youtube.com</ref>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' website hosts a \"CCP Renunciations\" service, encouraging Chinese people to quit the CCP and its related organizations. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tuidang.epochtimes.com/|title=\u5927\u7eaa\u5143\u9000\u515a\u7f51\u7ad9|website=tuidang.epochtimes.com|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref> The Chinese edition of the newspaper publishes the number of people who it claims have quit.\n\n== Assessments ==\nAccording to Ming Xia, political science professor at the Graduate Center at the City University of New York, ''The Epoch Times'' represents part of Falun Gong's effort to expand to non-practitioners, and \"is part of the Falun Gong strategy to embed itself into the large civil society for influence and legitimacy\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.religionnewsblog.com/17386/epoch-times|title=Paper denies representing Falun Gong|date=February 5, 2007|publisher=Religionnewsblog.com|access-date=6 March 2014}}</ref> He described ''The Epoch Times'' staff as largely part-time and volunteer, and said they \"do not follow the protocols professional journalists abide by.\"<ref name=\":5\"/>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' has been criticized by some scholars for biases, particularly regarding the Chinese Communist Party and mainland China issues, as well as for being a \"mouthpiece\" of the [[Falun Gong]] movement.<ref name=\"Groot, Stafford 2012\" /><ref name=\"Thornton2008\" /><ref name=\"James Jiann Hua To, 2014\" /><ref name=\"Elwood2007\" /><ref name=\"Sun2009\" /><ref name=\"Denton2011\" /> James To<!-- Not the Hong Kong legislator -->, a New Zealand political scientist, described ''The Epoch Times'' as the \"primary mouthpiece\" of Falun Gong, writing that it \"lacks credibility\", despite the newspaper posing a \"viable threat to the CCP\" by publishing articles about the party's negative aspects.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=To|first=James|date=December 2012|title=Beijing's Policies for Managing Han and Ethnic-Minority Chinese Communities Abroad|journal=Journal of Current Chinese Affairs|volume=41|pages=183\u2013221|doi=10.1177/186810261204100407|number=4}}</ref> In his book ''Blocked on Weibo: What Gets Suppressed on China's Version of Twitter and Why,'' [[University of Toronto]] [[research fellow]] Jason Q. Ng referred to the paper's coverage of mainland China issues as \"heavily biased against the Communist Party\" and thus its reportage \"should be viewed skeptically.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kHARBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA127|title=Blocked on Weibo: What Gets Suppressed on China's Version of Twitter (And Why)|last=Ng|first=Jason Q.|date=August 27, 2013|publisher=New Press|isbn=9781595588715|page=127}}</ref>\n\nSeth Hettna wrote in ''[[The New Republic]]'' that ''The Epoch Times'' \"has built a global propaganda machine, similar to Russia\u2019s [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] or [[RT (TV network)|RT]], that pushes a mix of alternative facts and conspiracy theories that has won it far-right acolytes around the world.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nJoan Donovan of the [[Shorenstein Center on Media, Politics and Public Policy]] at [[Harvard University]] called ''The Epoch Times'' \"a known [[disinformation]] operation\".<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/social-media/wake-call-iowa-caucus-disinformation-serves-warning-about-2020-election-n1130111|title='Wake-up call': Iowa caucus disinformation serves as warning about 2020 election|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nBen Collins of [[NBC News]] called ''The Epoch Times'' a \"pro-Trump conspiracy website.\"<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nThe paper has also been lauded by some political commentators and media experts. [[Ethan Gutmann]] of the [[Foundation for Defense of Democracies]], a [[Neoconservatism|neoconservative]] think tank, has characterized ''The Epoch Times'' as a leader in political analysis of the Chinese regime, writing: \"With the \"Chinese Regime in Crisis\" series, ''Epoch Times'' has finally and indisputably arrived. Any China expert who wants to save face by pretending the paper doesn't exist can continue to do so\u2014for a little while anyway\u2014but they had better be reading it in secret.\"<ref>Ethan Gutman, Facebook. (23 Apr 2012) [https://www.facebook.com/ethan.gutmann/posts/10150841176268179 Now quoted by the paper]</ref>\n\nJames Bettinger, a professor of Communications at [[Stanford University]] and the director of the John S. Knight Journalism Fellowships, said \"Even if ''Epoch Times'' is not associated with Falun Gong, if they consistently write about Falun Gong in the same perspective, or if there are no articles examining Falun Gong, people would perceive it as being not credible.\"<ref name=\"waves2\">Eugenia Chien, [http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a \"Falun Gong-Linked Media Venture Makes Waves, Raises Questions\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306081937/http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a|date=March 6, 2008}} ''New America Media'', News Analysis, May 16, 2006</ref> Orville Schell, dean of the Graduate School of Journalism at [[University of California, Berkeley]], said in 2005 that \"It's hard to vouch for their quality because it's difficult to corroborate, but it's not something to be dismissed as pure propaganda.\"<ref name=\"sfgate23\"/>\n\nIn his 2008 book on Falun Gong, David Ownby wrote that ''The Epoch Times'' articles are \"well written and interesting, if occasionally idiosyncratic in their coverage.\"<ref name=\"DO2\" /><ref name=\"morais\">Morais, Betsy. \"''The Epoch Times'' doesn't like to brag\", Capital Magazine, Jun. 23, 2010</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://berkleycenter.georgetown.edu/people/david-ownby|title=David Ownby|last=University|first=Berkley Center for Religion, Peace and World Affairs at Georgetown|website=berkleycenter.georgetown.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> According to Ownby, the newspaper has been praised and also criticized for a perceived bias against the CCP, and support of Falun Gong practitioners and other dissidents such as Tibetans, Taiwanese independence advocates, democracy activists, Uyghurs and others. The paper, therefore, is often assessed in light of its connection to Falun Gong, rather than a thorough analysis of its editorial content.<ref>Ownby 2008, pp. ''vii''\u2013''viii'', 163, 221\u20133, 229.</ref>\n\n[[Jiao Guobiao]], a former Beijing University journalism professor who was dismissed after criticizing the [[Publicity Department of the Communist Party of China|Propaganda Department]], proposed that even if ''The Epoch Times'' published only negative information highly critical of the CCP, the weight of their attacks could never begin to counterbalance the positive propaganda the party publishes about itself. In addressing media balance, Jiao noted that the Chinese public lacked negative, critical information regarding their country. As such, he noted for a need of media balance based on the principles of freedom, equality, and legality, and that media balance \"is the result of the collective imbalances of all\".<ref name=\"Thornton2008\" />\n\nIn 2010, ''The Epoch Times'' successfully defended its reporting in the Canadian court system,<ref name=\"Canada2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scc-csc.ca/case-dossier/info/sum-som-eng.aspx?cas=34781|title=Supreme Court of Canada - SCC Case Information - Summary - 34781|last=Canada|first=Supreme Court of|date=2001-01-01|website=www.scc-csc.ca|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref>[http://www.facts.org.cn/reports/world/200805/t80351.htm Facts.org] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005152705/http://www.facts.org.cn/reports/world/200805/t80351.htm|date=October 5, 2011}}, quoting from Xinhua, March 23, 2006 (Retrieved July 23, 2011)</ref> when a publisher it had reported on, Crescent Chau of ''[[Les Presses Chinoises]]'', sued for libel.<ref name=\"straightgood2\">Miller, John Gordon (31 May 2010) [http://www.straightgoods.ca/2010/ViewArticle.cfm?Ref=554 \"Judge rules that Falun Gong newspaper acted in the public interest\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903024152/http://www.straightgoods.ca/2010/ViewArticle.cfm?Ref=554|date=September 3, 2010}} Straight Goods</ref> The Supreme Court of Canada ruled that ''The Epoch Times'' article expressed \"legitimate concerns and constitute an opinion which is drawn from a factual premise.\"<ref name=\"Canada2\" /> In examining the case, John Gordon Miller, a Canadian journalist and media professor, noted that articles in question \"appear to be thoroughly and professionally reported\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thejournalismdoctor.ca/Blog.php/33|title=Blog: Good journalism|last=Ubertor.com|first=John Miller, The Journalism Doctor, Bewdley, Real Estate Website by|website=thejournalismdoctor.ca|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref name=\"straightgood2\" />\n\nHayes Brown of ''[[BuzzFeed News|Buzzfeed News]]'' called ''The Epoch Times'' \"one of the staunchest defenders of [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] presidency.\"<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nU.S. Representative [[Paul Gosar]], Republican of Arizona, called ''The Epoch Times'' \u201cour favorite paper.\u201d<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/technology/epoch-times-youtube.html|title=Epoch Times, Punished by Facebook, Gets a New Megaphone on YouTube|last=Roose|first=Kevin|date=2020-02-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nHaifeng Huang, a professor of political science, said, \"I'm not exactly clear why they have become such a major pro-Trump voice\" but \"part of it is perhaps because they regard President Trump as tough on the Chinese government and therefore a natural ally for them\".<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe web-only, German edition of the paper, ''Epoch Times Deutschland'', has been criticized by media analysts<ref>Notably such media analysts include Bethany Allen-Ebrahimian of ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' magazine and Stefan Winterbauer of Germany's [[:de:Meedia|Meedia]].</ref> for its favorable coverage of far right populist groups such as the [[Alternative for Germany]] and [[Pegida]], both of which proclaim anti-immigrant views, and promotion of skepticism towards mainstream German media and politicians.<ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\" /> A German media report described the outlet, along with [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik News]] and Kopp Report, as a \"favorite\" of Pegida supporters, and found that its articles critical of immigration have been shared almost daily.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nA report by the [[Institute for Strategic Dialogue]], a London-based think tank, said the German edition of ''The Epoch Times'' \"primarily runs anti-West, anti-American and pro-Kremlin content \u2013 a high proportion of this content is based on unverified information.\"<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isdglobal.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Make-Germany-Great-Again-ENG-061217.pdf|title=Make Germany Great Again: Kremlin, Alt-Right and International Influences in the 2017 German Elections|last=|first=|date=2017|website=Institute for Strategic Dialogue|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n*'''2012 Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal'''&nbsp;\u2014 Canadian publisher Cindy Gu of ''The Epoch Times'' was one of about 60,000 recipients awarded this commemorative medal, which honors \"significant contributions and achievements by Canadians.\"<ref>[https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/canadian-honours/directory-honours/queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee-medal Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal] The Governor General of Canada. Retrieved 28 Apr 2013</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients?filter_name=Cindy+Gu |title=Find a Recipient |publisher=The Governor General of Canada|date=June 11, 2018 }}</ref> She was nominated for the medal by the Canadian Centre for Abuse Awareness for raising awareness of human rights abuses in China and the organ harvesting of Falun Gong practitioners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ausepochmedia.com/2016/10/25/epoch-times-publisher-awarded-diamond-jubilee-medal/|title=Epoch Times Publisher Awarded Diamond Jubilee Medal|date=2016-10-25|website=Chinese Newspaper - Perth Epoch Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref>\n*'''2012 National Ethnic Press and Media Council Award'''&nbsp;\u2014The Chinese edition of ''The Epoch Times'' was one of nine newspapers given an award for \"excellence in editorial/free expression, best concept and visual presentation.\"<ref>[https://www.sources.com/Releases/NR1780.htm \"National Ethnic Press and Media Council of Canada Award Recipients 2012\"] sources.com 7 November 2012</ref><ref>''The Epoch Times'' (13 November 2012) [https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/canada/epoch-times-wins-ethnic-press-media-award-in-canada-314136.html ''The Epoch Times'' Wins Ethnic Press Media Award] Retrieved 28 Apr 2013</ref>\n*'''2012 New York Press Association Award'''&nbsp;\u2014 ''The Epoch Times'' won first place in the category \"Best Special Section&nbsp;\u2014 Advertising, Division 2\" for a special section produced for ''Asia Week'' New York in March 2012. \"A great special section has five strong components: a great cover, appealing design, good art, strong content, and well-designed complementary advertising. This section has all five\", said the NYPA judges. \"In all, this is one of the nicest sections I have ever seen produced by a newspaper.\"<ref>[http://www.freeinews.com Free-i-News.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421130806/http://www.freeinews.com/ |date=April 21, 2013}} (8 April 2013) [http://www.freeinews.com/global/epoch-times-wins-newspaper-excellence-award \"''The Epoch Times'' Wins Newspaper Excellence Award\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102140506/http://www.freeinews.com/global/epoch-times-wins-newspaper-excellence-award |date=November 2, 2013}} Retrieved 28 Apr 2013</ref>\n*'''2012 [[Society of Professional Journalists]]' [[Sigma Delta Chi Award]]'''&nbsp;\u2014 ''The Epoch Times'' China reporter Matthew Robertson won this award in the category of Non-Deadline Reporting in newspapers with a circulation of less than 50,000 per day, for a series of articles he wrote on forced, live organ harvesting in China.<ref name=\"SPJ22\">[https://www.spj.org/sdxa12.asp \"2012 Sigma Delta Chi Award Honorees\"], The Society of Professional Journalists, spj.org Accessed 8 Dec. 2014</ref>\n*'''2013 Newswomen's Club Award'''&nbsp;\u2014 ''The Epoch Times'' New York reporter Genevieve Belmaker won a Front Page Award from the Newswomen's Club of New York for reporting on the effects of [[Hurricane Sandy]], in the category of newspapers with a circulation of less than 100,000 per day.<ref>Newswomen's Club of New York [https://www.newswomensclubnewyork.com/2013-front-page-awards/ \"2013 Front Page Award Winners\"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124095018/http://www.newswomensclubnewyork.com/2013-fpa-winners |date=January 24, 2015}} newswomensclubnewyork.com</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*Falun Gong-related groups:\n:*[[New Tang Dynasty Television]]\n:*[[Shen Yun]] Performing Arts\n:*[[Sound of Hope]]\n*''[[World Journal]]''\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Epoch Times}}\n*[https://www.theepochtimes.com/ ''Epoch Times''] {{in lang|en}}\n*[https://epochtimes.com ''Epoch Times''] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[https://www.epochtimes.org.au/ ''Epoch Times''] Australia\n*[https://www.ninecommentaries.com/ \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"]\n\n{{Falun Gong}}\n{{Portal bar|Journalism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Epoch Times, The}}\n[[Category:2000 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Chinese-American culture in New York City]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers (Traditional Chinese)]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers published in Canada]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers published in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:Criticism of journalism]]\n[[Category:Falun Gong]]\n[[Category:Free daily newspapers]]\n[[Category:French-language newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:German-language newspapers published in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Internet-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Media bias controversies]]\n[[Category:Media-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in New York City]]\n[[Category:Non-English-language newspapers published in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:Conservative media in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Newspaper focused on China, based in New York City}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name              = The Epoch Times\n| image             = Epochtimescover.png\n| caption           = Front page of ''The Epoch Times'' New York edition for March 18, 2016\n| type              = International newspaper\n| format            = [[Broadsheet]]\n| owners            = Epoch Media Group\n| founder           = John Tang\n| publisher         = Epoch Media Group\n| foundation        = {{start date and age|2000|5|20}}\n| political         = [[Conservatism]], [[anti-Communism]], [[anti-Socialism]], [[Right-wing populism]]\n| language          = Multiple, mainly Chinese and English\n| headquarters      = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| circulation       = 1,314,375 (2012, unaudited)<ref name=WWdistribution>[http://ads.epochtimes.com/pages/distribution-pricing-newspapers-distribution.htm \"The Epoch Times \u2013 Worldwide distribution\"]. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817010655/http://ads.epochtimes.com/pages/distribution-pricing-newspapers-distribution.htm|date=17 August 2008}} Retrieved 6 March 2014.</ref>\n| sister newspapers =\n| website           = {{URL|https://www.theepochtimes.com/}}\n}}\n'''''The Epoch Times''''' is a multi-language newspaper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2010/06/the-epoch-times-doesnt-like-to-brag-067223|title=The Epoch Times doesn't like to brag|last=Morais|first=Betsy|publisher=[[Politico]]|date=June 23, 2010}}</ref> It was founded in 2000 by John Tang and a group of [[Chinese Americans]] associated with the [[Falun Gong]] spiritual movement.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lawrence|first=Susan V.|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB108190438992282143 |title=Falun Gong Fields Media Weapons |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |date=14 April 2004}}</ref> Though the newspaper is known for general interest topics with a focus on news about China and its [[human rights in China|human rights issues]], it has become known for its support of [[Donald Trump|U.S. President Donald Trump]] and favorable coverage of far-right politicians in Europe; a 2019 report showed it to be the second-largest funder of pro-Trump Facebook advertising after the Trump campaign.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|last=Brown|first=Hayes|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/hayesbrown/epoch-times-trump-administration-falun-gong|title=A Newspaper Banned In China Is Now One Of Trump's Biggest Defenders|work=BuzzFeed News|date=October 23, 2018|access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/a-letter-to-our-readers-regarding-buzzfeeds-reporting-about-the-epoch-times_2697534.html|title=A Letter to Our Readers Regarding BuzzFeed's Reporting About The Epoch Times|date=2018-10-23|website=The Epoch Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=https://popular.info/p/the-epoch-of-social-media|title=The Epoch of Social Media|website=popular.info|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref><ref name=\"NBCNews\"/><ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" /><ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\">{{Cite magazine|url=http://www.chinafile.com/reporting-opinion/media/german-edition-of-falun-gong-affiliated-epoch-times-aligns-far-right |title=The German Edition of Falun Gong's 'Epoch Times' Aligns with the Far Right |first=Bethany |last=Allen-Ebrahimian |publisher=Center on U.S.-China Relations at Asia Society |magazine=China File |date=23 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028135010/http://www.chinafile.com/reporting-opinion/media/german-edition-of-falun-gong-affiliated-epoch-times-aligns-far-right |archive-date=28 October 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BI-facebook\">{{Cite news |title=Aside from the Trump campaign itself, the biggest spender on pro-Trump Facebook ads is reportedly a secretive New York-based newspaper |last=Gilbert |first=Ben |date=August 21, 2019 |newspaper=Business Insider |publisher=Insider Inc. |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/epoch-times-pro-trump-facebook-ads-2019-8 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821030349/https://www.businessinsider.com/epoch-times-pro-trump-facebook-ads-2019-8 |archive-date=21 August 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy}}</ref><ref name=\":3\"/> The newspaper is part of the '''Epoch Media Group''', which also operates [[New Tang Dynasty Television]] (NTD).<ref name=\"NBCNews\"/> The group's news sites and [[YouTube]] channels have spread [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] such as [[QAnon]] and [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vaccination]] propaganda.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/technology/facebook-ads-epoch-times.html|title=Facebook Bans Ads From The Epoch Times|last=Alba|first=Davey|date=2019-08-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/8/23/20830229/epoch-times-facebook-ban-buying-ads-violating-policies-trump-propaganda|title=Epoch Times banned from advertising after sneaking pro-Trump propaganda onto Facebook|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=2019-08-23|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> \n\nFor its articles, the publication draws from a network within China, as well as staff living in the West.<ref name=\"Congressional Research Service2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|title=China and Falun Gong|author=Thomas Lum|date=August 11, 2006|publisher=Congressional Research Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205064042/http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|archivedate=February 5, 2012|df=mdy-all}} <!-- page CRS-8, list of Falun Gong-affiliated media --></ref><ref name=\"sfgate23\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/CULTURE-AND-RELIGION-Dissident-media-linked-to-2587555.php|title=Dissident media linked to Falun Gong / Chinese-language print, broadcast outlets in U.S. are making waves|last=Hua|first=Vanessa|date=December 18, 2005|work=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=December 9, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Schworm_Boston_Globe_12_03_20072\">{{Cite news|url=http://archive.boston.com/news/world/asia/articles/2007/12/03/chinese_american_activists_decry_chinas_communism/|title=Chinese-American activists decry China's communism|first=Peter|last=Schworm|date=December 3, 2007|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> ''The Epoch Times'' has print editions in English, Chinese, and six other languages.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/about-us|title=The Epoch Times - About Us|website=www.theepochtimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref> Fifteen additional languages are published online only. The English edition of ''The Epoch Times'' is sold in broadsheet format Monday to Friday in New York City and Washington, D.C., and weekly across the United States and Canada.<ref name=\":0\" /> A typical issue includes news sections, including Nation, World, Business, Opinion, and Commentary, and lifestyle sections, including Travel, Life & Tradition, Mind & Body, Food, and Puzzles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://printarchive.epochtimes.com/a1/en/region.php?dir=us/nyc|title=Epoch Times: Print Archive: United States: New York City|website=epoch Times|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' has been publishing in Chinese since May 2000. It is either sold or distributed free-of-charge in 35 countries, including various international regional editions. ''The Epoch Times'' websites are blocked in mainland China.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.aim.org/media-monitor/independent-chinese-newspaper-bucks-communists/|title= Independent Chinese Newspaper Bucks Communists|last1= Gossett|first1= Sherrie|date= 15 June 2005|website= aim.org|publisher= Accuracy in Media|access-date= 19 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n''The Epoch Times'' was founded in 2000 by John Tang and other [[Chinese Americans]] associated with the spiritual practice [[Falun Gong]].<ref>|title=\"The Epoch Times\", Falun Gong, and Me|https://www.williamgairdner.ca/the-epoch-times-falun-gong-and-me/</ref> The founders said they were responding to censorship inside China and a lack of international understanding about the Chinese government's repression of Falun Gong.<ref name=\"Congressional Research Service\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|title=China and Falun Gong|author=Thomas Lum|date=August 11, 2006|publisher=Congressional Research Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205064042/http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|archivedate=February 5, 2012|df=mdy-all}}<!-- page CRS-8, list of Falun Gong-affiliated media --></ref><ref>Ownby 2008, p. 223.</ref> In May 2000, the paper was first published in the [[Chinese language]] in New York, with the web launch in August 2000.<ref name=About_Us>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/n3/about-us \"''The Epoch Times'' \u2013 About Us\"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106083455/https://www.theepochtimes.com/n3/about-us |date=November 6, 2016}} theepochtimes.com access-date 6 March 2014</ref>\n\nBy 2003, ''The Epoch Times'' website and group of newspapers had grown into one of the largest Chinese-language news sites and newspaper groups outside China, with local editions in the U.S., Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Japan, Indonesia, Taiwan, Hong Kong, and major Western European countries.<ref name=zhao /> The first English edition launched online in 2003, followed by the New York print edition in 2004.<ref name=About_Us />\n\nIn 2000, ten of ''The Epoch Times'' correspondents were imprisoned in China, but current staff of the Chinese-language edition work in Hong Kong.<ref name=Tenth>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/canada/epoch-times-marks-10-years-in-canada-53136.html |title=Epoch Times Marks 10 Years in Canada|work=Epoch Times|date=March 17, 2011|access-date=July 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[NBC News]], \"little is publicly known about the precise ownership, origins or influences of ''The Epoch Times'',\" and it is loosely organized into several regional [[Nonprofit organization|tax free non-profits]], under the umbrella of the Epoch Media Group, together with [[New Tang Dynasty Television]].<ref name=\"NBCNews\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/trump-qanon-impending-judgment-day-behind-facebook-fueled-rise-epoch-n1044121|title=Trump, QAnon and an impending judgment day: Behind the Facebook-fueled rise of The Epoch Times|author=Brandy Zadrozny and Ben Collins|date=August 20, 2019|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> Its revenue in 2017 was [[United States dollar|US$]]8.1 million, and reported a spending of US$7.2 million.\n\n== Distribution ==\n[[File:Epoch Times Montreal.jpg|thumb|''\u00c9poqueTimes'' headquarters in [[Montreal]]'s [[Chinatown, Montreal|Chinatown]] in 2015]]\nAs of February 2012, 67 ''The Epoch Times'' newspaper editions{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} are published, in print in 11 languages, online in 21 languages.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nIn April 2019, videos and ads from the Epoch Media Group including ''The Epoch Times'' and New Tang Dynasty (NTD) totaled 3 billion views on Facebook, YouTube and Twitter, according to the analytics company Tubular. That ranked it 11th among all video creators, and ahead of any other traditional news publisher, according to NBC News.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" />\n\n== Relationship to Falun Gong ==\n[[Associated Press]] reporter [[Nahal Toosi]] wrote that it is \"technically inaccurate\" to say that the Falun Gong organization owns ''The Epoch Times,'' but many of the newspaper's staffers are Falun Gong practitioners. Toosi noted \"many observers\" have said Falun Gong uses the newspaper for its public relations campaigns,<ref name=\"thepost\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/05/AR2007020500185_pf.html|title=Paper denies representing Falun Gong|newspaper=Washington Post|access-date=4 December 2015}}</ref> and the paper is connected with the group and carries sympathetic coverage of it.<ref name=\"thepost\" /><ref name=\"Groot, Stafford 2012\" /><ref name=Elwood2007>{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=34vGv_HDGG8C&pg=PA217 |page=217 |title=World Religions in America |editor=Jacob Neusner |publisher=Westminster John Knox Press |year=2007 |last=Ellwood |first=Robert S. |last2=Csikszentmihalyi |first2=Mark A. |chapter=East Asian Religions |isbn=9781611640472 |quote=... the ''Epoch Times'', an anticommunist newspaper connected with Falun Gong organization...}}</ref><ref name=Sun2009>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAsB54UlQE8C&pg=PR11 |page=xi |last=Sun |first=Wanning |title=Media and the Chinese Diaspora: Community, Communications and Commerce |publisher=Routledge |year=2009 |isbn=9781134263592 |quote=...the ''Epoch Times''&nbsp;\u2013 a globally circulated pro-Falun Gong, anti-Communist Chinese-language newspaper...}}</ref><ref name=Denton2011>{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ul89eeKHLGEC&pg=PA268 |page=268 |title=Places of Memory in Modern China: History, Politics, and Identity |editor=Marc Andre Matten |last=Denton |first=Kirk A. |chapter=Yan'an as a Site of Memory |publisher=Brill |year=2011 |isbn=9789004219014 |series=Leiden Series in Comparative Historiography |volume=5 |quote=An article in the anti-Communist, Falun Gong ''Epoch Times'' claims, without citing any sources, that Zhang's death was the result of an accident involving opium use.}}</ref>\n\nThe English ''Epoch Times'' chair Stephen Gregory said in 2007: \"It's not a Falun Gong newspaper. Falun Gong is a question of an individual's belief. The paper's not owned by Falun Gong, it doesn't speak for Falun Gong, it doesn't represent Falun Gong. It does cover the persecution of Falun Gong in China.\"<ref name=\"thepost\" /> In 2003 sociologist [[Yuezhi Zhao]] wrote that the paper \"displays an indisputable ideological and organizational affinity with Falun Gong\" and that it strongly emphasizes negative portrayals of the Chinese government and positive portrayals of Falun Gong. Per Zhao, ''Epoch'' portrays itself as neutral, independent, and public-interest oriented.<ref name=\"zhao\" />  \n\nCanadian scholar Clement Tong wrote<ref name=\"Groot, Stafford 2012\">{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lm2tdagEnL4C&pg=PA103 |page=103 |title=The Engaging State: South Australia's Engagement with the Asia-Pacific Region |editor=John Spoehr |editor2=Purnendra Jain |chapter=China and South Australia |publisher=Wakefield Press |year=2012 |isbn=9781743051573 |last=Groot |first=Gerry |last2=Stafford |first2=Glen |quote=In related vein, another paper with wide distribution but published elsewhere is ''The Epoch Times'' (Dajiyuan shibao), the qigong meditation religious group Falun gong mouth-piece, which runs a strong anti-communist line.}}</ref><ref name=\"Thornton2008\">{{Cite book |title=Popular Protest in China |last=Thornton |first=Patricia M. |editor=Kevin J. O'Brien |pages=199\u2013200 |chapter=Manufacturing Dissent in Transnational China |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=9780674041585 |year=2008 |series=Harvard Contemporary China |volume=15}}</ref><ref name=\"Tong2015\">{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kpHvCgAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA71 |page=71 |editor=Jean-Guy A. Goulet |editor2=Liam D. Murphy |editor3=Anastasia Panagakos |last=Tong |first=Clement |title=Religious Diversity Today: Experiencing Religion in the Contemporary World |chapter=Western Apocalyptic Narratives in the International Arena |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2015 |isbn=9781440833328 |volume=3}}</ref><ref name=\"James Jiann Hua To, 2014\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KGe7AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA197 |page=97 |title=Qiaowu: Extra-Territorial Policies for the Overseas Chinese |author=James Jiann Hua To |publisher=Brill |year=2014 |isbn=9789004272286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Noakes |first=Stephen |title=Falun Gong, Ten Years On |date=June 2010 |journal=Pacific Affairs |volume=83 |number=2 |pages=349\u201357 |quote=The Epoch Times newspaper also serves as a mouthpiece for Falun Gong internationally...|doi= 10.5509/2010832349}}</ref> ''The Epoch Times'' \"operates as a mouthpiece for\" Falun Gong without an official statement of affiliation with the movement.<ref name=\"Tong2015\" /> In 2008, David Ownby, director of the Center for East Asian Studies at the [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]] and the author of ''Falun Gong and the Future of China'', said the newspaper is set up by Falun Gong practitioners with their own money.<ref name=\"Ownby 2008 p.223\" /> He describes ''The Epoch Times'' as wishing to be taken seriously as a global newspaper rather than being judged on the basis of its strong association with Falun Gong.<ref name=\"Ownby 2008 p.223\">{{Cite book |last=Ownby |first=David |title=Falun Gong and the Future of China |year=2008 |url=https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb/page/223 223] |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199716371}}</ref><ref name=\"Ownby 2008 p.8\">{{Cite book |last=Ownby |first=David |title=Falun Gong and the Future of China |year=2008 |url=https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb/page/8 8] |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199716371}}</ref> He wrote: \"''Epoch Times'' is a newspaper with a mission, that of reporting on issues bearing on human rights throughout the world, which allows for considerable focus on China and Falun Gong.\"<ref name=\"DO2\">Ownby 2008, p. 221.</ref> The paper's reporting on Chinese affairs often highlights negative news about the Chinese government, and covers Falun Gong in a sympathetic light. The paper is seen to articulate Falun Gong's views on a range of issues, and may be part of a ''de facto'' media alliance with democracy activists in exile.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Couldry|first=Nick|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yRVtAAAAQBAJ|title=Contesting Media Power: Alternative Media in a Networked World|last2=Curran|first2=James|date=2003-09-22|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=9780742575202}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, [[Li Hongzhi]], the founder of Falun Gong, appeared at the newspaper's office in New York City and called for the expansion of ''The Epoch Times'' to \"become regular media\". Former employees also noted the involvement of Falun Gong practitioners in the management and editorial process.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /> Three anonymous former employees said ''Epoch Times'' workers were encouraged to attend weekly \"Fa study\" sessions outside work hours to study the teachings of Li Hongzhi.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n''The Epoch Times'' runs frequent promotional stories about the [[Shen Yun]] dance troupe that is affiliated with Falun Gong. ''The New Yorker'''s review of Shen Yun called ''The Epoch Times'' \"the world\u2019s foremost purveyor of Shen Yun content.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/stepping-into-the-uncanny-unsettling-world-of-shen-yun|title=Stepping Into the Uncanny, Unsettling World of Shen Yun|last=Tolentino|first=Jia|date=2019-03-19|access-date=2019-08-24|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, an [[NBC News]] investigative report suggested ''The Epoch Times's'' political coverage may be affected by Falun Gong believers' anticipation of a judgment day in which communists are sent to hell, and Falun Gong's allies are spared. Former ''Epoch Times''' employees told NBC News that President Donald Trump is viewed as a key anti-communist ally,<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /> allegedly \"hastening judgement day and the delivery of communists to hell.\"<ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\">{{cite news |last1=Zadrozny |first1=Brandy |last2=Collins |first2=Ben |title=Facebook bans ads from The Epoch Times after huge pro-Trump buy |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/23/facebook-bans-ads-from-the-epoch-times-after-huge-pro-trump-buy.html |accessdate=7 October 2019 |agency=CNBC |date=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notable coverage ==\n=== Organ harvesting in China ===\n{{Further|Persecution of Falun Gong#Organ harvesting |Organ harvesting from Falun Gong practitioners in China}}\nIn March 2006, ''The Epoch Times'' published the allegations of three Chinese individuals who said that thousands of [[Falun Gong]] practitioners had been killed to supply China's organ transplant industry,<ref>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/worse-than-any-nightmarejournalist-quits-china-to-expose-concentration-camp-horrors-and-bird-flu-coverup_1732938.html \"Worse Than Any Nightmare\u2014Journalist Quits China to Expose Concentration Camp Horrors and Bird Flu Coverup\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207185741/http://en.epochtimes.com/news/6-3-10/39111.html |date=February 7, 2009}}, Epoch Times, 10 March 2006</ref><ref>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/news/6-3-17/39405.html \"New Witness Confirms Existence of Chinese Concentration Camp, Says Organs Removed from Live Victims\"] ''The Epoch Times'', 17 March 2006</ref><ref name=36cc /> including a doctor, who said there were 36 concentration camps all over China.<ref name=36cc>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/news/6-3-31/39910.html \"Source Reveals Other Chinese Concentration Camps\"] ''The Epoch Times'', 31 March 2006</ref> The [[Kilgour\u2013Matas report]]<ref name=orgharv>[[David Kilgour]], [[David Matas]] (6 July 2006, revised 31 January 2007) [http://organharvestinvestigation.net \"An Independent Investigation into Allegations of Organ Harvesting of Falun Gong Practitioners in China\"] (in 22 languages) organharvestinvestigation.net</ref> stated that \"the source of 41,500 transplants for the six year period 2000 to 2005 is unexplained\" and \"we believe that there has been and continues today to be large scale organ seizures from unwilling [[Falun Gong]] practitioners\".<ref name=orgharv /> Appendix 16 of the revised report refuted [[Harry Wu]]'s negative comments.<ref name=orgharv />\n\nIn 2008, two United Nations Special Rapporteurs reiterated their requests for \"the Chinese government to fully explain the allegation of taking vital organs from Falun Gong practitioners and the source of organs for the sudden increase in organ transplants that has been going on in China since the year 2000\".<ref>[http://www.theinformationdaily.com/2008/05/09/united-nations-human-rights-special-rapporteurs-reiterate-findings-on-chinas-organ-harvesting-from-falun-gong-practitioners \"United Nations Human Rights Special Rapporteurs Reiterate Findings on China's Organ Harvesting from Falun Gong Practitioners\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512183828/http://www.theinformationdaily.com/2008/05/09/united-nations-human-rights-special-rapporteurs-reiterate-findings-on-chinas-organ-harvesting-from-falun-gong-practitioners |date=May 12, 2015}}, The Information Daily.com, 9 May 2008</ref> The Chinese government has consistently denied the allegations. The Foreign Affairs Subcommittee of the [[United States House of Representatives]] has adopted resolutions condemning alleged organ harvesting from Falun Gong prisoners of conscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-resolution/343/text |title=H.Res.343 \u2013 Expressing concern regarding persistent and credible reports of systematic, state-sanctioned organ harvesting from non-consenting prisoners of conscience in the People's Republic of China, including from large numbers of Falun Gong practitioners and members of other religious and ethnic minority groups. |author=Ileana Ros-Lehtinen |date=25 June 2015 |publisher=Library of Congress |access-date=20 December 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122222318/https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-resolution/343/text |archivedate=November 22, 2016 |url-status=live |website=congress.gov |df=mdy}}</ref>\n\n=== Other reports ===\nDuring the 2009 [[New York City Comptroller]] elections, ''The Epoch Times'' alleged that [[Taiwan]]-born [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee [[John Liu]] is part of a \"United Front\" by the [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] (CCP) to infiltrate the United States and subvert its government, democracy, and human rights in general.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/content/view/22317/ |title=Chinese Communist Party Subverts Democracies and Rights Abroad |work=The Epoch Times |date=September 10, 2009 |access-date=December 18, 2009}}</ref> The newspaper alleged that \"the CCP works tenaciously and systematically to place its people [...] in key positions in corporations, academia, and government in the United States and other countries.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/content/view/22292/|title=Editor's Note on Coverage of John Liu: Uncovering a hidden threat|date=September 10, 2009}}</ref> ''The Epoch Times'' also published an 8-page \"special edition\", and also featured on its website a section focused on coverage of Liu's reported ties with CCP officials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/component/option,com_ettopic/topicid,57/ |title=John Liu and the United Front |work=The Epoch Times |access-date=December 18, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Hu Jintao]]'s visit to Canada in June 2010, the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' noted that ''The Epoch Times'' had published several \"hard-hitting\" critical stories on Hu's visit, such as allegations of the local Chinese embassy's orchestration of welcome parades, as well as an alleged recording of a speech by the first secretary of education Liu Shaohua, in which Liu stated that embassy would provide accommodation and transport for over 3,000 participants in the welcome parade.<ref name=star>Susan Delacourt, [https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/827903--harper-helps-hu-keep-critics-away \"Harper helps Hu keep critics away\"], thestar.com 25 Jun 2010</ref>\n\nCanadian media reported that the parliamentary press office made deliberate arrangements in relation to Hu's public appearances limiting ''The Epoch Times''{{'}} access to the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], even though the newspaper is an accredited member of the Canadian Parliamentary Press Gallery.<ref name=star /> The paper carried an exclusive interview with outspoken Canadian Member of Parliament [[Rob Anders]], wherein Anders alleged that the Chinese government used gifts and business deals in attempts to influence Canadian political decisions.<ref name='Secrecy'>{{Cite news |first=Norma |last=Greenaway |title=Liberals decry secrecy around CSIS report |date=August 3, 2010 |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/Liberals+decry+secrecy+around+CSIS+report/3355144/story.html |work=Vancouver Sun |access-date=2012-05-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100805081220/http://www.vancouversun.com/news/Liberals+decry+secrecy+around+CSIS+report/3355144/story.html |archivedate=2010-08-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vancourier.com/Chinese+Canadian+leader+laments+agency+allegations/3337835/story.html |title=Chinese-Canadian leader laments spy agency allegations |publisher=[[Vancouver Courier]] |date=July 29, 2010 |access-date=2012-05-25}}</ref>\n\nA story in ''The Epoch Times'' on February 17, 2020 shared a map from the internet that falsely alleged massive sulfur dioxide releases from crematoriums during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] in China, speculating that 14,000 bodies may have been burned.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/map-forecast-based-past-data-not-real-time-satellite-readings|title=This map is a forecast based on past data, not real-time satellite readings|date=2020-02-20|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epochtimes.com/b5/20/2/17/n11875579.htm|title=\u6b66\u6f22\u4e8c\u6c27\u5316\u786b\u7206\u8868 \u53f0\u5b78\u8005\uff1a\u71d2\u5c4d\u9ad4\u662f\u5408\u7406\u63a8\u65b7 - \u5927\u7d00\u5143|date=2020-02-17|website=\u5927\u7d00\u5143 www.epochtimes.com|language=zh-TW|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref> A fact check by [[Agence France-Presse|AFP]] reported that the map was a NASA forecast taken out of context.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== Editorial stance ==\nThe editorial stance of ''The Epoch Times'' is generally considered [[anti-communism|anti-communist]], specifically opposing the [[Communist Party of China]].<ref name=\"Thornton2008\" />\n\nIn recent years, the newspaper has also been noted for favorable coverage of the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]], [[far-right politics in Germany|the German far right]], and the [[History of far-right movements in France|French far right]].<ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\" /><ref name=\":12\">[https://meedia.de/2016/03/18/kopp-sputnik-epoch-times-co-nachrichten-aus-einem-rechten-paralleluniversum/ Kopp, Sputnik, Epoch Times & Co: Nachrichten aus einem rechten Paralleluniversum] Stefan Winterbauer, Meedia. March 13, 2016</ref><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/155076/obscure-newspaper-fueling-far-right-europe|title=The Obscure Newspaper Fueling the Far-Right in Europe|last=Hettena|first=Seth|date=2019-09-17|work=The New Republic|access-date=2019-12-16|issn=0028-6583}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a report by NBC News, ''The Epoch Times'' \"generally stayed out of U.S. politics\" before 2016, \"unless they dovetailed with Chinese interests.\" Ben Hurley, a former ''Epoch Times'' employee until 2013, told NBC News that the newspaper was critical toward abortion and LGBT, and that Falun Gong practitioners \"saw communism everywhere\" including in internationalist figures like [[Hillary Clinton]] and [[Kofi Annan]], \"but there was more room for disagreements in the early days.\" Since 2016, according to NBC News, ''The Epoch Times'' has promoted favorable coverage of [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] campaign and presidency, and emphasized issues such as [[Islamic terrorism]] and [[illegal immigration to the United States]]. It has also emphasized \"what the publication claims is a labyrinthian, global conspiracy led by [Hillary] Clinton and former President Barack Obama to tear down Trump.\"<ref name=\"NBCNews\" />\n\nThe newspaper counters what it considers to be Chinese Communist Party propaganda through its own opinion pieces and reporting. It covers causes and groups opposed to the CCP, including Falun Gong, dissidents, activists, and supporters of the [[Central Tibetan Administration|Tibetan government-in-exile]]. The paper also reports on Falun Gong-related news, including the group's attempt to sue former [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Communist Party general secretary]] [[Jiang Zemin]] under civil legislation for \"[[genocide]]\", not covered by most other overseas Chinese-language newspapers.<ref name=\"sfgate2\">{{Cite news|url= https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/CULTURE-AND-RELIGION-Dissident-media-linked-to-2587555.php|title= Dissident media linked to Falun Gong / Chinese-language print, broadcast outlets in U.S. are making waves|work= San Francisco Chronicle|date= December 18, 2005|access-date= December 9, 2006|first= Vanessa|last= Hua}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper is also at odds with the [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]]-owned newspaper ''[[World Journal]]'', accusing it of being a \"megaphone for the evil Chinese Communist Party\".<ref name= \"HPheartsandmind\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/chinese-press-abroad_n_4729474|title=The Chinese Press Battles For Hearts And Minds Abroad|date=February 13, 2014|website=HuffPost Canada}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epochtimes.com/gb/14/1/24/n4067175.htm|title=\u65e7\u91d1\u5c71\u6cd5\u8f6e\u529f\u5b66\u5458\u81f4\u4e16\u754c\u65e5\u62a5\u7684\u516c\u5f00\u4fe1 - \u5927\u7eaa\u5143|date=January 24, 2014|website=\u5927\u7eaa\u5143 www.epochtimes.com}}</ref>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' is known for alleging [[conspiracy|conspiracies]] against former [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Communist Party general secretary]] [[Jiang Zemin]],<ref name= \"HPheartsandmind\" /> under whose administration Falun Gong was suppressed in China.\n\nIn 2005, the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' reported that \"three new U.S.-based, Chinese-language media outlets that provide provocative reporting about the Communist Party, government oppression and social unrest in China [namely ''The Epoch Times'', Sound of Hope, and NTDTV] have ties to the Falun Gong spiritual movement.\" When interviewed, executives at each outlet claimed they did not represent the Falun Gong movement as a whole.<ref name=\"sfgate2\" />\n\n''The Epoch Times'' also picks up mainstream [[News agency|newswire]] stories and in some places can resemble a community newspaper.<ref name=\"waves\">Eugenia Chien, [http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a \"Falun Gong-Linked Media Venture Makes Waves, Raises Questions\"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306081937/http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a |date=March 6, 2008}} ''New America Media'', News Analysis, May 16, 2006</ref> According to sociologist [[Yuezhi Zhao|Zhao Yuezhi]], \"While mainstream newspaper typically treat Web versions as an extension of the already-existing print version, ''The Epoch Times'' website serves as the master for all its worldwide papers.\"<ref name=\"zhao\">Zhao, Yuezhi, \"Falun Gong, Identity, and the Struggle over Meaning Inside and Outside China\", pp 209\u2013223 in ''Contesting Media Power: Alternative Media in a Networked World'', edited by Nick Couldry and James Curran (Rowman & Littlefield, 2003)</ref>\n\nIn some cases ''The Epoch Times'' operates in a hostile overseas environment, in which \"overseas Chinese media companies choosing to remain independent or publish non-approved content become the targets of an aggressive campaign of elimination or control.\" In one instance Chinese diplomatic officials made threats against media for reporting Falun Gong-related content; in other cases, advertisers have been regularly threatened not to support ''The Epoch Times'' in any way. Communist Party authorities have been accused of resorting to \"militant methods\" against the newspaper and its staff, including attacking staff and destroying computer equipment.<ref>{{Cite book|title= Qiaowu: Extra-Territorial Policies for the Overseas Chinese|last= To|first= James Jiann Hua|publisher= BRILL|year= 2014|isbn= 9789004272286|location= |pages= 180}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper reported that in 2005 the Communist Party \"exerted hard and soft pressure\" on printing houses in Hong Kong, forcing the paper to stop printing, after it reported on Tibet, human rights, Falun Gong, and was the first media to break the story on [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]].<ref>{{Cite book|title= Taiwan: The Threatened Democracy|last= Herschensohn|first= Bruce|publisher= WND Books|year= 2006|isbn= 9780977898428|location= |pages= 99}}</ref> The newspaper was also briefly banned from Malaysia after coming under reported pressure by the Chinese Communist Party.<ref name=Sun2009 />\n\nIn 2016, the newspaper was removed from the pharmacy of [[Australian National University]], after the president of the [[Chinese Students and Scholars Association]] confronted the pharmacist and threw out the papers. The incident drew national media coverage over questions of Chinese government sponsored overseas student organizations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/education/the-patriotic-education-of-chinese-students-at-australian-universities-20161003-gru13j.html|title=The 'patriotic education' of Chinese students at Australian universities|last=Wen|first=Alexander Joske and Philip|date=2016-10-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/world/asia/canberra-pharmacy-at-front-line-of-chinas-push-for-global-influence-20160901-gr65xy|title=Canberra pharmacy at front line of China's push for global influence|date=2016-09-01|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, The German edition of the newspaper, ''The Epoch Times Deutschland'', which became Web-only in 2012, was accused by online magazine ''The China File'' of being aligned with the German far-right, and attractive to supporters of the [[Alternative for Germany]] (AfD) party and the anti-immigrant group [[Pegida]].<ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\" />  Stefanie Albrecht, a reporter for the German broadcaster RTL who spent several days inside the Berlin office of ''The Epoch Times'' while investigating the far right, said that ''The Epoch Times'' staffers she met had no journalistic training and didn't check facts, trusting instead in the alternative sources they consulted.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn [[France]], ''The Epoch TImes'' gives \"an unfettered platform to [[Jean-Marie Le Pen]], the patriarch of the French far right, and his daughter, [[Marine Le Pen|Marine]], who leads the nationalist party her father founded,\" according to ''[[The New Republic]]''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Trump administration ==\nAccording to ''[[BuzzFeed News]]'', ''The Epoch Times'' is known as \"one of the staunchest defenders of [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Donald Trump's presidency]].\"<ref name=\":22\" /> The paper has championed Trump's [[Spygate (conspiracy theory)|Spygate conspiracy theory]] in its news coverage and advertising, and the Epoch Media Group's ''Edge of Wonder'' videos on YouTube have spread the right-wing, pro-Trump [[QAnon|QAnon conspiracy theory]].<ref name=\"NBCNews\" />\n\nThe ''Edge of Wonder'' hosts, according to ''[[The Daily Dot]]'', \"embrace QAnon completely\" even though \"almost nothing QAnon has foretold has actually taken place.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/layer8/edge-wonder-qanon-youtube/|title=This massive YouTube channel is normalizing QAnon|date=2019-08-27|website=The Daily Dot|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> An NBC News report found that the ''Edge of Wonder'' hosts have been creative director and chief photo editor at ''The Epoch Times,'' and the newspaper promoted ''Edge of Wonder'' videos in dozens of Facebook posts through 2019.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /> The hosts and the newspaper's publisher deny that they are currently affiliated.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/our-response-to-nbc-news-inappropriate-questions_2971493.html|title=Our Response to NBC News' Inappropriate Questions|last=|first=|date=|work=The Epoch Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edgeofwonder.tv/about|title=Edge of Wonder|website=edgeofwonder.tv|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn a response to a ''BuzzFeed'' report about ''The Epoch Times''' coverage of Trump, ''The Epoch Times'' editor-in-chief Jasper Fakkert wrote in a letter to readers: \"We see the Trump administration's efforts to change socialist policies in America, as well as set policies to counter infiltration and subversion by China, as remarkable reversals from past policies, and sincere efforts that, if fully realized, will benefit America and the world as a whole.\"<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":32\" />\n\nIn April 2018, ''The Epoch Times'' publisher Stephen Gregory and editor-in-chief Jasper Fakkert reported a third-hand claim that [[Donald Trump]] reads ''The Epoch Times'' every day and \"it's the one newspaper that he believes to be a truthful and correct paper.\"<ref name=\":22\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/trump-said-to-describe-the-epoch-times-as-most-credible-newspaper_2495714.html|title=Trump Said to Describe The Epoch Times as 'Most Credible Newspaper'|date=2018-04-16|website=The Epoch Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, ''The Epoch Times'' photographer Samira Bouaou broke White House protocol and handed Trump a folder during an official event.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/white-house-reviews-incident-involving-epoch-times-photographer-handing-a-folder-to-trump/2018/09/18/e9d8b8ba-bac5-11e8-bdc0-90f81cc58c5d_story.html|title=White House reviews incident involving ''The Epoch Times'' photographer handing a folder to Trump|last=Nakamura|first=David|date=September 18, 2018|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919014513/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/white-house-reviews-incident-involving-epoch-times-photographer-handing-a-folder-to-trump/2018/09/18/e9d8b8ba-bac5-11e8-bdc0-90f81cc58c5d_story.html?tid=pm_politics_pop|archive-date=September 19, 2018|last2=Shih|first2=Gerry|quote=The photographer, identified by other photojournalists as Samira Bouaou, passed the purple-colored folder to Trump as he was walking out of the East Room on Sept. 12 after delivering remarks at a reception for the Congressional Medal of Honor Society.}}</ref>\n\nDuring the February 2020 [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|Iowa Democratic Caucuses]], ''The Epoch Times'' shared viral [[disinformation]] from the conservative group [[Judicial Watch]] that falsely alleged inflated voter rolls.<ref name=\":8\" /> The claim, which went viral on Facebook, was debunked by fact checkers and the Iowa secretary of state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/live-blog/iowa-caucuses-live-updates-2020-democrats-make-their-final-pitches-n1128596/ncrd1128966|title=Debunked claims about Iowa voter fraud pushed by conservative activists|last=Brandy Zadrozny26d ago / 8:32 PM UTC|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/iowa-misinformation-spreads-online-despite-new-policies/|title=Iowa Misinformation Spreads Online, Despite New Policies|work=Wired|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref> A Harvard media expert quoted by NBC News said ''The Epoch Times'' employed a \"classic disinformation tactic\" known as \"trading up the chain,\" in which false stories are repackaged and shared.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Advertising controversies ===\n\n==== Ad ban on Facebook ====\nDuring a six month period in 2019, ''The Epoch Times'' spent more than $1.5 million on about 11,000 Facebook ads that NBC News said were \"pro-Trump advertisements\". NBC said the amount spent was more than any group except the Trump campaign itself.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref name=\"BI-facebook\" /> Political ad spending on Facebook in April 2019 through an account called \"Coverage of the Trump Presidency by The Epoch Times\" exceeded any politician's spending except Trump and Democrat [[Joe Biden]].<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\"FWIW: Where are they now\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anotheracronym.org/newsletter/where-are-they-now/|title=FWIW: Where are they now?|website=ACRONYM|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Journalist [[Judd Legum]] wrote in May 2019 that ''The Epoch Times'' ads were \"boosting Donald Trump and floating conspiracy theories about Joe Biden\".<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\"FWIW: Where are they now\" />\n\nIn August 2019, [[Facebook]] banned ''The Epoch Times'' from advertising on its platform, after finding that the newspaper broke Facebook's political transparency rules by publishing pro-Trump subscription ads through [[Sockpuppet (Internet)|sockpuppet]] pages such as \u201cHonest Paper\u201d and \u201cPure American Journalism.\"<ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> A Facebook representative told NBC: \"Over the past year we removed accounts associated with ''The Epoch Times'' for violating our ad policies, including trying to get around our review systems.\" <ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" />\n\n''The Epoch Times'' publisher, Stephen Gregory, wrote in response that the paper didn't intend to violate Facebook's rules. The video ads, he wrote, \"are overtly ''Epoch Times'' advertisements for our subscriptions,\u201d and \"discuss ''The Epoch Times''\u2019 editorial and feature content and encourage people to subscribe to our print newspaper.\"<ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/epoch-times-statement-in-response-to-nbc-facebook-stories_3053492.html|title=Epoch Times Statement in Response to NBC Facebook Stories|date=2019-08-23|website=www.theepochtimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\n==== Removal of ''The BL'' on Facebook ====\nIn October 2019, the fact-checking website [[Snopes]] reported that ''The Epoch Times'' is closely linked to a large network of Facebook pages and groups called ''The BL'' (''The Beauty of Life'') that shares pro-Trump views and conspiracy theories such as [[QAnon]]. ''The BL'' has spent at least $510,698 on Facebook advertising. Hundreds of the ads were removed for violations of Facebook's advertising rules. The ''BL'' network of pages has 28 million followers on Facebook in total, according to ''Snopes''. The editor-in-chief of ''The BL'' recently worked as editor-in-chief of ''The Epoch Times,'' and several other ''BL'' employees are listed as current or former employees of ''The Epoch Times''. ''The BL'' is registered in [[Middletown, Orange County, New York|Middletown]], [[New York (state)|New York]], to an address that also is registered to Falun Gong's ''Sound of Hope Radio Network'' and is associated with the YouTube series ''Beyond Science,'' but Snopes found \"the outlet as a whole is literally the English-language edition of ''Epoch Times'' Vietnam.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/10/11/pro-trump-outlet-linked-epoch-times/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Expanding Pro-Trump Outlet 'The BL' Is Closely Linked to The Epoch Times|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/12/13/facebook-bl-cib/|title=If Facebook Is Dealing with Deceptive 'BL' Network, It's Not Working|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> Snopes found that''The BL'' uses more than 300 fake Facebook profiles based in Vietnam and other countries, using names, stock photos and celebrity photos in their profiles to emulate Americans, to administer more than 150 pro-Trump Facebook groups amplifying its content.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/11/12/bl-fake-profiles/|title=How a Pro-Trump Network Is Building a Fake Empire on Facebook and Getting Away with It|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\nAn unnamed representative of ''The BL'' wrote to ''Snopes'' that \u201cThe BL has NO connection with ''The Epoch Times'',\" and a \"few of our staff has job experience \u2026 working in ''The Epoch Times'', but now they are working full time in The BL.\u201d ''The Epoch Times''\u2019 publisher, Stephen Gregory, said \u201c''The Epoch Times'' is not affiliated with the BL.\u201d <ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn December 2019, Facebook announced it removed a large network of accounts, pages, and groups linked to The BL and Epoch Media Group for coordinated inauthentic behavior on behalf of a foreign actor. The network had 55 million followers on Facebook and Instagram, and $9.5 million had been spent on Facebook ads through its accounts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://about.fb.com/news/2019/12/removing-coordinated-inauthentic-behavior-from-georgia-vietnam-and-the-us/|title=Removing Coordinated Inauthentic Behavior From Georgia, Vietnam and the US|date=2019-12-20|website=About Facebook|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\nOn December 20, 2019, ''The New York Times'' reported, in \"Facebook Discovers Fakes That Show Evolution of [[Fake news|Disinformation]]\", that Facebook had deleted \"hundreds of accounts with ties to the Epoch Media Group, parent company of the Falun Gong-related publication and conservative news outlet ''The Epoch Times''\" using fake profile photos that had been generated using [[artificial intelligence]]. The [[Atlantic Council#The Digital Forensic Research Lab (DFRLab)|Atlantic Council Digital Forensic Research Lab]] (DFRLab) director Graham Brookie stated that the coordinated network of fake accounts demonstrated \"an eerie, tech-enabled future of disinformation\". Facebook's head of security policy, Nathaniel Gleicher, said, \"What\u2019s new here is that this is purportedly a U.S.-based media company leveraging foreign actors posing as Americans to push political content. We\u2019ve seen it a lot with state actors in the past.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/20/business/facebook-ai-generated-profiles.html?ribbon-ad-idx=2&rref=business|title=Facebook Discovers Fakes That Show Evolution of Disinformation|website=The New York Times|language=en|date=2019-12-20|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/facebook-says-pro-trump-media-outlet-used-artificial-intelligence-create-n1105951|title=Facebook says a pro-Trump media outlet used artificial intelligence to create fake people and push conspiracies|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n==== YouTube ads ====\nAs Facebook banned ''The Epoch Times'' from advertising, the newspaper shifted its spending to [[YouTube]]. ''The Epoch Times'' has spent more than $1 million on YouTube ads, some promoting conspiracy theories,''The New York Times'' reported in February 2020.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Editorials ==\n=== Nine commentaries on the Communist Party ===\nIn November 2004, the Chinese version of ''The Epoch Times'' published a series of editorials titled \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"<ref name=9com>[http://www.ninecommentaries.com/english \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"] ninecommentaries.com/english</ref> ({{Lang-zh|t=\u4e5d\u8a55\u5171\u7522\u9ee8|s=\u4e5d\u8bc4\u5171\u4ea7\u515a|first=t|links=no}}). The editorials detail what ''The Epoch Times'' characterizes as the CCP's violent political campaigns throughout its history, from its ascent to power under [[Mao Zedong]] to its present-day form. The CCP is criticized as an illegitimate institution that used underhanded tactics to gain power. The commentaries allege that the CCP \"destroyed traditional Chinese culture\" and call the CCP an \"evil cult\".<ref>{{Cite web|author=The Epoch Times Dec 26, 2004 |url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/commentary-8-on-how-the-chinese-communist-party-is-an-evil-cult_3950.html |title=Part 8: On How the Chinese Communist Party Is an Evil Cult |work=The Epoch Times |date=December 26, 2004 |access-date=December 18, 2009}}</ref> According to China scholar David Ownby, the Nine Commentaries are a \"condemnation of communism and a direct indictment of the legitimacy of the Chinese Communist Party's rule in China\". While acknowledging the \"unnecessary violence\" the Chinese Communist Party has inflicted, Ownby finds that the lack of balance and nuance in tone and style makes the editorials resemble \"anti-Communist propaganda written in Taiwan in the 1950s.\"<ref name=\"DO2\" />\n\nThe Nine Commentaries have been translated into more than 30 other languages<ref name=9com /> and released as a DVD.<ref name=9comDVD>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s8oaUepvc70 \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"] NTDTV youtube.com</ref>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' website hosts a \"CCP Renunciations\" service, encouraging Chinese people to quit the CCP and its related organizations. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tuidang.epochtimes.com/|title=\u5927\u7eaa\u5143\u9000\u515a\u7f51\u7ad9|website=tuidang.epochtimes.com|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref> The Chinese edition of the newspaper publishes the number of people who it claims have quit.\n\n== Assessments ==\nAccording to Ming Xia, political science professor at the Graduate Center at the City University of New York, ''The Epoch Times'' represents part of Falun Gong's effort to expand to non-practitioners, and \"is part of the Falun Gong strategy to embed itself into the large civil society for influence and legitimacy\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.religionnewsblog.com/17386/epoch-times|title=Paper denies representing Falun Gong|date=February 5, 2007|publisher=Religionnewsblog.com|access-date=6 March 2014}}</ref> He described ''The Epoch Times'' staff as largely part-time and volunteer, and said they \"do not follow the protocols professional journalists abide by.\"<ref name=\":5\"/>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' has been criticized by some scholars for biases, particularly regarding the Chinese Communist Party and mainland China issues, as well as for being a \"mouthpiece\" of the [[Falun Gong]] movement.<ref name=\"Groot, Stafford 2012\" /><ref name=\"Thornton2008\" /><ref name=\"James Jiann Hua To, 2014\" /><ref name=\"Elwood2007\" /><ref name=\"Sun2009\" /><ref name=\"Denton2011\" /> James To<!-- Not the Hong Kong legislator -->, a New Zealand political scientist, described ''The Epoch Times'' as the \"primary mouthpiece\" of Falun Gong, writing that it \"lacks credibility\", despite the newspaper posing a \"viable threat to the CCP\" by publishing articles about the party's negative aspects.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=To|first=James|date=December 2012|title=Beijing's Policies for Managing Han and Ethnic-Minority Chinese Communities Abroad|journal=Journal of Current Chinese Affairs|volume=41|pages=183\u2013221|doi=10.1177/186810261204100407|number=4}}</ref> In his book ''Blocked on Weibo: What Gets Suppressed on China's Version of Twitter and Why,'' [[University of Toronto]] [[research fellow]] Jason Q. Ng referred to the paper's coverage of mainland China issues as \"heavily biased against the Communist Party\" and thus its reportage \"should be viewed skeptically.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kHARBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA127|title=Blocked on Weibo: What Gets Suppressed on China's Version of Twitter (And Why)|last=Ng|first=Jason Q.|date=August 27, 2013|publisher=New Press|isbn=9781595588715|page=127}}</ref>\n\nSeth Hettna wrote in ''[[The New Republic]]'' that ''The Epoch Times'' \"has built a global propaganda machine, similar to Russia\u2019s [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] or [[RT (TV network)|RT]], that pushes a mix of alternative facts and conspiracy theories that has won it far-right acolytes around the world.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nJoan Donovan of the [[Shorenstein Center on Media, Politics and Public Policy]] at [[Harvard University]] called ''The Epoch Times'' \"a known [[disinformation]] operation\".<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/social-media/wake-call-iowa-caucus-disinformation-serves-warning-about-2020-election-n1130111|title='Wake-up call': Iowa caucus disinformation serves as warning about 2020 election|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nBen Collins of [[NBC News]] called ''The Epoch Times'' a \"pro-Trump conspiracy website.\"<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nThe paper has also been lauded by some political commentators and media experts. [[Ethan Gutmann]] of the [[Foundation for Defense of Democracies]], a [[Neoconservatism|neoconservative]] think tank, has characterized ''The Epoch Times'' as a leader in political analysis of the Chinese regime, writing: \"With the \"Chinese Regime in Crisis\" series, ''Epoch Times'' has finally and indisputably arrived. Any China expert who wants to save face by pretending the paper doesn't exist can continue to do so\u2014for a little while anyway\u2014but they had better be reading it in secret.\"<ref>Ethan Gutman, Facebook. (23 Apr 2012) [https://www.facebook.com/ethan.gutmann/posts/10150841176268179 Now quoted by the paper]</ref>\n\nJames Bettinger, a professor of Communications at [[Stanford University]] and the director of the John S. Knight Journalism Fellowships, said \"Even if ''Epoch Times'' is not associated with Falun Gong, if they consistently write about Falun Gong in the same perspective, or if there are no articles examining Falun Gong, people would perceive it as being not credible.\"<ref name=\"waves2\">Eugenia Chien, [http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a \"Falun Gong-Linked Media Venture Makes Waves, Raises Questions\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306081937/http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a|date=March 6, 2008}} ''New America Media'', News Analysis, May 16, 2006</ref> Orville Schell, dean of the Graduate School of Journalism at [[University of California, Berkeley]], said in 2005 that \"It's hard to vouch for their quality because it's difficult to corroborate, but it's not something to be dismissed as pure propaganda.\"<ref name=\"sfgate23\"/>\n\nIn his 2008 book on Falun Gong, David Ownby wrote that ''The Epoch Times'' articles are \"well written and interesting, if occasionally idiosyncratic in their coverage.\"<ref name=\"DO2\" /><ref name=\"morais\">Morais, Betsy. \"''The Epoch Times'' doesn't like to brag\", Capital Magazine, Jun. 23, 2010</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://berkleycenter.georgetown.edu/people/david-ownby|title=David Ownby|last=University|first=Berkley Center for Religion, Peace and World Affairs at Georgetown|website=berkleycenter.georgetown.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> According to Ownby, the newspaper has been praised and also criticized for a perceived bias against the CCP, and support of Falun Gong practitioners and other dissidents such as Tibetans, Taiwanese independence advocates, democracy activists, Uyghurs and others. The paper, therefore, is often assessed in light of its connection to Falun Gong, rather than a thorough analysis of its editorial content.<ref>Ownby 2008, pp. ''vii''\u2013''viii'', 163, 221\u20133, 229.</ref>\n\n[[Jiao Guobiao]], a former Beijing University journalism professor who was dismissed after criticizing the [[Publicity Department of the Communist Party of China|Propaganda Department]], proposed that even if ''The Epoch Times'' published only negative information highly critical of the CCP, the weight of their attacks could never begin to counterbalance the positive propaganda the party publishes about itself. In addressing media balance, Jiao noted that the Chinese public lacked negative, critical information regarding their country. As such, he noted for a need of media balance based on the principles of freedom, equality, and legality, and that media balance \"is the result of the collective imbalances of all\".<ref name=\"Thornton2008\" />\n\nIn 2010, ''The Epoch Times'' successfully defended its reporting in the Canadian court system,<ref name=\"Canada2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scc-csc.ca/case-dossier/info/sum-som-eng.aspx?cas=34781|title=Supreme Court of Canada - SCC Case Information - Summary - 34781|last=Canada|first=Supreme Court of|date=2001-01-01|website=www.scc-csc.ca|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref>[http://www.facts.org.cn/reports/world/200805/t80351.htm Facts.org] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005152705/http://www.facts.org.cn/reports/world/200805/t80351.htm|date=October 5, 2011}}, quoting from Xinhua, March 23, 2006 (Retrieved July 23, 2011)</ref> when a publisher it had reported on, Crescent Chau of ''[[Les Presses Chinoises]]'', sued for libel.<ref name=\"straightgood2\">Miller, John Gordon (31 May 2010) [http://www.straightgoods.ca/2010/ViewArticle.cfm?Ref=554 \"Judge rules that Falun Gong newspaper acted in the public interest\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903024152/http://www.straightgoods.ca/2010/ViewArticle.cfm?Ref=554|date=September 3, 2010}} Straight Goods</ref> The Supreme Court of Canada ruled that ''The Epoch Times'' article expressed \"legitimate concerns and constitute an opinion which is drawn from a factual premise.\"<ref name=\"Canada2\" /> In examining the case, John Gordon Miller, a Canadian journalist and media professor, noted that articles in question \"appear to be thoroughly and professionally reported\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thejournalismdoctor.ca/Blog.php/33|title=Blog: Good journalism|last=Ubertor.com|first=John Miller, The Journalism Doctor, Bewdley, Real Estate Website by|website=thejournalismdoctor.ca|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref name=\"straightgood2\" />\n\nHayes Brown of ''[[BuzzFeed News|Buzzfeed News]]'' called ''The Epoch Times'' \"one of the staunchest defenders of [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] presidency.\"<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nU.S. Representative [[Paul Gosar]], Republican of Arizona, called ''The Epoch Times'' \u201cour favorite paper.\u201d<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/technology/epoch-times-youtube.html|title=Epoch Times, Punished by Facebook, Gets a New Megaphone on YouTube|last=Roose|first=Kevin|date=2020-02-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nHaifeng Huang, a professor of political science, said, \"I'm not exactly clear why they have become such a major pro-Trump voice\" but \"part of it is perhaps because they regard President Trump as tough on the Chinese government and therefore a natural ally for them\".<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe web-only, German edition of the paper, ''Epoch Times Deutschland'', has been criticized by media analysts<ref>Notably such media analysts include Bethany Allen-Ebrahimian of ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' magazine and Stefan Winterbauer of Germany's [[:de:Meedia|Meedia]].</ref> for its favorable coverage of far right populist groups such as the [[Alternative for Germany]] and [[Pegida]], both of which proclaim anti-immigrant views, and promotion of skepticism towards mainstream German media and politicians.<ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\" /> A German media report described the outlet, along with [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik News]] and Kopp Report, as a \"favorite\" of Pegida supporters, and found that its articles critical of immigration have been shared almost daily.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nA report by the [[Institute for Strategic Dialogue]], a London-based think tank, said the German edition of ''The Epoch Times'' \"primarily runs anti-West, anti-American and pro-Kremlin content \u2013 a high proportion of this content is based on unverified information.\"<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isdglobal.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Make-Germany-Great-Again-ENG-061217.pdf|title=Make Germany Great Again: Kremlin, Alt-Right and International Influences in the 2017 German Elections|last=|first=|date=2017|website=Institute for Strategic Dialogue|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n*'''2012 Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal'''&nbsp;\u2014 Canadian publisher Cindy Gu of ''The Epoch Times'' was one of about 60,000 recipients awarded this commemorative medal, which honors \"significant contributions and achievements by Canadians.\"<ref>[https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/canadian-honours/directory-honours/queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee-medal Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal] The Governor General of Canada. Retrieved 28 Apr 2013</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients?filter_name=Cindy+Gu |title=Find a Recipient |publisher=The Governor General of Canada|date=June 11, 2018 }}</ref> She was nominated for the medal by the Canadian Centre for Abuse Awareness for raising awareness of human rights abuses in China and the organ harvesting of Falun Gong practitioners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ausepochmedia.com/2016/10/25/epoch-times-publisher-awarded-diamond-jubilee-medal/|title=Epoch Times Publisher Awarded Diamond Jubilee Medal|date=2016-10-25|website=Chinese Newspaper - Perth Epoch Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref>\n*'''2012 National Ethnic Press and Media Council Award'''&nbsp;\u2014The Chinese edition of ''The Epoch Times'' was one of nine newspapers given an award for \"excellence in editorial/free expression, best concept and visual presentation.\"<ref>[https://www.sources.com/Releases/NR1780.htm \"National Ethnic Press and Media Council of Canada Award Recipients 2012\"] sources.com 7 November 2012</ref><ref>''The Epoch Times'' (13 November 2012) [https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/canada/epoch-times-wins-ethnic-press-media-award-in-canada-314136.html ''The Epoch Times'' Wins Ethnic Press Media Award] Retrieved 28 Apr 2013</ref>\n*'''2012 New York Press Association Award'''&nbsp;\u2014 ''The Epoch Times'' won first place in the category \"Best Special Section&nbsp;\u2014 Advertising, Division 2\" for a special section produced for ''Asia Week'' New York in March 2012. \"A great special section has five strong components: a great cover, appealing design, good art, strong content, and well-designed complementary advertising. This section has all five\", said the NYPA judges. \"In all, this is one of the nicest sections I have ever seen produced by a newspaper.\"<ref>[http://www.freeinews.com Free-i-News.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421130806/http://www.freeinews.com/ |date=April 21, 2013}} (8 April 2013) [http://www.freeinews.com/global/epoch-times-wins-newspaper-excellence-award \"''The Epoch Times'' Wins Newspaper Excellence Award\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102140506/http://www.freeinews.com/global/epoch-times-wins-newspaper-excellence-award |date=November 2, 2013}} Retrieved 28 Apr 2013</ref>\n*'''2012 [[Society of Professional Journalists]]' [[Sigma Delta Chi Award]]'''&nbsp;\u2014 ''The Epoch Times'' China reporter Matthew Robertson won this award in the category of Non-Deadline Reporting in newspapers with a circulation of less than 50,000 per day, for a series of articles he wrote on forced, live organ harvesting in China.<ref name=\"SPJ22\">[https://www.spj.org/sdxa12.asp \"2012 Sigma Delta Chi Award Honorees\"], The Society of Professional Journalists, spj.org Accessed 8 Dec. 2014</ref>\n*'''2013 Newswomen's Club Award'''&nbsp;\u2014 ''The Epoch Times'' New York reporter Genevieve Belmaker won a Front Page Award from the Newswomen's Club of New York for reporting on the effects of [[Hurricane Sandy]], in the category of newspapers with a circulation of less than 100,000 per day.<ref>Newswomen's Club of New York [https://www.newswomensclubnewyork.com/2013-front-page-awards/ \"2013 Front Page Award Winners\"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124095018/http://www.newswomensclubnewyork.com/2013-fpa-winners |date=January 24, 2015}} newswomensclubnewyork.com</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*Falun Gong-related groups:\n:*[[New Tang Dynasty Television]]\n:*[[Shen Yun]] Performing Arts\n:*[[Sound of Hope]]\n*''[[World Journal]]''\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Epoch Times}}\n*[https://www.theepochtimes.com/ ''Epoch Times''] {{in lang|en}}\n*[https://epochtimes.com ''Epoch Times''] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[https://www.epochtimes.org.au/ ''Epoch Times''] Australia\n*[https://www.ninecommentaries.com/ \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"]\n\n{{Falun Gong}}\n{{Portal bar|Journalism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Epoch Times, The}}\n[[Category:2000 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Chinese-American culture in New York City]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers (Traditional Chinese)]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers published in Canada]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers published in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:Criticism of journalism]]\n[[Category:Falun Gong]]\n[[Category:Free daily newspapers]]\n[[Category:French-language newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:German-language newspapers published in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Internet-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Media bias controversies]]\n[[Category:Media-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in New York City]]\n[[Category:Non-English-language newspapers published in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:Conservative media in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Swiftlizz", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I'm not sure)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Epoch_Times"}
{"title_page": "Bible John", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name=Bible John\n| image     = File:Bible_John_1969_Police_Composite_Sketch.jpg\n| caption   = 1969 [[Facial composite|composite drawing]] of ''Bible John''\n| alt       = Composite drawing of Bible John, created with the assistance of the sister of his last known victim, Helen Puttock\n| victims= 3 \n| locations = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| beginyear= 22 February 1968\n| endyear= 31 October 1969\n| apprehended= Unapprehended \n}}\n\n'''Bible John''' is an unidentified [[serial killer]] who is believed to have murdered three young women between 1968 and 1969 in [[Glasgow]], Scotland.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lister|first=David Brown, Sean O\u2019Neill and David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bible-john-the-sanctimonious-dancehall-killer-who-vanished-gmfgpwb7j6d|title=\u2018Bible John\u2019 \u2013 the sanctimonious dancehall killer who vanished|access-date=2020-03-07|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nEach of the victims of Bible John were young [[brunette]] women between the ages of 25 and 32, and all had met their murderer at the [[Barrowland Ballroom]]: a [[dance hall]] and [[music venue]] in the city. The perpetrator has never been identified and the case remains both unsolved and also one of the most extensive [[manhunt (law enforcement)|manhunts]] in Scottish criminal history.<ref>{{cite book|title=Glasgow Almanac: An A-Z of the City and its People|isbn=978-1-906-47625-0|page=112|location=Glasgow|publisher=Neil Wilson Publishing|year=2011|first=Stephen|last=Terry}}</ref>\n\nThe murders committed by Bible John would prove to be the first time in Scotland in which the [[Clerk of the Crown in Chancery|Crown Office]] authorised the publication of a [[facial composite|composite drawing]] of an individual suspected of murder for public viewing.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|Whittington-Egan|1992|p=18}}\n\nThis unidentified serial killer became known as \"Bible John\" due to his having repeatedly quoted from the [[Christian Bible|Bible]] and to have condemned any form of [[adultery]] while in the company of his final victim.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=21}} The known movements and ''[[modus operandi]]'' of convicted serial killer and rapist [[Peter Tobin]] have given rise to suspicions that he may be Bible John.\n\n==First murders==\n===Patricia Docker===\nOn 23 February 1968, the naked body of a 25-year-old [[auxiliary nurse]] named Patricia Docker was found in the doorway of a lock-up garage by a man on his way to work in [[Battlefield, Glasgow|Battlefield, South Glasgow]].<ref name=\"Skelton\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=v-NAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3KYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1709,2603592&dq|title=20 years on, the mystery of Bible John still haunts a city|newspaper=[[Evening Times]]|last=Skelton|first=Douglas|date=10 February 1989|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> The location of her body was only yards from her home in Langside Place. Her body bore evidence of extensive [[blunt force trauma]]\u2014particularly to the face and head.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|Whittington-Egan|1992|p=17}} She had been [[strangulation|strangled]] to death with a strong [[strangling#Ligature strangulation|ligature]], possibly a belt.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=52}} Patricia's handbag, watch, and clothes were missing from the [[crime scene]]. Her clothing was never found,<ref name=\"MacDougall\"/> although her handbag was later recovered from the [[River Cart]] by an [[underwater search and recovery|underwater search unit]],{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=53}} whereas her watch was recovered from a pool of water close to the scene of her murder.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\">''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 34. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref>\n\nExtensive door-to-door inquiries in the area produced a witness who recalled hearing a female scream, \"Leave me alone!\" the previous evening. Little [[smoking gun|hard evidence]] was discovered at the crime scene. Nonetheless, an ambulanceman who retrieved the body informed investigators the victim had been a nurse who worked at Mearnskirk Hospital in nearby [[Renfrewshire]].<ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> Consequently, the victim was formally identified by her father the following day.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=191}}\n\nPatricia was a married mother of one but [[family estrangement|estranged]] from her husband.<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\">{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> The night of her murder, she informed her parents she would spend the evening dancing at the Majestic Ballroom in nearby Hope Street, although for unknown reasons, she had chosen to spend the majority of the evening at the Barrowland Ballroom, likely to attend the over-25s night which the Barrowland hosted each Thursday.<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\">{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref> When she failed to return home that evening, her parents assumed she had spent the night with a friend.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Petrie|first1=Ewan|title=Bible John: Remembering Notorious Serial Killer's Victims|url=https://stv.tv/news/features/1408716-bible-john-victims-of-notorious-glasgow-serial-killer/|publisher=STV|accessdate=23 July 2018|date=23 February 2018}}</ref> Police inquiries would only determine several days later<ref>{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> that in the late evening, Patricia had left the Majestic Ballroom to attend the Barrowland,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/DANCING+WITH+DEATH%3B+CHASING+KILLERS%3A+RETIRED+COP+JOE+JACKSON+ON+THE...-a0186026767|title=Dancing With Death; Chasing Killers|publisher=[[The Free Library]]|website=Daily Record|last=Jackson|first=Joe|date=1 October 2008|accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref> where she had likely encountered her killer.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/><ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[autopsy|postmortem]] conducted by Gilbert Forbes at the [[University of Glasgow Medical School]] confirmed that the cause of death had been strangulation, and that Patricia's body bore no clear evidence of [[sexual assault]].{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=192}}<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\"/> Furthermore, the stage of [[rigor mortis]] upon her body at the time of discovery indicated she had likely died shortly after she had left the Barrowland Ballroom.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=52}} Investigators surmised the perpetrator had likely grabbed Patricia before repeatedly punching her and kicking her in the face as she twice screamed \"Leave me alone!\"<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\"/> He had then proceeded to [[rape]] Patricia before strangling her to death, and leaving her naked body, with nothing but one shoe nearby, close to the doorway of the lock-up garage at Carmichael Place.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\"/>\n\n===Jemima McDonald===\nOn Saturday, 16 August 1969, a 32-year-old mother of three named Jemima McDonald also opted to attend the Barrowland Ballroom to spend the evening dancing. Jemima was a regular attendee of the Barrowland, and as per family custom, her sister, Margaret O'Brien, took care of her three children as Jemima attended the Barrowland.<ref>''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 35. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref> As midnight approached, Jemima was seen by several people in the company of a young, well-dressed and well-spoken man of slim build aged between 25 and 35 and between {{nowrap|6 ft 0 in}} and {{nowrap|6 ft 2 in}} ({{convert|72|and|74|in|cm|disp=out}}) in height.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=195}} This individual had short, dark brown hair with fair streaks,{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=253}} likely spoke with a distinctive [[Glasgow accent|Glaswegian accent]], and occasionally inserted brief Biblical quotations into his conversation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nJemima was seen leaving the Barrowland shortly after midnight on 17 August in the company of this individual, and was last seen walking towards either Main Street or Landressy Street, in the direction of her home, at approximately 12:40&nbsp;a.m.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=195}} The following day, Jemima's sister, Margaret, became concerned when her sister failed to return home. Later the same day, she began hearing local rumours that young children had been seen leaving a derelict [[tenement]] building in MacKeith Street discussing a body in the premises.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/> By the Monday morning, Margaret was so concerned that she herself, fearing the worst, walked into the old building. There she discovered her own sister's extensively battered body lying face down, with her shoes and stockings lying beside her.\n\nA postmortem concluded Jemima had been raped and extensively beaten, particularly about the face,<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\"/> before she had been strangled to death with one of her own stockings. Her murder had occurred approximately 30 hours before her body had been discovered.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\">{{cite news|title=Bible John Killer may be Unmasked After 30 Years |date=15 October 2000 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1370421/Bible-John-killer-may-be-unmasked-after-30-years.html |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=19 June 2018}}</ref> Unlike Patricia Docker, the body of Jemima McDonald was fully clothed,<ref name=\"Skelton\"/> although her underclothing had been torn, and like Patricia, Jemima had been [[menstruation|menstruating]] at the time of her death.<ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nPolice inquiries into Jemima's movements on the night of her murder produced several [[Eyewitness memory|eyewitness]]es who were able to accurately describe the man with whom Jemima had been in the company of at the Barrowland. Door-to-door inquiries on MacKieth Street also produced a woman who remembered hearing female screams on the evening of Jemima's murder, although this individual could not recall the precise time. Consequently, police considered this information of little use to their inquiry.\n\n==Initial investigation==\nAlthough the [[City of Glasgow Police]] noted several striking similarities between the murders of Patricia Docker and Jemima McDonald, including that both women had attended the Barrowland Ballroom on the evening of their murder, been beaten before being strangled to death with a ligature, were menstruating, and had their handbags taken from the crime scene. Initially, both murders were not considered to be the work of the same perpetrator.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=194}}\n\nDespite extensive public appeals, the investigation into the murder of Patricia Docker in 1968 had quickly become a [[cold case]]. Police had little information, owing to both a lack of [[witness]]es and hard evidence.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=193}} The investigation had also been severely hindered by  investigators discovering three days after her death that Patricia had attended the Barrowland Ballroom on the evening of her murder.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/i-think-bible-john-already-11923937|title=False Information Doomed Bible John Probe from the Start|website=The Daily Record|last=Silvester|first=Norman|date=28 January 2018|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/DANCING+WITH+DEATH%3B+CHASING+KILLERS%3A+RETIRED+COP+JOE+JACKSON+ON+THE...-a0186026767|title=Dancing With Death: Chasing Killers|publisher=[[The Free Library]]|website=Daily Record|last=Jackson|first=Joe|date=1 October 2008|accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref> Eighteen months later, following the discovery of Jemima McDonald, police became aware of remarkable similarities to the murder of Patricia Docker. Although police did not conclusively link both murders to the same perpetrator, they could not completely discount this theory. In addition, police were certain the perpetrator or perpetrators held a high degree of local geographical knowledge. However, they may have been a stranger to the district, as none of the eyewitnesses with whom investigators conversed directly knew the individual(s) seen in the company of either woman prior to her murder.<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\"/>\n[[File:Barrowlands, Glasgow - geograph.org.uk - 663608.jpg|thumb|right|The Barrowland Ballroom, seen here in 2011. Each of the women murdered are believed to have encountered Bible John at this dance hall]]\n\nFor the first time in a Scottish murder hunt, a [[facial composite|composite drawing]] of the man with whom Jemima had last been seen alive was given to the press, being widely distributed via both newspapers and upon television throughout Scotland in efforts to identify the suspect.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/> Moreover, both male and female [[Undercover operation|undercover police officers]] performed discreet surveillance at the Barrowland Ballroom in efforts to identify the suspect.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=196}} Police surveillance at the Barrowland Ballroom would be terminated in late October 1969 due to the initiative both failing to produce any suspects. Detectives were also blamed by proprietors for a sharp decrease in attendance figures.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|pp=196-197}}\n\n===Helen Puttock===\nOn 31 October 1969, a man walking his dog discovered the body of 29-year-old Helen Puttock behind a [[tenement]] in the [[Scotstoun]] district of Glasgow. Her body was found beside a drainpipe in the back garden of her Earl Street flat. She had been stripped partially naked, extensively beaten about the face before being raped, then strangled to death with one of her own stockings.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=201}} The contents of her handbag had been scattered close to her body, although the handbag itself was missing from the crime scene. Grass and weed stains upon the soles of Helen's feet and shoes indicated that she had engaged in a ferocious struggle with her killer. She had evidently at one point attempted to scale a nearby railway embankment. Her body also bore a deep [[forensic dentistry|bite mark]] on her upper right thigh.<ref name=\"Skelton2\"/> Her murderer had placed her [[sanitary towel]] beneath her left arm. As had been the case with the two previous victims, Helen had been menstruating at the time of her murder.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|Whittington-Egan|1992|p=17}}\n\nThe evening prior to her murder, Helen and her sister, Jean Langford, had been to the Barrowland Ballroom, where both had become acquainted with men named John. One of these individuals had said he worked as a [[slater]] who resided in [[Castlemilk]],{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}} while the other individual had been a well-spoken man who did not disclose where he actually lived. After being in the company of these two individuals for in excess of an hour, all four left the Barrowland to head home. The individual named John who had been Jean's dance partner walked to [[George Square]] to board a bus, while Jean, Helen, and the individual who had been Helen's dance partner hailed a taxi.<ref name=\"Hamilton\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/legendary-glasgow-detective-tells-believes-1052300|title=Legendary Glasgow detective tells why he believes serial killer Peter Tobin was notorious murderer Bible John|work=Daily Record|last=Hamilton|first=Tom|date=5 March 2010|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> The trio set off from [[Glasgow Cross]], making a 20-minute westward journey toward Jean's [[Knightswood]] residence. There she exited the taxi, which then continued towards Helen's Scotstoun residence. During conversations between the trio upon this journey, most of the crucial information pertaining to the killer's [[psychological profiling|psychological profile]] became apparent.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/>\n\nJean later informed detectives{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=53}} that her sister's companion had been a [[teetotalism|teetotal]] individual{{sfn|Newton|2004|p=42}} who repeatedly quoted from the [[Old Testament]] stories of [[Moses]] during the time she and her sister had conversed with him in the taxi; having previously referred to the Barrowland as an \"[[adultery|adulterous]] den of [[wikt:iniquity|iniquity]]\", and of his disapproval of married women visiting the premises as the quartet had retrieved their coats at the end of the evening.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Detective Still Convinced Bible John is Behind Bars |date=23 February 2018 |url=https://stv.tv/news/features/1408962-former-detective-still-convinced-bible-john-is-behind-bars/ |work=STV News |accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref> She had herself alighted the taxi at Kelso Street, before viewing the taxi turn towards Earl Street.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 36\">''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 36. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref> {{refn|group=n|Helen Puttock had been married at the time of her murder, although she did not disclose this fact to her murderer.}}{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=53}}\n\n==Suspect==\nThe suspect was described by Helen's sister Jean as being a tall, slim and well-dressed young man with reddish or fair hair rounded neatly at the back,{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=199}} aged between 25 and 30, and approximately {{convert|5|ft|10|in|m}} in height. This individual had given his name as either \"John Templeton\", \"John Sempleson\", or \"John Emerson\", and he had been a polite and well-spoken individual,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mountflorida.eveningtimes.co.uk/area/dark-days-and-dreadful-deeds-that-haunt-our-city.html|title=Dark days and dreadful deeds that haunt our city|work=Evening Times|date=7 June 2005|accessdate=26 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208143050/http://mountflorida.eveningtimes.co.uk/area/dark-days-and-dreadful-deeds-that-haunt-our-city.html|archivedate=8 February 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> having frequently quoted from the Old Testament during the trio's taxi ride home,<ref name=Findlay/> although he had indicated he was neither a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] nor [[Protestantism|Protestant]] individual.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 36\"/> Jean would also state to investigators it had become increasingly clear to her as the trio had ridden in the taxi that this individual had considered her presence in the vehicle to be an inconvenience.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=200}} At one point during this ride, this individual had explained to the women the reason he refrained from consuming alcohol was due to his being conditioned so by a strict parental attitude, before adding: \"I don't drink at [[Hogmanay]]; I pray.\" He had also alluded to his father's belief that dance halls were \"dens of iniquity\", with any married woman who frequented these premises being \"adulterous\" by nature.<ref name=\"Hamilton\"/>{{refn|group=n|The suspect's repeatedly referencing quotes from the Old Testament led to ''[[Evening Times]]'' journalist John Quinn naming the unknown murderer \"Bible John\".{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}}}}\n\nAlthough Jean Langford had informed detectives that the man accompanying Helen had been a \"slim, tall\" individual who had been dressed in a well-cut brown ''Reid and Taylor'' brand suit{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=54}} who smoked ''[[Embassy (cigarette)|Embassy]]'' cigarettes,<ref name=\"Bible John p. 36\"/> she also recalled this individual mentioning that he had been familiar with several drinking premises in the [[Yoker]] district of Glasgow,{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}} and that he had at one stage worked in a laboratory.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=204}} She would also recall distinct facial features of this man, such as his having overlapping front teeth. (Bouncers at the Barrowland Ballroom dismissed much of this description, claiming that the man in Helen's company had been a short and well-spoken individual with black hair.)<ref name=\"DR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/crime-professor-quizzes-detective-centre-1077102|title=Crime professor quizzes detective at centre of search for Bible John|work=Daily Record|date=28 November 2010|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Police initially considered the description provided by the bouncers to be a more reliable description than that provided by Jean Langford, as she had allegedly been [[alcohol intoxication|intoxicated]] at the time she and her sister had left the Barrowland Ballroom on the night of Helen's murder. Furthermore, police had reason to believe that the killer had not been quoting directly from the Bible, but had simply been referring to it. However, Jean strongly attested to her having been [[sobriety|sober]] at the time she had left the Barrowland, and a bouncer at these premises would later state that staff who worked at the premises were not \"good with faces\".}}\n\nThe last possible sighting of the suspect was made by both the driver and [[Bus conductor|conductor]] upon a night service bus, who noticed a young man matching Jean's description alighting a bus at the junction of Dumbarton Road and Gray Street at approximately 2:00&nbsp;a.m. on 31 October.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}} He was in a notably disheveled state, with mud stains on his jacket and a livid red mark on his cheek just beneath one eye. Both witnesses also recalled his repeatedly tucking a short cuff of one sleeve into his jacket sleeve (a man's cuff link had been found alongside the body of Helen Puttock).<ref>''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 37. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref> This individual was last seen walking towards the public ferry to cross the [[River Clyde]] to the south side of the city.<ref name=\"Wier\"/>\n\n===Link to series===\nThe murder of Helen Puttock held remarkable similarities to the two previous murders, further raising suspicions that all three murders had been committed by the same individual. All of the victims had been mothers of at least one child and had met her murderer at the Barrowland Ballroom. The handbag of each woman was missing. Each victim had been strangled to death; and at least two of these women had been raped prior to her murder.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=21}} In addition, the three women had been escorted home by her killer and murdered within yards of their doorstep, and all had been menstruating at the time of her death.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\"/> Each had had her sanitary towel or [[tampon]] placed upon, beneath, or near her body,<ref name=\"Skelton2\"/>{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|pp=202-203}} leading to speculation the women had been murdered due to their refusing to engage in intercourse with their murderer due to their periods.<ref>{{cite news|title=Was Peter Tobin Bible John? |date=6 December 2008 |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/was-peter-tobin-bible-john-1-1302021 |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n{{quote box\n| quote = \"It is quite incredible that this man has eluded us. I am positive this man comes from Glasgow or nearby. He is between 25 and 30, between {{nowrap|5 ft 10 in}} and {{nowrap|6 ft}} tall, has light red hair, good features, blue-grey eyes and a smart modern appearance. I do not think he is a very religious man, but just has a normal intelligent working knowledge of the Bible which he likes to air ... there must be many people who know someone who looks like this artist's impression.\"\n| source = Detective Superintendent Joe Beattie, describing the prime suspect in the Bible John murders (1972).<ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n| width = 35em\n}}\n\n==Ongoing investigation==\nWithin hours of the discovery of the body of Helen Puttock, an additional composite drawing of the suspect was created using the detailed description provided by her sister;{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=203}} this composite drawing would rapidly become one of the most famous facial composites in Scotland.<ref name=\"express\">{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/356076/I-am-sure-the-famous-portrait-of-Bible-John-shows-the-wrong-man|title=I am sure the famous portrait of Bible John shows the wrong man|work=[[Daily Express]]|last=Borland|first=Ben|date=4 November 2012|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|At the headquarters of the [[City of Glasgow Police]], Jean Langford happened to view an earlier [[facial composite|composite drawing]] created relating to the chief suspect in the murder of Jemima McDonald. Upon viewing this Identikit, Langford exclaimed, \"That man looks just like him!\"{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=203}}}} Detective Superintendent Joe Beattie asked the public to closely study this composite drawing, should it resemble anyone they knew. Due to the suspect's hair being unfashionably short for the era, over 450 hairdressers in and around Glasgow were shown the updated composite drawing of the suspect, and all dentists in and around Glasgow were asked to examine their records to determine whether they held records of a male patient with overlapping [[incisor]]s and a missing tooth in the upper right jaw. Both lines of inquiry would prove fruitless.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=54}}\n\nMore than 100 detectives were assigned to work full-time on the case, and 50,000 [[witness statement]]s would be taken in subsequent door-to-door inquiries.<ref name=\"Skelton2\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=OhQ-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=HEoMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6523,4393868&dq|title=Bible John: Final Part of a Harrowing Tale of Terror|work=Evening Times|last=Skelton|first=Douglas|date=18 February 1989|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The True Story of Bible John and the Barrowland Killings |date=22 February 2018 |url=https://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/news/history/bible-john-killing-glasgow-barrowlands-11533797 |work=Glasgow Live |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref> Ultimately, more than 5,000 potential suspects would be quizzed in relation to the murders in the first year of the inquiry alone, and Jean Langford would be required to attend over 300 [[police lineup|identity parades]],{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=204}} although she was adamant none of the individuals required to participate in these identity parades had been the individual with whom she had last seen her sister, and all would be cleared of any involvement.<ref name=\"Skelton2\"/> Fearing that the perpetrator would strike again, a team of 16 detectives were instructed to mingle with dancers at all dance halls in Glasgow. In particular, these detectives frequented the Barrowland on Thursday and Saturday nights at the over-25s events, where each victim was presumed to have met her murderer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Two of the three victims murdered by Bible John had been killed on a Thursday, and one on a Saturday.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=190}}}}\n\nDespite the extensive manhunt, no further developments would arise and the investigation into the three murders gradually became cold, with many individuals assigned to the case opining that the perpetrator had either died, been jailed for an unrelated offense, had been incarcerated at a mental hospital, or that senior police officers had known his actual identity, but had been unable to prove he had committed the murders.<ref name=\"MacDougall\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Fwc-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=m0kMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4523,2561436&dq|title=Dark world of a dance hall killer|newspaper=Evening Times|last=MacDougall|first=Carl|date=9 October 1987|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> Others speculated that he may have simply moved away from the Glasgow district, or murdered whenever in the vicinity;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/bible-john-may-be-in-england-1.213923|title=Bible John may be in England|work=[[The Herald (Scotland)|The Herald]]|date=16 October 2000|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> this possibility prompted police to circulate multiple copies of the composite drawing at all [[British Army]], [[Royal Navy|Navy]] and [[Royal Air Force|Air Force]] bases in the United Kingdom, Europe, and the [[Middle East|Middle]] and [[Far East]], although this potential line of inquiry also failed to produce any significant leads.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Potential suspects==\n===\"John White\"===\nOne former Detective Chief Inspector, Les Brown (then working with the [[Strathclyde Police]]), has supplied current investigators with details of the arrest of a suspect conducted in 1969 which he believes was of an extremely likely perpetrator, but which was dismissed simply because this individual did not have notably overlapping front teeth.\n\nAccording to Les Brown, the man's arguing with a young woman in the Barrowland Ballroom immediately prior to his arrest had greatly raised investigators' concerns, yet\u2014despite the fact the suspect had closely resembled the facial composite and had subsequently supplied police with a false name and address before revealing his true name and address in [[Gorbals|the Gorbals]]\u2014was simply released. According to Brown, the simple fact of this particular suspect not having notably overlapping front teeth - despite one police sergeant's acknowledgement of his being the best suspect yet - was sufficient enough for ordering his release.<ref name=\"Bible John Police Get New Informati\">{{cite news|title=Bible John Police Get New Information on Serial Killer's Identity |date=23 October 2005 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12472387.Bible_John_police_get_new_information_on_serial_killer_apos_s_identity/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral years later, Brown extensively conversed with a detective who had taken the same individual to a hospital after arresting him outside the Barrowland Ballroom at the time of the murders. Although the suspect had needed several stitches in his head following an altercation, as soon as his handcuffs had been released, he escaped from the hospital. At the time of this incident, this individual had also falsely given his name to medical personnel as John White.\n\nIn addition to this basic circumstantial evidence, the \"whole demeanour\" of this individual had led Les Brown and several of his colleagues to believe this individual may have been the perpetrator.<ref name=\"Bible John Police Get New Informati\"/>\n\n===John Irvine McInnes===\nIn 1996, Strathclyde Police [[Burial#Exhumation|exhumed]] the body of John Irvine McInnes from a graveyard in [[Stonehouse, South Lanarkshire]]. McInnes, who had served in the [[Scots Guards]], had committed [[suicide]] in 1980 at the age of 41, having severed the [[brachial artery]] in his upper arm. He had been the cousin of one of the original suspects in the series of murders.<ref name=\"Bizarre suicide of Bible John\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Bizarre+suicide+of+Bible+John.-a061271527|title=Bizarre suicide of Bible John|publisher=The Free Library|website=Daily Record|date=30 January 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> A [[Genetic testing|DNA sample]] was taken from McInnes's body for comparison with [[semen analysis|semen samples]] discovered upon the stockings with which victim Helen Puttock had been strangled.<ref name=\"Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Seria\">{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12036852.DNA_tests_clear_Bible_John_suspect/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|According to a contemporary [[psychiatrist]]'s report, the unusual method of suicide chosen by McInnes was akin to [[psychopathy]], leading to suggestions McInnes may have opted to take his own life in search of the \"ultimate thrill\".<ref name=\"Bizarre suicide of Bible John\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Bizarre+suicide+of+Bible+John.-a061271527|title=Bizarre suicide of Bible John|publisher=The Free Library|website=Daily Record|date=30 January 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> }}\n\nThe results of the testing conducted proved inconclusive, with then-[[Lord Advocate]] [[James Mackay, Baron Mackay of Clashfern|Lord Mackay]] stating [[Burden of proof (law)|insufficient evidence]]<ref name=\"Men give DNA in Bible John case\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/4089653.stm|title=Men give DNA in Bible John case|work=[[BBC News]]|date=12 December 2004|accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> existed to link McInnes with the murder of Helen Puttock.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/dna-tests-clear-bible-john-suspect-1.447304|title=DNA tests clear Bible John suspect|work=The Herald|last=Freeman|first=James|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> [[The Crown]] would officially clear McInnes of any involvement in the Bible John murders in July 1996.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12036852.DNA_tests_clear_Bible_John_suspect/|title=DNA Tests Clear Bible John Suspect|work=Herald Scotland|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Peter Tobin===\nSeveral [[Criminology|criminologists]] and investigators have suggested that convicted serial killer [[Peter Tobin]] may have been Bible John. Tobin was convicted in May 2007 of the 2006 murder of a [[Poles|Polish]] student named Angelika Kluk, who had been raped, beaten, then stabbed to death;<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|title=I'm Ashamed I Had Sex With Girl, Priest Tells Murder Trial |date=4 April 2007 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1547590/Im-ashamed-I-had-sex-with-girl-priest-tells-murder-trial.html |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref> he had relocated from [[Shettleston|Shettleston, Glasgow]]<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\"/> to England in 1969 after marrying his first wife, whom he had met at the Barrowland Ballroom the same year as the murders attributed to Bible John had ended.<ref name=\"Wier\">{{cite book|last=Wier|first=Nigel|year=2012|title=British Serial Killers|publisher=AuthorHouseUK|page=226}}</ref> Tobin would subsequently live in [[Brighton]] for 20 years from 1969,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/jul/12/peter-tobin-serial-killer-brighton-search|title=Peter Tobin's former homes searched in hunt for more victims|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Tran|first=Mark|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/scotland/article6968389.ece|title=Killer question|work=[[The Times]]|date=27 December 2009}}</ref> although from the late 1980s, he would alternately reside in either Scotland or the South of England.<ref name=\"Wilson2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/books/features/a-life-of-crime-professor-david-wilson-trying-to-understand-why-serial-killers-kill-1-816044|title=A life of crime: Professor David Wilson \u2013 trying to understand why serial killers kill|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=4 July 2010|accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|A former detective named Joe Jackson (who had investigated the ''Bible John'' murders in the 1960s) has stated that he suspected Tobin may be the perpetrator shortly after he was arrested for Kluk's murder in 2006, adding: \"When I saw his photograph, I thought, 'This is as near to Bible John as you are going to get. This looks a winner.' He fitted the bill in every way, and he had connections with religion.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/exclusive-cops-believe-peter-tobin-1000204|title=Exclusive: Cops believe Peter Tobin was Bible John|work=Daily Record|last=O'Hare|first=Paul|date=3 December 2008|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref>}}\n\nTobin had been in his mid-40s when he committed the 1991 murder of two teenage girls whose [[skeletonization|skeletonized]] bodies would subsequently be unearthed from the garden of his home in [[Margate, Kent]] in 2007. He would be convicted of these murders\u2014alongside that of Kluk\u2014between 2007 and 2009. Commencing serial murderous offences of an extremely calculated nature at such an age is unusual\u2014though not unheard of\u2014for a male. Furthermore, the fact that Tobin had attacked Kluk with such violence, then hidden her body before absconding to London prior to his subsequent arrest in addition to the abduction, restraining and concealment known to have been exhibited upon the two 1991 murder victims unearthed from the garden of his Margate home did not suggest the work of an amateur in any of these three cases.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/1823130|title=Expert convinced Tobin is Bible John says more murders likely|work=[[The Press and Journal (Scotland)|The Press and Journal]]|last=Lindsay|first=Morag|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nStriking contemporary visual similarities exist between Peter Tobin when aged in his 20s and the 1969 composite drawing of Bible John. In addition, all three of Tobin's former wives have given accounts of being repeatedly imprisoned, throttled, beaten and raped at his hands, and each has stated he had been driven to extreme physical violence by the female [[menstrual cycle]] (a factor long suspected by investigators as being the perpetrator's actual motive behind the murders).<ref name=\"Hamilton\"/> In addition, Tobin is known to have been a staunch [[Roman Catholic]] with strong religious views,<ref name=Wilson/> and the alias Bible John had given to Jean Langford and Helen Puttock in 1969 is similar to one of the [[pseudonym]]s known to have been regularly used by Tobin: John Semple.<ref name=\"Wilson2\"/>\n\nCriminologist [[David Wilson (criminologist)|David Wilson]] actively investigated Tobin's case for three years and strongly believes the available evidence supports his theory that Peter Tobin is Bible John.<ref name=Wilson/> He has stated that the moment he believed Tobin was Bible John occurred during Tobin's trial for the 1991 murder of 18-year-old Dinah McNicol, one of the women whose body had been unearthed from his Margate garden. The [[circumstantial evidence]] which Wilson uses to support this theory includes striking similarities between trial testimony from an acquaintance of Dinah's who had been in her company on the evening of her abduction and the conversation with Bible John that Jean Langford claimed to have had on the evening of her sister's murder; among the important points of overlap are both men mentioning they did not drink at Hogmanay and had a cousin who had once scored a [[hole-in-one]] in a golf match.<ref name=Wilson/> This information\u2014alongside other circumstantial evidence\u2014has led Professor Wilson to state: \"I didn't set out to prove Tobin was Bible John, but I would stake my professional reputation on it.\"<ref name=Wilson/><ref>{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Genetic testing|DNA testing]] has been used to clear several suspects, detectives believe obtaining a forensic link between Peter Tobin and any of the murder victims linked to Bible John is unlikely due to the deterioration of the physical samples owing to poor storage.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\n'''Operation Anagram'''\n\nAs a result of a police investigation named Operation Anagram, which was initiated in 2006 to trace the movements of Tobin throughout the decades and to determine his potential [[culpability]] in any other crimes, a woman informed investigators she had been raped by Tobin after she had met him at the Barrowland Ballroom in 1968, shortly after the first of the murders known to have been committed by Bible John.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10507524|title=Peter Tobin Crimewatch appeal gets 'massive' response|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=6 July 2010|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> Another woman informed investigators in 2010 that she had endured a threatening experience with Tobin at the Barrowland Ballroom, claiming that Tobin had introduced himself as Peter, before pestering her to go with him to a party in the city's Castlemilk area. When this woman viewed pictures of Tobin dating from the late 1960s and early 1970s, she stated: \"[He] was the man who came up to me so many years ago in [the] Barrowlands. I am 100 per cent certain [that] Tobin is Bible John.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/bible-john-asked-me-to-dance---1062823|title=Bible John asked me to dance \u2013 it was Peter Tobin, reveals terrified gran|work=Daily Record|last=Stewart|first=Stephen|date=27 June 2010|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nNo further murder victims killed in Scotland or elsewhere in the United Kingdom have ever been conclusively attributed to Bible John,{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|pp=207-208}} and the manhunt for this murderer was one of the most extensive manhunts in Scottish criminal history.<ref name=\"DR\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1370421/Bible-John-killer-may-be-unmasked-after-30-years.html|title=Bible John Killer May be Unmasked After 30 Years|work=The Telegraph|last=Booth|first=Jenny|date=15 October 2000|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> The murders of the three women remain unsolved, although the case remains open, with many investigators remaining certain that the perpetrator(s)<ref name=\"Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Seria\"/> of these crimes were highly likely to have been shielded by one or more individuals whom he had known.<ref>''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 38. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref>\n\nNo uniform consensus that the three killings were actually the work of the same person exists.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=205}} It has been claimed that the gap of 18 months between the first two killings is unusual for a serial killer, and that the later two murders may have either been copycat killings, or the sole two committed by the same perpetrator. Criticism has also been levelled against the police for potentially hampering their own investigation by prematurely jumping to the conclusion that all three murders had been committed by the same person.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jeffrey|first=Robert|year=2006|title=Crimes Past: Glasgow's Crimes of the Century|publisher=Black and White Publishing}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|[[David Wilson (criminologist)|Professor David Wilson]] has stated that a lapse of time approximating 18 months is not unusual between a serial killer's first and second murders.<ref name=Wilson>{{Cite news|title=Scots murderer Peter Tobin is Bible John, says UK serial killer expert|date=13 June 2010|work=Daily Record|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/scots-murderer-peter-tobin-is-bible-1061592|accessdate=4 March 2019|last=McPherson|first=Lynn}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930208&slug=1684320 |title=Serial Killer Says He'd Do It Again |last=Oak Kim |first=Myung |date=8 February 1993 |website=[[The Seattle Times]] |access-date=25 January 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125214432/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930208&slug=1684320 |archivedate=25 January 2017 }}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1983, an anonymous individual contacted [[Strathclyde Police]]. This individual claimed to conclusively know that his friend had been Bible John. According to this anonymous individual, both he and his friend had been raised in the [[Cranhill]] district of Glasgow, and both had frequented the Barrowland Ballroom in the 1960s. Allegedly, this individual had read an article in the ''[[Evening Times]]'' five years previously before suddenly realising his friend had been the perpetrator of the murders. The alleged suspect was traced living in [[Netherlands|the Netherlands]], married to a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] woman.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YNdAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=nqYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4240,1151385&dq|title=I know it is him|work=Evening Times|last=Hildrey|first=Mike|date=7 February 1983|accessdate=23 May 2013}}</ref> Nothing more was ever heard from the anonymous individual or the reputed suspect.\n\nIn 2004, police announced their intentions to [[genetic testing|genetically test]] a number of men in a further attempt to identify the perpetrator, with all individuals concerned being requested to submit [[Sampling (medicine)#Body fluid sampling|blood samples]].<ref name=\"Men give DNA in Bible John case\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/dna-tests-clear-bible-john-suspect-1.447304|title=DNA tests clear Bible John suspect|work=The Herald|last=Freeman|first=James|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> This endeavour followed the previous discovery of an 80% genetic match from the semen samples retrieved from the final crime scene attributed to Bible John with a DNA sample retrieved at the site of a minor crime committed two years earlier. The sample was enough of a match to lead officers to believe that the person who committed the offence was related to the killer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/DNA+BREAKTHROUGH%3A+POLICE+TRACE+FAMILY+OF+BIBLE+JOHN+SERIAL+KILLER.-a0126288448|title=DNA breakthrough: police trace family of Bible John serial killer|publisher=The Free Library|website=Sunday Mail|last=Lavery|first=Charles|date=19 December 2004|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe sole witness ever to have engaged in a lengthy conversation with Bible John, Jean Langford, died in September 2010 at the age of 74.<ref name=Findlay>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/2010/09/26/hunt-for-bible-john-comes-to-an-end-after-only-witness-in-case-dies-86908-22588146/|title=Hunt for Bible John comes to an end after only witness in case dies|date=26 September 2010|accessdate=4 March 2019|work=Daily Record|last=Findlay|first=Russell}}</ref> Langford had given police the description used to form the second composite drawing created of the suspect, which continues to remain the most significant clue as to the perpetrator's physical appearance. Despite Professor Wilson's assertion that Peter Tobin may have been Bible John, when Jean Langford discussed her sister's murderer many decades later, she dismissed this theory, stating emphatically that Tobin had not been the man with whom she had shared a taxi on the night of her sister's murder.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Whelan|first1=Michael|title=Bible John - Unresolved|url=https://unresolved.me/bible-john/|website=unresolved.me|accessdate=11 July 2018|date=21 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Media ==\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS LIKE SOUTH PARK OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n=== Books ===\n* {{Cite book|last= Harrison|first= Paul|title= Dancing with the Devil: The Bible John Murders|year= 2013|publisher= Vertical Editions|location= Skipton|isbn= 978-1-904-09173-8}}.\n* {{Cite book|last=Malloy|first=Andrew D.|title=Bible John - Closure|year= 2011|publisher= Pneuma Springs Publishing|location= Kent|isbn= 978-1-907-72816-7}}.\n* {{cite book| last = Stoddart| first = Charles| title = Bible John: Search for a Sadist|year = 1980| publisher = Paul Harris Publishing | location = Edinburgh| isbn = 978-0-904-50589-4}}.\n* {{cite book| last1 = Wilson| first1 = David| last2 = Harrison| first2 = Paul| title = The Lost British Serial Killer| year = 2010| publisher = Brown Book Group Limited | location = London| isbn = 978-0-751-54232-5}}\n\n=== Television ===\n* The [[BBC]] has broadcast a 30-minute documentary focusing upon the murders committed by Bible John. Presented by Hugh Cochrane, this episode was screened on 18 September 1970, and concluded with a direct quote from [[Jeremiah]], Chapter 23, Verse 24, appealing to the perpetrator to hand himself in to the police: 'Can any hide himself in secret places, that I shall not see him? saith the Lord?{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=204}}\n* [[STV (TV channel)|STV]] have broadcast a 45-minute documentary focusing upon the murders committed by Bible John. This documentary, titled ''In Search of Bible John'', was initially broadcast in 2011, and explores the possibility Peter Tobin may have been the perpetrator of the three murders.\n* The case of Bible John featured in a December 2005 episode of ''[[Unsolved (UK TV programme)|Unsolved]].'' Narrated by [[Alex Norton]], the program primarily focuses on the death of the final victim, Helen Puttock, and includes interviews with Puttock's husband.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taggart actor steps in to try to solve Bible John murder riddle |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/taggart-actor-steps-in-to-try-to-solve-bible-john-murder-riddle-1-1096054/amp |accessdate=27 January 2019 |work=The Scotsman |date=17 September 2005}}</ref>\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS LIKE THE SIMPSONS OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Capital punishment in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n* [[List of serial killers by number of victims|List of murderers by number of victims]]\n{{col-break}}\n* [[List of serial killers by country]]\n* [[Unsolved murders in the United Kingdom]]\n{{col-end}}\n{{Portal bar|1960s|Law|Scotland|United Kingdom}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Cited works and further reading==\n* {{Cite book|last= Cawthorne|first= Nigel|title=The Mammoth Book of Killers at Large|year= 2007|publisher=Constable & Robinson Ltd|location= London|isbn= 978-1-845-29631-5}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Harrison|first= Paul|title=Dancing with the Devil: The Bible John Murders|year= 2013|publisher= Vertical Editions|location= Skipton|isbn= 978-1-904-09173-8}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Lane|first= Brian|last2= Gregg|first2= Wilfred|title= The Encyclopedia Of Serial Killers|origyear= 1992|year= 1995|publisher= Berkley Books|location= New York City|isbn= 0-425-15213-8|ref= harv|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofse00lane}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Lloyd|first= Georgina|title= One Was Not Enough: True Stories of Multiple Murderers|year= 1986|publisher= Bantam Books|location= London|isbn= 978-0-553-17605-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Malloy|first=Andrew D.|title=Bible John - Closure|year= 2011|publisher= Pneuma Springs Publishing|location= Kent|isbn= 978-1-907-72816-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Newton| first = Michael| title = The Encyclopedia of Unsolved Crimes|year = 2004| publisher = Facts on File | location = New York| isbn = 978-0-816-07818-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Stoddart| first = Charles| title = Bible John: Search for a Sadist|year = 1980| publisher = Paul Harris Publishing | location = Edinburgh| isbn = 978-0-904-50589-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Whittington-Egan| first = Molly| title = Scottish Murder Stories|year = 1998| publisher = Neil Wilson Publishing Ltd.| location = Glasgow| isbn = 978-1-906-47647-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Whittington-Egan|first= Richard|last2= Whittington-Egan|first2= Molly|title= The Murder Almanac|year= 1992|publisher= Neil Wilson Publishing Ltd.|location= Glasgow|isbn= 978-1-897-78404-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last1 = Wilson| first1 = Colin| last2 = Wilson| first2 = Damon| last3 = Wilson| first3 = Rowan| title = World Famous Murders| year = 1993| publisher = Parragon Publishing| location = London| isbn = 978-0-752-50122-2|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* 2000 ''[[BBC News]]'' account detailing [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/971771.stm contemporary developments] pertaining to leads in the Bible John inquiry\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051104053053/http://www.crimelibrary.com/serial_killers/unsolved/bible_john/index.html Bible John] at Court TV's ''Crime Library''\n* [https://www.historicmysteries.com/bible-john/ Bible John] at ''historicmysteries.com''\n* [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=GGgVawPscysC&dat=19691101&printsec=frontpage&hl=en Contemporary edition] of ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Glasgow Herald]]'', focusing upon the discovery of the body of Helen Puttock (p.&nbsp;1)\n* [https://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/news/history/bible-john-killing-glasgow-barrowlands-11533797 ''glasgowlive.co.uk''] article pertaining to Bible John\n* International Crime Writing Festival [https://bloodyscotland.com/events/who-was-bible-john/ article focusing upon the Bible John murders]\n* [https://www.trace-evidence.com/008/ ''The Bible John Murders''] at trace-evidence.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John, Bible}}\n[[Category:1968 murders in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1969 murders in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1960s in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:1968 in Scotland]]\n[[Category:1969 in Scotland]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish criminals]]\n[[Category:History of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Murder in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Murder in Scotland]]\n[[Category:People associated with Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish rapists]]\n[[Category:Scottish serial killers]]\n[[Category:Scottish sex offenders]]\n[[Category:Unidentified serial killers]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name=Bible John\n| image     = File:Bible_John_1969_Police_Composite_Sketch.jpg\n| caption   = 1969 [[Facial composite|composite drawing]] of ''Bible John''\n| alt       = Composite drawing of Bible John, created with the assistance of the sister of his last known victim, Helen Puttock\n| victims= 3 \n| locations = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| beginyear= 22 February 1968\n| endyear= 31 October 1969\n| apprehended= Unapprehended \n}}\n\n'''Bible John''' is an unidentified [[serial killer]] who is believed to have murdered three young women between 1968 and 1969 in [[Glasgow]], Scotland.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lister|first=David Brown, Sean O\u2019Neill and David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bible-john-the-sanctimonious-dancehall-killer-who-vanished-gmfgpwb7j6d|title=\u2018Bible John\u2019 \u2013 the sanctimonious dancehall killer who vanished|access-date=2020-03-07|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nEach of the victims of Bible John were young [[brunette]] women between the ages of 25 and 32, and all had met their murderer at the [[Barrowland Ballroom]]: a [[dance hall]] and [[music venue]] in the city. The perpetrator has never been identified and the case remains both unsolved and also one of the most extensive [[manhunt (law enforcement)|manhunts]] in Scottish criminal history.<ref>{{cite book|title=Glasgow Almanac: An A-Z of the City and its People|isbn=978-1-906-47625-0|page=112|location=Glasgow|publisher=Neil Wilson Publishing|year=2011|first=Stephen|last=Terry}}</ref>\n\nThe murders committed by Bible John would prove to be the first time in Scotland in which the [[Clerk of the Crown in Chancery|Crown Office]] authorised the publication of a [[facial composite|composite drawing]] of an individual suspected of murder for public viewing.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|Whittington-Egan|1992|p=18}}\n\nThis unidentified serial killer became known as \"Bible John\" due to his having repeatedly quoted from the [[Christian Bible|Bible]] and to have condemned any form of [[adultery]] while in the company of his final victim.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=21}} The known movements and ''[[modus operandi]]'' of convicted serial killer and rapist [[Peter Tobin]] have given rise to suspicions that he may be Bible John.\n\n==First murders==\n===Patricia Docker===\nOn 23 February 1968, the naked body of a 25-year-old [[auxiliary nurse]] named Patricia Docker was found in the doorway of a lock-up garage by a man on his way to work in [[Battlefield, Glasgow|Battlefield, South Glasgow]].<ref name=\"Skelton\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=v-NAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3KYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1709,2603592&dq|title=20 years on, the mystery of Bible John still haunts a city|newspaper=[[Evening Times]]|last=Skelton|first=Douglas|date=10 February 1989|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> The location of her body was only yards from her home in Langside Place. Her body bore evidence of extensive [[blunt force trauma]]\u2014particularly to the face and head.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|Whittington-Egan|1992|p=17}} She had been [[strangulation|strangled]] to death with a strong [[strangling#Ligature strangulation|ligature]], possibly a belt.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=52}} Patricia's handbag, watch, and clothes were missing from the [[crime scene]]. Her clothing was never found,<ref name=\"MacDougall\"/> although her handbag was later recovered from the [[River Cart]] by an [[underwater search and recovery|underwater search unit]],{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=53}} whereas her watch was recovered from a pool of water close to the scene of her murder.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\">''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 34. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref>\n\nExtensive door-to-door inquiries in the area produced a witness who recalled hearing a female scream, \"Leave me alone!\" the previous evening. Little [[smoking gun|hard evidence]] was discovered at the crime scene. Nonetheless, an ambulanceman who retrieved the body informed investigators the victim had been a nurse who worked at Mearnskirk Hospital in nearby [[Renfrewshire]].<ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> Consequently, the victim was formally identified by her father the following day.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=191}}\n\nPatricia was a married mother of one but [[family estrangement|estranged]] from her husband.<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\">{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> The night of her murder, she informed her parents she would spend the evening dancing at the Majestic Ballroom in nearby Hope Street, although for unknown reasons, she had chosen to spend the majority of the evening at the Barrowland Ballroom, likely to attend the over-25s night which the Barrowland hosted each Thursday.<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\">{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref> When she failed to return home that evening, her parents assumed she had spent the night with a friend.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Petrie|first1=Ewan|title=Bible John: Remembering Notorious Serial Killer's Victims|url=https://stv.tv/news/features/1408716-bible-john-victims-of-notorious-glasgow-serial-killer/|publisher=STV|accessdate=23 July 2018|date=23 February 2018}}</ref> Police inquiries would only determine several days later<ref>{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> that in the late evening, Patricia had left the Majestic Ballroom to attend the Barrowland,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/DANCING+WITH+DEATH%3B+CHASING+KILLERS%3A+RETIRED+COP+JOE+JACKSON+ON+THE...-a0186026767|title=Dancing With Death; Chasing Killers|publisher=[[The Free Library]]|website=Daily Record|last=Jackson|first=Joe|date=1 October 2008|accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref> where she had likely encountered her killer.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/><ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[autopsy|postmortem]] conducted by Gilbert Forbes at the [[University of Glasgow Medical School]] confirmed that the cause of death had been strangulation, and that Patricia's body bore no clear evidence of [[sexual assault]].{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=192}}<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\"/> Furthermore, the stage of [[rigor mortis]] upon her body at the time of discovery indicated she had likely died shortly after she had left the Barrowland Ballroom.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=52}} Investigators surmised the perpetrator had likely grabbed Patricia before repeatedly punching her and kicking her in the face as she twice screamed \"Leave me alone!\"<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\"/> He had then proceeded to [[rape]] Patricia before strangling her to death, and leaving her naked body, with nothing but one shoe nearby, close to the doorway of the lock-up garage at Carmichael Place.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\"/>\n\n===Jemima McDonald===\nOn Saturday, 16 August 1969, a 32-year-old mother of three named Jemima McDonald also opted to attend the Barrowland Ballroom to spend the evening dancing. Jemima was a regular attendee of the Barrowland, and as per family custom, her sister, Margaret O'Brien, took care of her three children as Jemima attended the Barrowland.<ref>''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 35. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref> As midnight approached, Jemima was seen by several people in the company of a young, well-dressed and well-spoken man of slim build aged between 25 and 35 and between {{nowrap|6 ft 0 in}} and {{nowrap|6 ft 2 in}} ({{convert|72|and|74|in|cm|disp=out}}) in height.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=195}} This individual had short, dark brown hair with fair streaks,{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=253}} likely spoke with a distinctive [[Glasgow accent|Glaswegian accent]], and occasionally inserted brief Biblical quotations into his conversation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nJemima was seen leaving the Barrowland shortly after midnight on 17 August in the company of this individual, and was last seen walking towards either Main Street or Landressy Street, in the direction of her home, at approximately 12:40&nbsp;a.m.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=195}} The following day, Jemima's sister, Margaret, became concerned when her sister failed to return home. Later the same day, she began hearing local rumours that young children had been seen leaving a derelict [[tenement]] building in MacKeith Street discussing a body in the premises.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/> By the Monday morning, Margaret was so concerned that she herself, fearing the worst, walked into the old building. There she discovered her own sister's extensively battered body lying face down, with her shoes and stockings lying beside her.\n\nA postmortem concluded Jemima had been raped and extensively beaten, particularly about the face,<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\"/> before she had been strangled to death with one of her own stockings. Her murder had occurred approximately 30 hours before her body had been discovered.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\">{{cite news|title=Bible John Killer may be Unmasked After 30 Years |date=15 October 2000 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1370421/Bible-John-killer-may-be-unmasked-after-30-years.html |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=19 June 2018}}</ref> Unlike Patricia Docker, the body of Jemima McDonald was fully clothed,<ref name=\"Skelton\"/> although her underclothing had been torn, and like Patricia, Jemima had been [[menstruation|menstruating]] at the time of her death.<ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nPolice inquiries into Jemima's movements on the night of her murder produced several [[Eyewitness memory|eyewitness]]es who were able to accurately describe the man with whom Jemima had been in the company of at the Barrowland. Door-to-door inquiries on MacKieth Street also produced a woman who remembered hearing female screams on the evening of Jemima's murder, although this individual could not recall the precise time. Consequently, police considered this information of little use to their inquiry.\n\n==Initial investigation==\nAlthough the [[City of Glasgow Police]] noted several striking similarities between the murders of Patricia Docker and Jemima McDonald, including that both women had attended the Barrowland Ballroom on the evening of their murder, been beaten before being strangled to death with a ligature, were menstruating, and had their handbags had been taken from the crime scene. Initially, both murders were not considered to be the work of the same perpetrator.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=194}}\n\nDespite extensive public appeals, the investigation into the murder of Patricia Docker in 1968 had quickly become a [[cold case]]. Police had little information, owing to both a lack of [[witness]]es and hard evidence.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=193}} The investigation had also been severely hindered by  investigators discovering three days after her death that Patricia had attended the Barrowland Ballroom on the evening of her murder.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/i-think-bible-john-already-11923937|title=False Information Doomed Bible John Probe from the Start|website=The Daily Record|last=Silvester|first=Norman|date=28 January 2018|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/DANCING+WITH+DEATH%3B+CHASING+KILLERS%3A+RETIRED+COP+JOE+JACKSON+ON+THE...-a0186026767|title=Dancing With Death: Chasing Killers|publisher=[[The Free Library]]|website=Daily Record|last=Jackson|first=Joe|date=1 October 2008|accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref> Eighteen months later, following the discovery of Jemima McDonald, police became aware of remarkable similarities to the murder of Patricia Docker. Although police did not conclusively link both murders to the same perpetrator, they could not completely discount this theory. In addition, police were certain the perpetrator or perpetrators held a high degree of local geographical knowledge. However, they may have been a stranger to the district, as none of the eyewitnesses with whom investigators conversed directly knew the individual(s) seen in the company of either woman prior to her murder.<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\"/>\n[[File:Barrowlands, Glasgow - geograph.org.uk - 663608.jpg|thumb|right|The Barrowland Ballroom, seen here in 2011. Each of the women murdered are believed to have encountered Bible John at this dance hall]]\n\nFor the first time in a Scottish murder hunt, a [[facial composite|composite drawing]] of the man with whom Jemima had last been seen alive was given to the press, being widely distributed via both newspapers and upon television throughout Scotland in efforts to identify the suspect.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/> Moreover, both male and female [[Undercover operation|undercover police officers]] performed discreet surveillance at the Barrowland Ballroom in efforts to identify the suspect.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=196}} Police surveillance at the Barrowland Ballroom would be terminated in late October 1969 due to the initiative both failing to produce any suspects. Detectives were also blamed by proprietors for a sharp decrease in attendance figures.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|pp=196-197}}\n\n===Helen Puttock===\nOn 31 October 1969, a man walking his dog discovered the body of 29-year-old Helen Puttock behind a [[tenement]] in the [[Scotstoun]] district of Glasgow. Her body was found beside a drainpipe in the back garden of her Earl Street flat. She had been stripped partially naked, extensively beaten about the face before being raped, then strangled to death with one of her own stockings.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=201}} The contents of her handbag had been scattered close to her body, although the handbag itself was missing from the crime scene. Grass and weed stains upon the soles of Helen's feet and shoes indicated that she had engaged in a ferocious struggle with her killer. She had evidently at one point attempted to scale a nearby railway embankment. Her body also bore a deep [[forensic dentistry|bite mark]] on her upper right thigh.<ref name=\"Skelton2\"/> Her murderer had placed her [[sanitary towel]] beneath her left arm. As had been the case with the two previous victims, Helen had been menstruating at the time of her murder.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|Whittington-Egan|1992|p=17}}\n\nThe evening prior to her murder, Helen and her sister, Jean Langford, had been to the Barrowland Ballroom, where both had become acquainted with men named John. One of these individuals had said he worked as a [[slater]] who resided in [[Castlemilk]],{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}} while the other individual had been a well-spoken man who did not disclose where he actually lived. After being in the company of these two individuals for in excess of an hour, all four left the Barrowland to head home. The individual named John who had been Jean's dance partner walked to [[George Square]] to board a bus, while Jean, Helen, and the individual who had been Helen's dance partner hailed a taxi.<ref name=\"Hamilton\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/legendary-glasgow-detective-tells-believes-1052300|title=Legendary Glasgow detective tells why he believes serial killer Peter Tobin was notorious murderer Bible John|work=Daily Record|last=Hamilton|first=Tom|date=5 March 2010|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> The trio set off from [[Glasgow Cross]], making a 20-minute westward journey toward Jean's [[Knightswood]] residence. There she exited the taxi, which then continued towards Helen's Scotstoun residence. During conversations between the trio upon this journey, most of the crucial information pertaining to the killer's [[psychological profiling|psychological profile]] became apparent.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/>\n\nJean later informed detectives{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=53}} that her sister's companion had been a [[teetotalism|teetotal]] individual{{sfn|Newton|2004|p=42}} who repeatedly quoted from the [[Old Testament]] stories of [[Moses]] during the time she and her sister had conversed with him in the taxi; having previously referred to the Barrowland as an \"[[adultery|adulterous]] den of [[wikt:iniquity|iniquity]]\", and of his disapproval of married women visiting the premises as the quartet had retrieved their coats at the end of the evening.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Detective Still Convinced Bible John is Behind Bars |date=23 February 2018 |url=https://stv.tv/news/features/1408962-former-detective-still-convinced-bible-john-is-behind-bars/ |work=STV News |accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref> She had herself alighted the taxi at Kelso Street, before viewing the taxi turn towards Earl Street.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 36\">''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 36. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref> {{refn|group=n|Helen Puttock had been married at the time of her murder, although she did not disclose this fact to her murderer.}}{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=53}}\n\n==Suspect==\nThe suspect was described by Helen's sister Jean as being a tall, slim and well-dressed young man with reddish or fair hair rounded neatly at the back,{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=199}} aged between 25 and 30, and approximately {{convert|5|ft|10|in|m}} in height. This individual had given his name as either \"John Templeton\", \"John Sempleson\", or \"John Emerson\", and he had been a polite and well-spoken individual,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mountflorida.eveningtimes.co.uk/area/dark-days-and-dreadful-deeds-that-haunt-our-city.html|title=Dark days and dreadful deeds that haunt our city|work=Evening Times|date=7 June 2005|accessdate=26 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208143050/http://mountflorida.eveningtimes.co.uk/area/dark-days-and-dreadful-deeds-that-haunt-our-city.html|archivedate=8 February 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> having frequently quoted from the Old Testament during the trio's taxi ride home,<ref name=Findlay/> although he had indicated he was neither a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] nor [[Protestantism|Protestant]] individual.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 36\"/> Jean would also state to investigators it had become increasingly clear to her as the trio had ridden in the taxi that this individual had considered her presence in the vehicle to be an inconvenience.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=200}} At one point during this ride, this individual had explained to the women the reason he refrained from consuming alcohol was due to his being conditioned so by a strict parental attitude, before adding: \"I don't drink at [[Hogmanay]]; I pray.\" He had also alluded to his father's belief that dance halls were \"dens of iniquity\", with any married woman who frequented these premises being \"adulterous\" by nature.<ref name=\"Hamilton\"/>{{refn|group=n|The suspect's repeatedly referencing quotes from the Old Testament led to ''[[Evening Times]]'' journalist John Quinn naming the unknown murderer \"Bible John\".{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}}}}\n\nAlthough Jean Langford had informed detectives that the man accompanying Helen had been a \"slim, tall\" individual who had been dressed in a well-cut brown ''Reid and Taylor'' brand suit{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=54}} who smoked ''[[Embassy (cigarette)|Embassy]]'' cigarettes,<ref name=\"Bible John p. 36\"/> she also recalled this individual mentioning that he had been familiar with several drinking premises in the [[Yoker]] district of Glasgow,{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}} and that he had at one stage worked in a laboratory.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=204}} She would also recall distinct facial features of this man, such as his having overlapping front teeth. (Bouncers at the Barrowland Ballroom dismissed much of this description, claiming that the man in Helen's company had been a short and well-spoken individual with black hair.)<ref name=\"DR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/crime-professor-quizzes-detective-centre-1077102|title=Crime professor quizzes detective at centre of search for Bible John|work=Daily Record|date=28 November 2010|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Police initially considered the description provided by the bouncers to be a more reliable description than that provided by Jean Langford, as she had allegedly been [[alcohol intoxication|intoxicated]] at the time she and her sister had left the Barrowland Ballroom on the night of Helen's murder. Furthermore, police had reason to believe that the killer had not been quoting directly from the Bible, but had simply been referring to it. However, Jean strongly attested to her having been [[sobriety|sober]] at the time she had left the Barrowland, and a bouncer at these premises would later state that staff who worked at the premises were not \"good with faces\".}}\n\nThe last possible sighting of the suspect was made by both the driver and [[Bus conductor|conductor]] upon a night service bus, who noticed a young man matching Jean's description alighting a bus at the junction of Dumbarton Road and Gray Street at approximately 2:00&nbsp;a.m. on 31 October.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}} He was in a notably disheveled state, with mud stains on his jacket and a livid red mark on his cheek just beneath one eye. Both witnesses also recalled his repeatedly tucking a short cuff of one sleeve into his jacket sleeve (a man's cuff link had been found alongside the body of Helen Puttock).<ref>''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 37. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref> This individual was last seen walking towards the public ferry to cross the [[River Clyde]] to the south side of the city.<ref name=\"Wier\"/>\n\n===Link to series===\nThe murder of Helen Puttock held remarkable similarities to the two previous murders, further raising suspicions that all three murders had been committed by the same individual. All of the victims had been mothers of at least one child and had met her murderer at the Barrowland Ballroom. The handbag of each woman was missing. Each victim had been strangled to death; and at least two of these women had been raped prior to her murder.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=21}} In addition, the three women had been escorted home by her killer and murdered within yards of their doorstep, and all had been menstruating at the time of her death.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\"/> Each had had her sanitary towel or [[tampon]] placed upon, beneath, or near her body,<ref name=\"Skelton2\"/>{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|pp=202-203}} leading to speculation the women had been murdered due to their refusing to engage in intercourse with their murderer due to their periods.<ref>{{cite news|title=Was Peter Tobin Bible John? |date=6 December 2008 |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/was-peter-tobin-bible-john-1-1302021 |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n{{quote box\n| quote = \"It is quite incredible that this man has eluded us. I am positive this man comes from Glasgow or nearby. He is between 25 and 30, between {{nowrap|5 ft 10 in}} and {{nowrap|6 ft}} tall, has light red hair, good features, blue-grey eyes and a smart modern appearance. I do not think he is a very religious man, but just has a normal intelligent working knowledge of the Bible which he likes to air ... there must be many people who know someone who looks like this artist's impression.\"\n| source = Detective Superintendent Joe Beattie, describing the prime suspect in the Bible John murders (1972).<ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n| width = 35em\n}}\n\n==Ongoing investigation==\nWithin hours of the discovery of the body of Helen Puttock, an additional composite drawing of the suspect was created using the detailed description provided by her sister;{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=203}} this composite drawing would rapidly become one of the most famous facial composites in Scotland.<ref name=\"express\">{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/356076/I-am-sure-the-famous-portrait-of-Bible-John-shows-the-wrong-man|title=I am sure the famous portrait of Bible John shows the wrong man|work=[[Daily Express]]|last=Borland|first=Ben|date=4 November 2012|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|At the headquarters of the [[City of Glasgow Police]], Jean Langford happened to view an earlier [[facial composite|composite drawing]] created relating to the chief suspect in the murder of Jemima McDonald. Upon viewing this Identikit, Langford exclaimed, \"That man looks just like him!\"{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=203}}}} Detective Superintendent Joe Beattie asked the public to closely study this composite drawing, should it resemble anyone they knew. Due to the suspect's hair being unfashionably short for the era, over 450 hairdressers in and around Glasgow were shown the updated composite drawing of the suspect, and all dentists in and around Glasgow were asked to examine their records to determine whether they held records of a male patient with overlapping [[incisor]]s and a missing tooth in the upper right jaw. Both lines of inquiry would prove fruitless.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=54}}\n\nMore than 100 detectives were assigned to work full-time on the case, and 50,000 [[witness statement]]s would be taken in subsequent door-to-door inquiries.<ref name=\"Skelton2\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=OhQ-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=HEoMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6523,4393868&dq|title=Bible John: Final Part of a Harrowing Tale of Terror|work=Evening Times|last=Skelton|first=Douglas|date=18 February 1989|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The True Story of Bible John and the Barrowland Killings |date=22 February 2018 |url=https://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/news/history/bible-john-killing-glasgow-barrowlands-11533797 |work=Glasgow Live |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref> Ultimately, more than 5,000 potential suspects would be quizzed in relation to the murders in the first year of the inquiry alone, and Jean Langford would be required to attend over 300 [[police lineup|identity parades]],{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=204}} although she was adamant none of the individuals required to participate in these identity parades had been the individual with whom she had last seen her sister, and all would be cleared of any involvement.<ref name=\"Skelton2\"/> Fearing that the perpetrator would strike again, a team of 16 detectives were instructed to mingle with dancers at all dance halls in Glasgow. In particular, these detectives frequented the Barrowland on Thursday and Saturday nights at the over-25s events, where each victim was presumed to have met her murderer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Two of the three victims murdered by Bible John had been killed on a Thursday, and one on a Saturday.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=190}}}}\n\nDespite the extensive manhunt, no further developments would arise and the investigation into the three murders gradually became cold, with many individuals assigned to the case opining that the perpetrator had either died, been jailed for an unrelated offense, had been incarcerated at a mental hospital, or that senior police officers had known his actual identity, but had been unable to prove he had committed the murders.<ref name=\"MacDougall\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Fwc-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=m0kMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4523,2561436&dq|title=Dark world of a dance hall killer|newspaper=Evening Times|last=MacDougall|first=Carl|date=9 October 1987|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> Others speculated that he may have simply moved away from the Glasgow district, or murdered whenever in the vicinity;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/bible-john-may-be-in-england-1.213923|title=Bible John may be in England|work=[[The Herald (Scotland)|The Herald]]|date=16 October 2000|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> this possibility prompted police to circulate multiple copies of the composite drawing at all [[British Army]], [[Royal Navy|Navy]] and [[Royal Air Force|Air Force]] bases in the United Kingdom, Europe, and the [[Middle East|Middle]] and [[Far East]], although this potential line of inquiry also failed to produce any significant leads.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Potential suspects==\n===\"John White\"===\nOne former Detective Chief Inspector, Les Brown (then working with the [[Strathclyde Police]]), has supplied current investigators with details of the arrest of a suspect conducted in 1969 which he believes was of an extremely likely perpetrator, but which was dismissed simply because this individual did not have notably overlapping front teeth.\n\nAccording to Les Brown, the man's arguing with a young woman in the Barrowland Ballroom immediately prior to his arrest had greatly raised investigators' concerns, yet\u2014despite the fact the suspect had closely resembled the facial composite and had subsequently supplied police with a false name and address before revealing his true name and address in [[Gorbals|the Gorbals]]\u2014was simply released. According to Brown, the simple fact of this particular suspect not having notably overlapping front teeth - despite one police sergeant's acknowledgement of his being the best suspect yet - was sufficient enough for ordering his release.<ref name=\"Bible John Police Get New Informati\">{{cite news|title=Bible John Police Get New Information on Serial Killer's Identity |date=23 October 2005 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12472387.Bible_John_police_get_new_information_on_serial_killer_apos_s_identity/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral years later, Brown extensively conversed with a detective who had taken the same individual to a hospital after arresting him outside the Barrowland Ballroom at the time of the murders. Although the suspect had needed several stitches in his head following an altercation, as soon as his handcuffs had been released, he escaped from the hospital. At the time of this incident, this individual had also falsely given his name to medical personnel as John White.\n\nIn addition to this basic circumstantial evidence, the \"whole demeanour\" of this individual had led Les Brown and several of his colleagues to believe this individual may have been the perpetrator.<ref name=\"Bible John Police Get New Informati\"/>\n\n===John Irvine McInnes===\nIn 1996, Strathclyde Police [[Burial#Exhumation|exhumed]] the body of John Irvine McInnes from a graveyard in [[Stonehouse, South Lanarkshire]]. McInnes, who had served in the [[Scots Guards]], had committed [[suicide]] in 1980 at the age of 41, having severed the [[brachial artery]] in his upper arm. He had been the cousin of one of the original suspects in the series of murders.<ref name=\"Bizarre suicide of Bible John\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Bizarre+suicide+of+Bible+John.-a061271527|title=Bizarre suicide of Bible John|publisher=The Free Library|website=Daily Record|date=30 January 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> A [[Genetic testing|DNA sample]] was taken from McInnes's body for comparison with [[semen analysis|semen samples]] discovered upon the stockings with which victim Helen Puttock had been strangled.<ref name=\"Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Seria\">{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12036852.DNA_tests_clear_Bible_John_suspect/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|According to a contemporary [[psychiatrist]]'s report, the unusual method of suicide chosen by McInnes was akin to [[psychopathy]], leading to suggestions McInnes may have opted to take his own life in search of the \"ultimate thrill\".<ref name=\"Bizarre suicide of Bible John\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Bizarre+suicide+of+Bible+John.-a061271527|title=Bizarre suicide of Bible John|publisher=The Free Library|website=Daily Record|date=30 January 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> }}\n\nThe results of the testing conducted proved inconclusive, with then-[[Lord Advocate]] [[James Mackay, Baron Mackay of Clashfern|Lord Mackay]] stating [[Burden of proof (law)|insufficient evidence]]<ref name=\"Men give DNA in Bible John case\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/4089653.stm|title=Men give DNA in Bible John case|work=[[BBC News]]|date=12 December 2004|accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> existed to link McInnes with the murder of Helen Puttock.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/dna-tests-clear-bible-john-suspect-1.447304|title=DNA tests clear Bible John suspect|work=The Herald|last=Freeman|first=James|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> [[The Crown]] would officially clear McInnes of any involvement in the Bible John murders in July 1996.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12036852.DNA_tests_clear_Bible_John_suspect/|title=DNA Tests Clear Bible John Suspect|work=Herald Scotland|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Peter Tobin===\nSeveral [[Criminology|criminologists]] and investigators have suggested that convicted serial killer [[Peter Tobin]] may have been Bible John. Tobin was convicted in May 2007 of the 2006 murder of a [[Poles|Polish]] student named Angelika Kluk, who had been raped, beaten, then stabbed to death;<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|title=I'm Ashamed I Had Sex With Girl, Priest Tells Murder Trial |date=4 April 2007 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1547590/Im-ashamed-I-had-sex-with-girl-priest-tells-murder-trial.html |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref> he had relocated from [[Shettleston|Shettleston, Glasgow]]<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\"/> to England in 1969 after marrying his first wife, whom he had met at the Barrowland Ballroom the same year as the murders attributed to Bible John had ended.<ref name=\"Wier\">{{cite book|last=Wier|first=Nigel|year=2012|title=British Serial Killers|publisher=AuthorHouseUK|page=226}}</ref> Tobin would subsequently live in [[Brighton]] for 20 years from 1969,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/jul/12/peter-tobin-serial-killer-brighton-search|title=Peter Tobin's former homes searched in hunt for more victims|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Tran|first=Mark|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/scotland/article6968389.ece|title=Killer question|work=[[The Times]]|date=27 December 2009}}</ref> although from the late 1980s, he would alternately reside in either Scotland or the South of England.<ref name=\"Wilson2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/books/features/a-life-of-crime-professor-david-wilson-trying-to-understand-why-serial-killers-kill-1-816044|title=A life of crime: Professor David Wilson \u2013 trying to understand why serial killers kill|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=4 July 2010|accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|A former detective named Joe Jackson (who had investigated the ''Bible John'' murders in the 1960s) has stated that he suspected Tobin may be the perpetrator shortly after he was arrested for Kluk's murder in 2006, adding: \"When I saw his photograph, I thought, 'This is as near to Bible John as you are going to get. This looks a winner.' He fitted the bill in every way, and he had connections with religion.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/exclusive-cops-believe-peter-tobin-1000204|title=Exclusive: Cops believe Peter Tobin was Bible John|work=Daily Record|last=O'Hare|first=Paul|date=3 December 2008|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref>}}\n\nTobin had been in his mid-40s when he committed the 1991 murder of two teenage girls whose [[skeletonization|skeletonized]] bodies would subsequently be unearthed from the garden of his home in [[Margate, Kent]] in 2007. He would be convicted of these murders\u2014alongside that of Kluk\u2014between 2007 and 2009. Commencing serial murderous offences of an extremely calculated nature at such an age is unusual\u2014though not unheard of\u2014for a male. Furthermore, the fact that Tobin had attacked Kluk with such violence, then hidden her body before absconding to London prior to his subsequent arrest in addition to the abduction, restraining and concealment known to have been exhibited upon the two 1991 murder victims unearthed from the garden of his Margate home did not suggest the work of an amateur in any of these three cases.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/1823130|title=Expert convinced Tobin is Bible John says more murders likely|work=[[The Press and Journal (Scotland)|The Press and Journal]]|last=Lindsay|first=Morag|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nStriking contemporary visual similarities exist between Peter Tobin when aged in his 20s and the 1969 composite drawing of Bible John. In addition, all three of Tobin's former wives have given accounts of being repeatedly imprisoned, throttled, beaten and raped at his hands, and each has stated he had been driven to extreme physical violence by the female [[menstrual cycle]] (a factor long suspected by investigators as being the perpetrator's actual motive behind the murders).<ref name=\"Hamilton\"/> In addition, Tobin is known to have been a staunch [[Roman Catholic]] with strong religious views,<ref name=Wilson/> and the alias Bible John had given to Jean Langford and Helen Puttock in 1969 is similar to one of the [[pseudonym]]s known to have been regularly used by Tobin: John Semple.<ref name=\"Wilson2\"/>\n\nCriminologist [[David Wilson (criminologist)|David Wilson]] actively investigated Tobin's case for three years and strongly believes the available evidence supports his theory that Peter Tobin is Bible John.<ref name=Wilson/> He has stated that the moment he believed Tobin was Bible John occurred during Tobin's trial for the 1991 murder of 18-year-old Dinah McNicol, one of the women whose body had been unearthed from his Margate garden. The [[circumstantial evidence]] which Wilson uses to support this theory includes striking similarities between trial testimony from an acquaintance of Dinah's who had been in her company on the evening of her abduction and the conversation with Bible John that Jean Langford claimed to have had on the evening of her sister's murder; among the important points of overlap are both men mentioning they did not drink at Hogmanay and had a cousin who had once scored a [[hole-in-one]] in a golf match.<ref name=Wilson/> This information\u2014alongside other circumstantial evidence\u2014has led Professor Wilson to state: \"I didn't set out to prove Tobin was Bible John, but I would stake my professional reputation on it.\"<ref name=Wilson/><ref>{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Genetic testing|DNA testing]] has been used to clear several suspects, detectives believe obtaining a forensic link between Peter Tobin and any of the murder victims linked to Bible John is unlikely due to the deterioration of the physical samples owing to poor storage.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\n'''Operation Anagram'''\n\nAs a result of a police investigation named Operation Anagram, which was initiated in 2006 to trace the movements of Tobin throughout the decades and to determine his potential [[culpability]] in any other crimes, a woman informed investigators she had been raped by Tobin after she had met him at the Barrowland Ballroom in 1968, shortly after the first of the murders known to have been committed by Bible John.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10507524|title=Peter Tobin Crimewatch appeal gets 'massive' response|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=6 July 2010|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> Another woman informed investigators in 2010 that she had endured a threatening experience with Tobin at the Barrowland Ballroom, claiming that Tobin had introduced himself as Peter, before pestering her to go with him to a party in the city's Castlemilk area. When this woman viewed pictures of Tobin dating from the late 1960s and early 1970s, she stated: \"[He] was the man who came up to me so many years ago in [the] Barrowlands. I am 100 per cent certain [that] Tobin is Bible John.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/bible-john-asked-me-to-dance---1062823|title=Bible John asked me to dance \u2013 it was Peter Tobin, reveals terrified gran|work=Daily Record|last=Stewart|first=Stephen|date=27 June 2010|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nNo further murder victims killed in Scotland or elsewhere in the United Kingdom have ever been conclusively attributed to Bible John,{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|pp=207-208}} and the manhunt for this murderer was one of the most extensive manhunts in Scottish criminal history.<ref name=\"DR\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1370421/Bible-John-killer-may-be-unmasked-after-30-years.html|title=Bible John Killer May be Unmasked After 30 Years|work=The Telegraph|last=Booth|first=Jenny|date=15 October 2000|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> The murders of the three women remain unsolved, although the case remains open, with many investigators remaining certain that the perpetrator(s)<ref name=\"Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Seria\"/> of these crimes were highly likely to have been shielded by one or more individuals whom he had known.<ref>''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 38. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref>\n\nNo uniform consensus that the three killings were actually the work of the same person exists.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=205}} It has been claimed that the gap of 18 months between the first two killings is unusual for a serial killer, and that the later two murders may have either been copycat killings, or the sole two committed by the same perpetrator. Criticism has also been levelled against the police for potentially hampering their own investigation by prematurely jumping to the conclusion that all three murders had been committed by the same person.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jeffrey|first=Robert|year=2006|title=Crimes Past: Glasgow's Crimes of the Century|publisher=Black and White Publishing}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|[[David Wilson (criminologist)|Professor David Wilson]] has stated that a lapse of time approximating 18 months is not unusual between a serial killer's first and second murders.<ref name=Wilson>{{Cite news|title=Scots murderer Peter Tobin is Bible John, says UK serial killer expert|date=13 June 2010|work=Daily Record|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/scots-murderer-peter-tobin-is-bible-1061592|accessdate=4 March 2019|last=McPherson|first=Lynn}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930208&slug=1684320 |title=Serial Killer Says He'd Do It Again |last=Oak Kim |first=Myung |date=8 February 1993 |website=[[The Seattle Times]] |access-date=25 January 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125214432/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930208&slug=1684320 |archivedate=25 January 2017 }}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1983, an anonymous individual contacted [[Strathclyde Police]]. This individual claimed to conclusively know that his friend had been Bible John. According to this anonymous individual, both he and his friend had been raised in the [[Cranhill]] district of Glasgow, and both had frequented the Barrowland Ballroom in the 1960s. Allegedly, this individual had read an article in the ''[[Evening Times]]'' five years previously before suddenly realising his friend had been the perpetrator of the murders. The alleged suspect was traced living in [[Netherlands|the Netherlands]], married to a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] woman.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YNdAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=nqYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4240,1151385&dq|title=I know it is him|work=Evening Times|last=Hildrey|first=Mike|date=7 February 1983|accessdate=23 May 2013}}</ref> Nothing more was ever heard from the anonymous individual or the reputed suspect.\n\nIn 2004, police announced their intentions to [[genetic testing|genetically test]] a number of men in a further attempt to identify the perpetrator, with all individuals concerned being requested to submit [[Sampling (medicine)#Body fluid sampling|blood samples]].<ref name=\"Men give DNA in Bible John case\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/dna-tests-clear-bible-john-suspect-1.447304|title=DNA tests clear Bible John suspect|work=The Herald|last=Freeman|first=James|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> This endeavour followed the previous discovery of an 80% genetic match from the semen samples retrieved from the final crime scene attributed to Bible John with a DNA sample retrieved at the site of a minor crime committed two years earlier. The sample was enough of a match to lead officers to believe that the person who committed the offence was related to the killer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/DNA+BREAKTHROUGH%3A+POLICE+TRACE+FAMILY+OF+BIBLE+JOHN+SERIAL+KILLER.-a0126288448|title=DNA breakthrough: police trace family of Bible John serial killer|publisher=The Free Library|website=Sunday Mail|last=Lavery|first=Charles|date=19 December 2004|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe sole witness ever to have engaged in a lengthy conversation with Bible John, Jean Langford, died in September 2010 at the age of 74.<ref name=Findlay>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/2010/09/26/hunt-for-bible-john-comes-to-an-end-after-only-witness-in-case-dies-86908-22588146/|title=Hunt for Bible John comes to an end after only witness in case dies|date=26 September 2010|accessdate=4 March 2019|work=Daily Record|last=Findlay|first=Russell}}</ref> Langford had given police the description used to form the second composite drawing created of the suspect, which continues to remain the most significant clue as to the perpetrator's physical appearance. Despite Professor Wilson's assertion that Peter Tobin may have been Bible John, when Jean Langford discussed her sister's murderer many decades later, she dismissed this theory, stating emphatically that Tobin had not been the man with whom she had shared a taxi on the night of her sister's murder.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Whelan|first1=Michael|title=Bible John - Unresolved|url=https://unresolved.me/bible-john/|website=unresolved.me|accessdate=11 July 2018|date=21 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Media ==\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS LIKE SOUTH PARK OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n=== Books ===\n* {{Cite book|last= Harrison|first= Paul|title= Dancing with the Devil: The Bible John Murders|year= 2013|publisher= Vertical Editions|location= Skipton|isbn= 978-1-904-09173-8}}.\n* {{Cite book|last=Malloy|first=Andrew D.|title=Bible John - Closure|year= 2011|publisher= Pneuma Springs Publishing|location= Kent|isbn= 978-1-907-72816-7}}.\n* {{cite book| last = Stoddart| first = Charles| title = Bible John: Search for a Sadist|year = 1980| publisher = Paul Harris Publishing | location = Edinburgh| isbn = 978-0-904-50589-4}}.\n* {{cite book| last1 = Wilson| first1 = David| last2 = Harrison| first2 = Paul| title = The Lost British Serial Killer| year = 2010| publisher = Brown Book Group Limited | location = London| isbn = 978-0-751-54232-5}}\n\n=== Television ===\n* The [[BBC]] has broadcast a 30-minute documentary focusing upon the murders committed by Bible John. Presented by Hugh Cochrane, this episode was screened on 18 September 1970, and concluded with a direct quote from [[Jeremiah]], Chapter 23, Verse 24, appealing to the perpetrator to hand himself in to the police: 'Can any hide himself in secret places, that I shall not see him? saith the Lord?{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=204}}\n* [[STV (TV channel)|STV]] have broadcast a 45-minute documentary focusing upon the murders committed by Bible John. This documentary, titled ''In Search of Bible John'', was initially broadcast in 2011, and explores the possibility Peter Tobin may have been the perpetrator of the three murders.\n* The case of Bible John featured in a December 2005 episode of ''[[Unsolved (UK TV programme)|Unsolved]].'' Narrated by [[Alex Norton]], the program primarily focuses on the death of the final victim, Helen Puttock, and includes interviews with Puttock's husband.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taggart actor steps in to try to solve Bible John murder riddle |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/taggart-actor-steps-in-to-try-to-solve-bible-john-murder-riddle-1-1096054/amp |accessdate=27 January 2019 |work=The Scotsman |date=17 September 2005}}</ref>\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS LIKE THE SIMPSONS OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Capital punishment in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n* [[List of serial killers by number of victims|List of murderers by number of victims]]\n{{col-break}}\n* [[List of serial killers by country]]\n* [[Unsolved murders in the United Kingdom]]\n{{col-end}}\n{{Portal bar|1960s|Law|Scotland|United Kingdom}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Cited works and further reading==\n* {{Cite book|last= Cawthorne|first= Nigel|title=The Mammoth Book of Killers at Large|year= 2007|publisher=Constable & Robinson Ltd|location= London|isbn= 978-1-845-29631-5}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Harrison|first= Paul|title=Dancing with the Devil: The Bible John Murders|year= 2013|publisher= Vertical Editions|location= Skipton|isbn= 978-1-904-09173-8}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Lane|first= Brian|last2= Gregg|first2= Wilfred|title= The Encyclopedia Of Serial Killers|origyear= 1992|year= 1995|publisher= Berkley Books|location= New York City|isbn= 0-425-15213-8|ref= harv|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofse00lane}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Lloyd|first= Georgina|title= One Was Not Enough: True Stories of Multiple Murderers|year= 1986|publisher= Bantam Books|location= London|isbn= 978-0-553-17605-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Malloy|first=Andrew D.|title=Bible John - Closure|year= 2011|publisher= Pneuma Springs Publishing|location= Kent|isbn= 978-1-907-72816-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Newton| first = Michael| title = The Encyclopedia of Unsolved Crimes|year = 2004| publisher = Facts on File | location = New York| isbn = 978-0-816-07818-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Stoddart| first = Charles| title = Bible John: Search for a Sadist|year = 1980| publisher = Paul Harris Publishing | location = Edinburgh| isbn = 978-0-904-50589-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Whittington-Egan| first = Molly| title = Scottish Murder Stories|year = 1998| publisher = Neil Wilson Publishing Ltd.| location = Glasgow| isbn = 978-1-906-47647-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Whittington-Egan|first= Richard|last2= Whittington-Egan|first2= Molly|title= The Murder Almanac|year= 1992|publisher= Neil Wilson Publishing Ltd.|location= Glasgow|isbn= 978-1-897-78404-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last1 = Wilson| first1 = Colin| last2 = Wilson| first2 = Damon| last3 = Wilson| first3 = Rowan| title = World Famous Murders| year = 1993| publisher = Parragon Publishing| location = London| isbn = 978-0-752-50122-2|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* 2000 ''[[BBC News]]'' account detailing [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/971771.stm contemporary developments] pertaining to leads in the Bible John inquiry\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051104053053/http://www.crimelibrary.com/serial_killers/unsolved/bible_john/index.html Bible John] at Court TV's ''Crime Library''\n* [https://www.historicmysteries.com/bible-john/ Bible John] at ''historicmysteries.com''\n* [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=GGgVawPscysC&dat=19691101&printsec=frontpage&hl=en Contemporary edition] of ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Glasgow Herald]]'', focusing upon the discovery of the body of Helen Puttock (p.&nbsp;1)\n* [https://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/news/history/bible-john-killing-glasgow-barrowlands-11533797 ''glasgowlive.co.uk''] article pertaining to Bible John\n* International Crime Writing Festival [https://bloodyscotland.com/events/who-was-bible-john/ article focusing upon the Bible John murders]\n* [https://www.trace-evidence.com/008/ ''The Bible John Murders''] at trace-evidence.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John, Bible}}\n[[Category:1968 murders in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1969 murders in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1960s in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:1968 in Scotland]]\n[[Category:1969 in Scotland]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish criminals]]\n[[Category:History of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Murder in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Murder in Scotland]]\n[[Category:People associated with Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish rapists]]\n[[Category:Scottish serial killers]]\n[[Category:Scottish sex offenders]]\n[[Category:Unidentified serial killers]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Kieronoldham", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInitial investigation:Adj.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bible_John"}
